INSERT INTO `gita` (`id`, `chapter_number`, `chapter_name`, `verse_number`, `verse`, `translation`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 1, 'धृतराष्ट्र उवाच |\nधर्मक्षेत्रे कुरुक्षेत्रे समवेता युयुत्सवः |\nमामकाः पाण्डवाश्चैव किमकुर्वत सञ्जय || 1 ||', 'Dhritarashtra said: O Sanjaya, what did my sons and the sons of Pandu do when they assembled on the holy field of Kurukshetra, eager for battle?'),
(2, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 2, 'सञ्जय उवाच |\nदृष्ट्वा तु पाण्डवानीकं व्यूढं दुर्योधनस्तदा |\nआचार्यमुपसंगम्य राजा वचनमब्रवीत् || 2 ||', 'Sanjaya said: O King, after observing the Pandava army arranged in military formation, King Duryodhana approached his teacher Dronacharya and said the following words.'),
(3, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 3, 'पश्यैतां पाण्डुपुत्राणामाचार्य महतीं चमूम् |\nव्यूढां द्रुपदपुत्रेण तव शिष्येण धीमता || 3 ||', 'O teacher, behold this mighty army of the sons of Pandu, organized by your intelligent disciple, the son of Drupada.'),
(4, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 4, 'अत्र शूरा महेष्वासा भीमार्जुनसमा युधि |\nयुयुधानो विराटश्च द्रुपदश्च महारथः || 4 ||', 'Here in this army are many heroic bowmen equal in fighting to Bhima and Arjuna; there are also great fighters like Yuyudhana, Virata, and Drupada.'),
(5, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 5, 'धृष्टकेतुश्चेकितानः काशिराजश्च वीर्यवान् |\nपुरुजित्कुन्तिभोजश्च शैब्यश्च नरपुङ्गवः || 5 ||', 'There are also great, heroic, and mighty warriors like Dhrishtaketu, Chekitana, the valorous King of Kashi, Purujit, Kuntibhoja, and Shaibya.'),
(6, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 6, 'युधामन्युश्च विक्रान्त उत्तमौजाश्च वीर्यवान् |\nसौभद्रो द्रौपदेयाश्च सर्व एव महारथाः || 6 ||', 'There are the powerful Yudhamanyu, the valiant Uttamauja, the son of Subhadra, and the sons of Draupadi. All of them are great warriors.'),
(7, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 7, 'अस्माकं तु विशिष्टा ये तान्निबोध द्विजोत्तम |\nनायका मम सैन्यस्य संज्ञार्थं तान्ब्रवीमि ते || 7 ||', 'O best of Brahmins, let me now tell you about the prominent leaders of my army, who are especially qualified to lead.'),
(8, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 8, 'भवान्भीष्मश्च कर्णश्च कृपश्च समितिंजयः |\nअश्वत्थामा विकर्णश्च सौमदत्तिस्तथैव च || 8 ||', 'There are personalities like yourself, Bhishma, Karna, Kripa, Ashvatthama, Vikarna, and the son of Somadatta, who are always victorious in battle.'),
(9, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 9, 'अन्ये च बहवः शूरा मदर्थे त्यक्तजीविताः |\nनानाशस्त्रप्रहरणाः सर्वे युद्धविशारदाः || 9 ||', 'There are many other heroes, all of whom are determined to lay down their lives for my sake. They are all skilled in the art of warfare and are equipped with various weapons.'),
(10, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 10, 'अपर्याप्तं तदस्माकं बलं भीष्माभिरक्षितम् |\nपर्याप्तं त्विदमेतेषां बलं भीमाभिरक्षितम् || 10 ||', 'The strength of our army, protected by Bhishma, is unlimited, while the strength of the Pandavas, carefully protected by Bhima, is limited.'),
(11, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 11, 'अयनेषु च सर्वेषु यथाभागमवस्थिताः |\nभीष्ममेवाभिरक्षन्तु भवन्तः सर्व एव हि || 11 ||', 'Therefore, all of you must give full support to Bhishma, as you stand at your respective strategic points in the formations of the army.'),
(12, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 12, 'तस्य सञ्जनयन्हर्षं कुरुवृद्धः पितामहः |\nसिंहनादं विनद्योच्चैः शङ्खं दध्मौ प्रतापवान् || 12 ||', 'Then Bhishma, the great valiant grandsire of the Kuru dynasty, the grandfather of the fighters, blew his conchshell very loudly, making a sound like the roar of a lion, giving Duryodhana joy.'),
(13, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 13, 'ततः शङ्खाश्च भेर्यश्च पणवानकगोमुखाः |\nसहसैवाभ्यहन्यन्त स शब्दस्तुमुलोऽभवत् || 13 ||', 'After that, the conch shells, drums, bugles, trumpets, and horns were all suddenly sounded, and the combined sound was tumultuous.'),
(14, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 14, 'ततः श्वेतैर्हयैर्युक्ते महति स्यन्दने स्थितौ |\nमाधवः पाण्डवश्चैव दिव्यौ शङ्खौ प्रदध्मतुः || 14 ||', 'On the other side, both Lord Krishna and Arjuna, stationed on a great chariot drawn by white horses, sounded their transcendental conch shells.'),
(15, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 15, 'पाञ्चजन्यं हृषीकेशो देवदत्तं धनञ्जयः |\nपौण्ड्रं दध्मौ महाशङ्खं भीमकर्मा वृकोदरः || 15 ||', 'Lord Krishna blew His conchshell called Panchajanya, Arjuna blew his, the Devadatta, and Bhima, the voracious eater and performer of Herculean tasks, blew his terrific conchshell called Paundra.'),
(16, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 16, 'अनन्तविजयं राजा कुन्तीपुत्रो युधिष्ठिरः |\nनकुलः सहदेवश्च सुघोषमणिपुष्पकौ || 16 ||', 'King Yudhishthira, the son of Kunti, blew his conchshell, Anantavijaya, while Nakula and Sahadeva blew the Sughosha and Manipushpaka.'),
(17, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 17, 'काश्यश्च परमेष्वासः शिखण्डी च महारथः |\nधृष्टद्युम्नो विराटश्च सात्यकिश्चापराजितः || 17 ||', 'The great archer the King of Kashi, the great fighter Shikhandi, Dhrishtadyumna, Virata, the unconquerable Satyaki,'),
(18, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 18, 'द्रुपदो द्रौपदेयाश्च सर्वशः पृथिवीपते |\nसौभद्रश्च महाबाहुः शङ्खान्दध्मुः पृथक्पृथक् || 18 ||', 'Drupada, the sons of Draupadi, and the mighty-armed son of Subhadra, all blew their respective conchshells, O King.'),
(19, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 19, 'स घोषो धार्तराष्ट्राणां हृदयानि व्यदारयत् |\nनभश्च पृथिवीं चैव तुमुलो व्यनुनादयन् || 19 ||', 'The blowing of these different conchshells became uproarious, vibrating both in the sky and on the earth. It shattered the hearts of the sons of Dhritarashtra.'),
(20, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 20, 'अथ व्यवस्थितान्दृष्ट्वा धार्तराष्ट्रान्कपिध्वजः |\nप्रवृत्ते शस्त्रसम्पाते धनुरुद्यम्य पाण्डवः || 20 ||', 'At that time, Arjuna, the son of Pandu, seated in the chariot bearing the flag marked with Hanuman, took up his bow and prepared to shoot his arrows, looking at the sons of Dhritarashtra.'),
(21, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 21, 'हृषीकेशं तदा वाक्यमिदमाह महीपते |\nअर्जुन उवाच |\nसेनयोरुभयोर्मध्ये रथं स्थापय मेऽच्युत || 21 ||', 'Arjuna said: O infallible one, please place my chariot between the two armies so that I may observe those who desire to fight, and with whom I must contend in this great battle.'),
(22, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 22, 'यावदेतान्निरीक्षेऽहं योद्धुकामानवस्थितान् |\nकैर्मया सह योद्धव्यमस्मिन्रणसमुद्यमे || 22 ||', 'Let me see those who have come here to fight, wishing to please the evil-minded son of Dhritarashtra.'),
(23, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 23, 'योत्स्यमानानवेक्षेऽहं य एतेऽत्र समागता: |\nधार्तराष्ट्रस्य दूऱ्बुद्धेर्युद्धे प्रियचिकीर्षवः || 23 ||', 'I wish to see those who have gathered here to fight on behalf of the wicked Duryodhana.'),
(24, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 24, 'सञ्जय उवाच |\nएवमुक्तो हृषीकेशो गुडाकेशेन भारत |\nसेनयोरुभयोर्मध्ये स्थापयित्वा रथोत्तमम् || 24 ||', 'Sanjaya said: O King, after Arjuna had thus spoken, Lord Krishna placed the chariot in the midst of the armies of both parties.'),
(25, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 25, 'भीष्मद्रोणप्रमुखतः सर्वेषां च महीक्षिताम् |\nउवाच पार्थ पश्यैतान्समवेतान्कुरूनिति || 25 ||', 'In the presence of Bhishma, Drona, and all the other chieftains of the world, the Lord said: Just behold, O Arjuna, all the Kurus assembled here.'),
(26, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 26, 'तत्रापश्यत्स्थितान्पार्थः पितॄनथ पितामहान् |\nआचार्यान्मातुलान्भ्रातॄन्पुत्रान्पौत्रान्सखींस्तथा || 26 ||', 'There Arjuna could see within the midst of the armies of both parties his fathers, grandfathers, teachers, maternal uncles, brothers, sons, grandsons, and friends.'),
(27, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 27, 'श्वशुरान्सुहृदश्चैव सेनयोरुभयोरपि |\nतान्समीक्ष्य स कौन्तेयः सर्वान्बन्धूनवस्थितान् || 27 ||', 'He could also see his father-in-law and well-wishers in both armies. Seeing all his relatives thus arrayed, Arjuna was overwhelmed with compassion.'),
(28, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 28, 'कृपया परयाविष्टो विषीदन्निदमब्रवीत् |\nअर्जुन उवाच |\nदृष्ट्वेमं स्वजनं कृष्ण युयुत्सुं समुपस्थितम् || 28 ||', 'Arjuna said: My dear Krishna, seeing my friends and relatives present before me in such a fighting spirit, I feel the limbs of my body quivering and my mouth drying up.'),
(29, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 29, 'सीदन्ति मम गात्राणि मुखं च परिशुष्यति |\nवेपथुश्च शरीरे मे रोमहर्षश्च जायते || 29 ||', 'My whole body is trembling, and my hair is standing on end. My bow, the Gandiva, is slipping from my hand, and my skin is burning.'),
(30, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 30, 'गाण्डीवं स्रंसते हस्तात्त्वक्चैव परिदह्यते |\nन च शक्नोम्यवस्थातुं भ्रमतीव च मे मनः || 30 ||', 'I am now unable to stand here any longer. I am forgetting myself, and my mind is reeling. I see only causes of misfortune, O Krishna, killer of the Kesi demon.'),
(31, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 31, 'निमित्तानि च पश्यामि विपरीतानि केशव |\nन च श्रेयोऽनुपश्यामि हत्वा स्वजनमाहवे || 31 ||', 'I do not see how any good can come from killing my own kinsmen in this battle, nor can I, my dear Krishna, desire any subsequent victory, kingdom, or happiness.'),
(32, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 32, 'न काङ्क्षे विजयं कृष्ण न च राज्यं सुखानि च |\nकिं नो राज्येन गोविन्द किं भोगैर्जीवितेन वा || 32 ||', 'I do not desire victory, O Krishna, nor kingdom, nor pleasures. O Govinda, of what use to us is a kingdom, happiness, or even life itself when all those for whom we may desire them are now arrayed on this battlefield?'),
(33, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 32, 'न काङ्क्षे विजयं कृष्ण न च राज्यं सुखानि च |\nकिं नो राज्येन गोविन्द किं भोगैर्जीवितेन वा || 32 ||', 'I do not desire victory, O Krishna, nor kingdom, nor pleasures. O Govinda, of what use to us is a kingdom, happiness, or even life itself when all those for whom we may desire them are now arrayed on this battlefield?'),
(34, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 33, 'येषामर्थे काङ्क्षितं नो राज्यं भोगाः सुखानि च |\nत इमेऽवस्थिता युद्धे प्राणांस्त्यक्त्वा धनानि च || 33 ||', 'For whose sake we desire the kingdom, enjoyments, and happiness, these men are ready to give up their lives and properties, and are standing before us in battle.'),
(35, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 34, 'आचार्याः पितरः पुत्रास्तथैव च पितामहाः |\nमातुलाः श्वशुराः पौत्राः श्यालाः सम्बन्धिनस्तथा || 34 ||', 'Teachers, fathers, sons, grandfathers, maternal uncles, fathers-in-law, grandsons, brothers-in-law, and other relatives.'),
(36, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 36, 'पापमेवाश्रयेदस्मान्हत्वैतानाततायिनः |\nतस्मान्नार्हा वयं हन्तुं धार्तराष्ट्रान्स्वबान्धवान् || 36 ||', 'Sin will overcome us if we slay such aggressors. Therefore, it is not proper for us to kill the sons of Dhritarashtra and our friends.'),
(37, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 37, 'स्वजनं हि कथं हत्वा सुखिनः स्याम माधव |\nयद्यप्येते न पश्यन्ति लोभोपहतचेतसः || 37 ||', 'O Madhava, although these men, overtaken by greed, see no fault in killing family members or quarreling with friends, why should we, who can see the crime in destroying a family, engage in these acts of sin?'),
(38, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 38, 'कुलक्षयकृतं दोषं मित्रद्रोहे च पातकम् |\nकथं न ज्ञेयमस्माभिः पापादस्मान्निवर्तितुम् || 38 ||', 'Why should we not refrain from this sin, O Janardana, we who can see the evil of destroying a family?'),
(39, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 39, 'कुलक्षये प्रणश्यन्ति कुलधर्माः सनातनाः |\nधर्मे नष्टे कुलं कृत्स्नमधर्मोऽभिभवत्युत || 39 ||', 'When a dynasty is destroyed, its traditions perish, and the rest of the family becomes involved in irreligion.'),
(40, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 40, 'अधर्माभिभवात्कृष्ण प्रदुष्यन्ति कुलस्त्रियः |\nस्त्रीषु दुष्टासु वार्ष्णेय जायते वर्णसङ्करः || 40 ||', 'O Krishna, when irreligion prevails in the family, the women of the family become corrupt, and from the degradation of womanhood, O descendant of Vrishni, comes unwanted progeny.'),
(41, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 41, 'सङ्करो नरकायैव कुलघ्नानां कुलस्य च |\nपतन्ति पितरो ह्येषां लुप्तपिण्डोदकक्रियाः || 41 ||', 'An increase in unwanted children results in hellish life both for the family and for those who destroy the family tradition. The ancestors of such corrupt families fall, deprived of the offerings of food and water.'),
(42, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 42, 'दोषैरेतैः कुलघ्नानां वर्णसङ्करकारकैः |\nउत्साद्यन्ते जातिधर्माः कुलधर्माश्च शाश्वताः || 42 ||', 'Due to the evil deeds of the destroyers of family tradition, all kinds of community projects and family welfare activities are devastated.'),
(43, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 43, 'उत्सन्नकुलधर्माणां मनुष्याणां जनार्दन |\nनरके नियतं वासो भवतीत्यनुशुश्रुम || 43 ||', 'O Janardana, I have heard from authoritative sources that those who destroy family traditions dwell in hell for an indefinite period.'),
(44, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 44, 'अहो बत महत्पापं कर्तुं व्यवसिता वयम् |\nयद्राज्यसुखलोभेन हन्तुं स्वजनमुद्यताः || 44 ||', 'Alas, how strange it is that we are preparing to commit greatly sinful acts, driven by the desire to enjoy royal happiness.'),
(45, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 45, 'यदि मामप्रतीकारमशस्त्रं शस्त्रपाणयः |\nधार्तराष्ट्रा रणे हन्युः तन्मे क्षेमतरं भवेत् || 45 ||', 'I would consider it better for the sons of Dhritarashtra to kill me unarmed and unresisting, rather than fight with them.'),
(46, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 46, 'सञ्जय उवाच |\nएवमुक्त्वार्जुनः सङ्ख्ये रथोपस्थ उपाविशत् |\nविसृज्य सशरं चापं शोकसंविग्नमानसः || 46 ||', 'Sanjaya said: Having spoken thus, Arjuna cast aside his bow and arrows and sat down on the chariot, his mind overwhelmed with grief.'),
(47, 1, 'Arjuna Vishada Yoga', 47, 'एतच्छ्रुत्वा हृषीकेशो गुडाकेशं ससंभ्रमः |\nमम चाप्रतिसंह्राद्यं यथापूर्वं प्रवर्तते || 47 ||', 'This is the conclusion of the first chapter of the Bhagavad Gita titled “Arjuna Vishada Yoga” or “The Yoga of Arjuna’s Dejection”.'),
(48, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 1, 'सञ्जय उवाच |\nतं तथा कृपयाविष्टमश्रुपूर्णाकुलेक्षणम् |\nविषीदन्तमिदं वाक्यमुवाच मधुसूदनः || 2.1 ||', 'At that time, Lord Krishna, seeing Arjuna full of compassion, his mind deeply depressed, and his eyes full of tears, spoke the following words.'),
(49, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nकुतस्त्वा कश्मलमिदं विषमे समुपस्थितम् |\nअनार्यजुष्टमस्वर्ग्यमकीर्तिकरमर्जुन || 2.2 ||', 'The Supreme Lord said: O Arjuna, how has this delusion overcome you in this crucial moment? This is unbecoming of a noble man and does not lead to higher planets but to infamy.'),
(50, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 3, 'क्लैब्यं मा स्म गमः पार्थ नैतत्त्वय्युपपद्यते |\nक्षुद्रं हृदयदौर्बल्यं त्यक्त्वोत्तिष्ठ परन्तप || 2.3 ||', 'O son of Pritha, do not yield to unmanliness. It does not become you. Give up this weak-heartedness and arise, O chastiser of the enemy.'),
(51, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 4, 'अर्जुन उवाच |\nकथं भीष्ममहं सङ्ख्ये द्रोणं च मधुसूदन |\nइषुभिः प्रतियोत्स्यामि पूजार्हावरिसूदन || 2.4 ||', 'Arjuna said: O Madhusudana, how can I counterattack with arrows in battle men like Bhishma and Drona, who are worthy of my worship?'),
(52, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 5, 'गुरूनहत्वा हि महानुभावान्श्रेयो भोक्तुं भैक्ष्यमपीह लोके |\nहत्वार्थकामांस्तु गुरूनिहैव भुञ्जीय भोगान्रुधिरप्रदिग्धान् || 2.5 ||', 'It would be better to live in this world by begging than to live at the cost of the lives of great souls who are my teachers. Even though they are desirous of worldly gain, they are superiors. If they are killed, our spoils will be tainted with blood.'),
(53, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 6, 'न चैतद्विद्मः कतरन्नो गरीयो\nयद्वा जयेम यदि वा नो जयेयुः |\nयानेव हत्वा न जिजीविषाम-\nस्तेऽवस्थिताः प्रमुखे धार्तराष्ट्राः || 2.6 ||', 'We do not know which is better—conquering them or being conquered by them. The sons of Dhritarashtra, whom if we killed, we would not care to live, are standing before us on this battlefield.'),
(54, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 7, 'कार्पण्यदोषोपहतस्वभावः\nपृच्छामि त्वां धर्मसम्मूढचेता: |\nयच्छ्रेयः स्यान्निश्रितं ब्रूहि तन्मे\nशिष्यस्तेऽहं शाधि मां त्वां प्रपन्नम् || 2.7 ||', 'Now I am confused about my duty, and I am stricken with sorrow because of weakness. In this condition, I am asking You to tell me clearly what is best for me. Now I am Your disciple, and a soul surrendered unto You. Please instruct me.'),
(55, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 8, 'न हि प्रपश्यामि ममापनुद्या-\nद्यच्छोकमुच्छोषणमिन्द्रियाणाम् |\nअवाप्य भूमावसपत्नमृद्धं\nराज्यं सुराणामपि चाधिपत्यम् || 2.8 ||', 'I can find no means to drive away this grief which is drying up my senses. I will not be able to destroy it even if I win an unrivaled kingdom on the earth with sovereignty like the demigods in heaven.'),
(56, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 9, 'सञ्जय उवाच |\nएवमुक्त्वा हृषीकेशं गुडाकेशः परन्तप |\nन योत्स्य इति गोविन्दमुक्त्वा तूष्णीं बभूव ह || 2.9 ||', 'Sanjaya said: Having thus spoken, Arjuna, the chastiser of enemies, told Krishna, \"Govinda, I shall not fight,\" and then fell silent.'),
(57, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 10, 'तमुवाच हृषीकेशः प्रहसन्निव भारत |\nसेनयोरुभयोर्मध्ये विषीदन्तमिदं वचः || 2.10 ||', 'At that time, Krishna, smiling in the midst of both armies, spoke the following words to the grief-stricken Arjuna.'),
(58, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 11, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nअशोच्यानन्वशोचस्त्वं प्रज्ञावादांश्च भाषसे |\nगतासूनगतासूंश्च नानुशोचन्ति पण्डिताः || 2.11 ||', 'The Supreme Personality of Godhead said: While speaking learned words, you are mourning for what is not worthy of grief. Those who are wise lament neither for the living nor for the dead.'),
(59, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 12, 'न त्वेवाहं जातु नासं न त्वं नेमे जनाधिपाः |\nन चैव न भविष्यामः सर्वे वयमतः परम् || 2.12 ||', 'Never was there a time when I did not exist, nor you, nor all these kings; nor in the future shall any of us cease to be.'),
(60, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 13, 'देहिनोऽस्मिन्यथा देहे कौमारं यौवनं जरा |\nतथा देहान्तरप्राप्तिर्धीरस्तत्र न मुह्यति || 2.13 ||', 'Just as the boyhood, youth, and old age come to the embodied soul in this body, in the same way, the soul passes into another body at death. A sober person is not bewildered by such a change.'),
(61, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 14, 'मात्रास्पर्शास्तु कौन्तेय शीतोष्णसुखदुःखदाः |\nआगमापायिनोऽनित्यास्तांस्तितिक्षस्व भारत || 2.14 ||', 'O son of Kunti, the nonpermanent appearance of happiness and distress, and their disappearance in due course, are like the appearance and disappearance of winter and summer seasons. They arise from sense perception, O scion of Bharata, and one must learn to tolerate them without being disturbed.'),
(62, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 15, 'यं हि न व्यथयन्त्येते पुरुषं पुरुषर्षभ |\nसमदुःखसुखं धीरं सोऽमृतत्वाय कल्पते || 2.15 ||', 'O best among men [Arjuna], the person who is not disturbed by happiness and distress and is steady in both is certainly eligible for liberation.'),
(63, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 16, 'नासतो विद्यते भावो नाभावो विद्यते सतः |\nउभयोरपि दृष्टोऽन्तस्त्वनयोस्तत्त्वदर्शिभिः || 2.16 ||', 'Those who are seers of the truth have concluded that of the nonexistent [the material body] there is no endurance, and of the eternal [the soul] there is no change. This they have concluded by studying the nature of both.'),
(64, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 17, 'अविनाशि तु तद्विद्धि येन सर्वमिदं ततम् |\nविनाशमव्ययस्यास्य न कश्चित्कर्तुमर्हति || 2.17 ||', 'That which pervades the entire body is indestructible. No one can destroy the imperishable soul.'),
(65, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 18, 'अन्तवन्त इमे देहा नित्यस्योक्ता: शरीरिण: |\nअनाशिनोऽप्रमेयस्य तस्माद्युध्यस्व भारत || 2.18 ||', 'The material body of the indestructible, immeasurable, and eternal living entity is sure to come to an end; therefore, fight, O descendant of Bharata.'),
(66, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 19, 'य एनं वेत्ति हन्तारं यश्चैनं मन्यते हतम् |\nउभौ तौ न विजानीतो नायं हन्ति न हन्यते || 2.19 ||', 'He who thinks that the soul kills or is killed does not understand the truth, for the soul kills not, nor is it killed.'),
(67, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 20, 'न जायते म्रियते वा कदाचि-\nन्नायं भूत्वा भविता वा न भूयः |\nअजो नित्यः शाश्वतोऽयं पुराणो\nन हन्यते हन्यमाने शरीरे || 2.20 ||', 'For the soul, there is neither birth nor death at any time. He has not come into being, does not come into being, and will not come into being. He is unborn, eternal, ever-existing, and primeval. He is not slain when the body is slain.'),
(68, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 21, 'वेदाविनाशिनं नित्यं य एनमजमव्ययम् |\nकथं स पुरुषः पार्थ कं घातयति हन्ति कम् || 2.21 ||', 'O Partha, how can a person who knows that the soul is indestructible, eternal, unborn, and immutable kill anyone or cause anyone to kill?'),
(69, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 22, 'वासांसि जीर्णानि यथा विहाय\nनवानि गृह्णाति नरोऽपराणि |\nतथा शरीराणि विहाय जीर्णा-\nन्यन्यानि संयाति नवानि देही || 2.22 ||', 'As a person puts on new garments, giving up old ones, the soul similarly accepts new material bodies, giving up the old and useless ones.'),
(70, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 23, 'नैनं छिन्दन्ति शस्त्राणि नैनं दहति पावकः |\nन चैनं क्लेदयन्त्यापो न शोषयति मारुतः || 2.23 ||', 'The soul can never be cut to pieces by any weapon, nor burned by fire, nor moistened by water, nor withered by the wind.'),
(71, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 24, 'अच्छेद्योऽयमदाह्योऽयमक्लेद्योऽशोष्य एव च |\nनित्यः सर्वगतः स्थाणुरचलोऽयं सनातनः || 2.24 ||', 'This individual soul is unbreakable and insoluble, and can be neither burned nor dried. He is everlasting, present everywhere, unchangeable, immovable, and eternally the same.'),
(72, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 25, 'अव्यक्तोऽयमचिन्त्योऽयमविकार्योऽयमुच्यते |\nतस्मादेवं विदित्वैनं नानुशोचितुमर्हसि || 2.25 ||', 'It is said that the soul is invisible, inconceivable, and immutable. Knowing this, you should not grieve for the body.'),
(73, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 26, 'अथ चैनं नित्यजातं नित्यं वा मन्यसे मृतम् |\nतथापि त्वं महाबाहो नैवं शोचितुमर्हसि || 2.26 ||', 'If, however, you think that the soul is perpetually born and always dies, still you have no reason to lament, O mighty-armed.'),
(74, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 27, 'जातस्य हि ध्रुवो मृत्युर्ध्रुवं जन्म मृतस्य च |\nतस्मादपरिहार्येऽर्थे न त्वं शोचितुमर्हसि || 2.27 ||', 'For one who has taken his birth, death is certain; and for one who is dead, birth is certain. Therefore, in the unavoidable discharge of your duty, you should not lament.'),
(75, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 28, 'अव्यक्तादीनि भूतानि व्यक्तमध्यानि भारत |\nअव्यक्तनिधनान्येव तत्र का परिदेवना || 2.28 ||', 'All created beings are unmanifest in their beginning, manifest in their interim state, and unmanifest again when annihilated. So what need is there for lamentation?'),
(76, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 29, 'आश्चर्यवत्पश्यति कश्चिदेन-\nमाश्चर्यवद्वदति तथैव चान्यः |\nआश्चर्यवच्चैनमन्यः श्रृणोति\nश्रुत्वाप्येनं वेद न चैव कश्चित् || 2.29 ||', 'Some look on the soul as amazing, some describe it as amazing, and some hear of it as amazing, while others, even after hearing about it, cannot understand it at all.'),
(77, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 30, 'देही नित्यमवध्योऽयं देहे सर्वस्य भारत |\nतस्मात्सर्वाणि भूतानि न त्वं शोचितुमर्हसि || 2.30 ||', 'O descendant of Bharata, he who dwells in the body can never be slain. Therefore you need not grieve for any living being.'),
(78, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 31, 'स्वधर्ममपि चावेक्ष्य न विकम्पितुमर्हसि |\nधर्म्याद्धि युद्धाच्छ्रेयोऽन्यत्क्षत्रियस्य न विद्यते || 2.31 ||', 'Considering your specific duty as a kshatriya, you should know that there is no better engagement for you than fighting on religious principles; and so there is no need for hesitation.'),
(79, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 32, 'यदृच्छया चोपपन्नं स्वर्गद्वारमपावृतम् |\nसुखिनः क्षत्रियाः पार्थ लभन्ते युद्धमीदृशम् || 2.32 ||', 'O Partha, happy are the kshatriyas to whom such fighting opportunities come unsought, opening for them the doors of the heavenly planets.'),
(80, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 33, 'अथ चेत्त्वमिमं धर्म्यं सङ्ग्रामं न करिष्यसि |\nततः स्वधर्मं कीर्तिं च हित्वा पापमवाप्स्यसि || 2.33 ||', 'If, however, you do not perform your religious duty of fighting, then you will certainly incur sins for neglecting your duties and thus lose your reputation as a fighter.'),
(81, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 34, 'अकीर्तिं चापि भूतानि कथयिष्यन्ति तेऽव्ययाम् |\nसम्भावितस्य चाकीर्तिर्मरणादतिरिच्यते || 2.34 ||', 'People will always speak of your infamy, and for a respectable person, dishonor is worse than death.'),
(82, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 35, 'भयाद्रणादुपरतं मंस्यन्ते त्वां महारथाः |\nयेषां च त्वं बहुमतो भूत्वा यास्यसि लाघवम् || 2.35 ||', 'The great generals who have highly esteemed your name and fame will think that you have left the battlefield out of fear only, and thus they will consider you a coward.'),
(83, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 36, 'अवाच्यवादांश्च बहून्वदिष्यन्ति तवाहिताः |\nनिन्दन्तस्तव सामर्थ्यं ततो दुःखतरं नु किम् || 2.36 ||', 'Your enemies will describe you in many unkind words and scorn your ability. What could be more painful for you?'),
(84, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 37, 'हतो वा प्राप्स्यसि स्वर्गं जित्वा वा भोक्ष्यसे महीम् |\nतस्मादुत्तिष्ठ कौन्तेय युद्धाय कृतनिश्चयः || 2.37 ||', 'O son of Kunti, either you will be killed on the battlefield and attain the heavenly planets, or you will conquer and enjoy the earthly kingdom. Therefore, get up and fight with determination.'),
(85, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 38, 'सुखदुःखे समे कृत्वा लाभालाभौ जयाजयौ |\nततो युद्धाय युज्यस्व नैवं पापमवाप्स्यसि || 2.38 ||', 'Fight for the sake of duty, treating alike happiness and distress, loss and gain, victory and defeat. Fulfilling your responsibility in this way, you will never incur sin.'),
(86, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 39, 'एषा तेऽभिहिता साङ्ख्ये बुद्धिर्योगे त्विमां श्रृणु |\nबुद्ध्या युक्तो यया पार्थ कर्मबन्धं प्रहास्यसि || 2.39 ||', 'Thus far I have described this knowledge to you through analytical study. Now listen as I explain it in terms of working without fruitive results. O son of Pritha, when you act in such knowledge, you can free yourself from the bondage of works.'),
(87, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 40, 'नेहाभिक्रमनाशोऽस्ति प्रत्यवायो न विद्यते |\nस्वल्पमप्यस्य धर्मस्य त्रायते महतो भयात् || 2.40 ||', 'In this endeavor, there is no loss or diminution, and a little advancement on this path can protect one from the most dangerous type of fear.'),
(88, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 41, 'व्यवसायात्मिका बुद्धिरेकेह कुरुनन्दन |\nबहुशाखा ह्यनन्ताश्च बुद्धयोऽव्यवसायिनाम् || 2.41 ||', 'Those who are on this path are resolute in purpose, and their aim is one. O beloved child of the Kurus, the intelligence of those who are irresolute is many-branched.'),
(89, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 42, 'यामिमां पुष्पितां वाचं प्रवदन्त्यविपश्चितः |\nवेदवादरताः पार्थ नान्यदस्तीति वादिनः || 2.42 ||', 'Men of small knowledge are very much attached to the flowery words of the Vedas, which recommend various fruitive activities for elevation to heavenly planets, resulting in good birth, power, and so forth.'),
(90, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 43, 'कामात्मानः स्वर्गपरा जन्मकर्मफलप्रदाम् |\nक्रियाविशेषबहुलां भोगैश्वर्यगतिं प्रति || 2.43 ||', 'Being desirous of sense gratification and opulent life, they say that there is nothing more than this.'),
(91, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 44, 'भोगैश्वर्यप्रसक्तानां तयापहृतचेतसाम् |\nव्यवसायात्मिका बुद्धिः समाधौ न विधीयते || 2.44 ||', 'In the minds of those who are too attached to sense enjoyment and material opulence, and who are bewildered by such things, the resolute determination for devotional service to the Supreme Lord does not take place.'),
(92, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 45, 'त्रैगुण्यविषया वेदा निस्त्रैगुण्यो भवार्जुन |\nनिर्द्वन्द्वो नित्यसत्त्वस्थो निर्योगक्षेम आत्मवान् || 2.45 ||', 'The Vedas deal mainly with the subject of the three modes of material nature. Rise above these modes, O Arjuna. Be transcendental to all of them. Be free from all dualities and from all anxieties for gain and safety, and be established in the Self.'),
(93, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 46, 'यावानर्थ उदपाने सर्वतः सम्प्लुतोदके |\nतावान्सर्वेषु वेदेषु ब्राह्मणस्य विजानतः || 2.46 ||', 'All purposes served by a small well can at once be served by a great reservoir of water. Similarly, all the purposes of the Vedas can be served to one who knows the purpose behind them.'),
(94, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 47, 'कर्मण्येवाधिकारस्ते मा फलेषु कदाचन |\nमा कर्मफलहेतुर्भूर्मा ते सङ्गोऽस्त्वकर्मणि || 2.47 ||', 'You have a right to perform your prescribed duties, but you are not entitled to the fruits of actions. Never consider yourself the cause of the results of your activities, nor be attached to inaction.'),
(95, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 48, 'योगस्थः कुरु कर्माणि सङ्गं त्यक्त्वा धनञ्जय |\nसिद्ध्यसिद्ध्योः समो भूत्वा समत्वं योग उच्यते || 2.48 ||', 'Perform your duty equipoised, O Arjuna, abandoning all attachment to success or failure. Such equanimity is called yoga.'),
(96, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 49, 'दूरेण ह्यवरं कर्म बुद्धियोगाद्धनञ्जय |\nबुद्धौ शरणमन्विच्छ कृपणाः फलहेतवः || 2.49 ||', 'O Dhananjaya, keep all abominable activities far distant by devotional service, and in that consciousness surrender unto the Lord. Those who want to enjoy the fruits of their work are misers.'),
(97, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 50, 'बुद्धियुक्तो जहातीह उभे सुकृतदुष्कृते |\nतस्माद्योगाय युज्यस्व योगः कर्मसु कौशलम् || 2.50 ||', 'A man engaged in devotional service rids himself of both good and bad actions even in this life. Therefore, strive for yoga, which is the art of all work.'),
(98, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 51, 'कर्मजं बुद्धियुक्ता हि फलं त्यक्त्वा मनीषिणः |\nजन्मबन्धविनिर्मुक्ताः पदं गच्छन्त्यनामयम् || 2.51 ||', 'By thus engaging in devotional service to the Lord, great sages or devotees free themselves from the results of work in the material world. In this way, they become free from the cycle of birth and death and attain the state beyond all miseries.'),
(99, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 52, 'यदा ते मोहकलिलं बुद्धिर्व्यतितरिष्यति |\nतदा गन्तासि निर्वेदं श्रोतव्यस्य श्रुतस्य च || 2.52 ||', 'When your intelligence has passed out of the dense forest of delusion, you shall become indifferent to all that has been heard and all that is to be heard.'),
(100, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 53, 'श्रुतिविप्रतिपन्ना ते यदा स्थास्यति निश्चला |\nसमाधावचला बुद्धिस्तदा योगमवाप्स्यसि || 2.53 ||', 'When your mind is no longer disturbed by the flowery language of the Vedas and when it remains fixed in the trance of self-realization, then you will have attained the divine consciousness.'),
(101, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 54, 'अर्जुन उवाच |\nस्थितप्रज्ञस्य का भाषा समाधिस्थस्य केशव |\nस्थितधीः किं प्रभाषेत किमासीत व्रजेत किम् || 2.54 ||', 'Arjuna said: O Keshava, what are the symptoms of one whose consciousness is merged in transcendence? How does he speak, and what is his language? How does he sit, and how does he walk?'),
(102, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 55, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nप्रजहाति यदा कामान्सर्वान्पार्थ मनोगतान् |\nआत्मन्येवात्मना तुष्टः स्थितप्रज्ञस्तदोच्यते || 2.55 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: O Partha, when a man gives up all varieties of desire for sense gratification, which arise from mental concoction, and when his mind, thus purified, finds satisfaction in the self alone, then he is said to be in pure transcendental consciousness.'),
(103, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 56, 'दुःखेष्वनुद्विग्नमना: सुखेषु विगतस्पृह: |\nवीतरागभयक्रोध: स्थितधीर्मुनिरुच्यते || 2.56 ||', 'One who is not disturbed in mind even amidst the threefold miseries or elated when there is happiness, and who is free from attachment, fear, and anger, is called a sage of steady mind.'),
(104, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 57, 'य: सर्वत्रानभिस्नेहस्तत्तत्प्राप्य शुभाशुभम् |\nनाभिनन्दति न द्वेष्टि तस्य प्रज्ञा प्रतिष्ठिता || 2.57 ||', 'In the material world, one who is unaffected by whatever good or evil he may obtain, neither praising it nor despising it, is firmly fixed in perfect knowledge.'),
(105, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 58, 'यदा संहरते चायं कूर्मोऽङ्गानीव सर्वश: |\nइन्द्रियाणीन्द्रियार्थेभ्यस्तस्य प्रज्ञा प्रतिष्ठिता || 2.58 ||', 'One who is able to withdraw his senses from sense objects, as the tortoise draws its limbs within the shell, is firmly fixed in perfect consciousness.'),
(106, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 59, 'विषया विनिवर्तन्ते निराहारस्य देहिन: |\nरसवर्जं रसोऽप्यस्य परं दृष्ट्वा निवर्तते || 2.59 ||', 'Though the embodied soul may be restricted from sense enjoyment, the taste for sense objects remains. But, ceasing such engagements by experiencing a higher taste, he is fixed in consciousness.'),
(107, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 60, 'यततो ह्यपि कौन्तेय पुरुषस्य विपश्चित: |\nइन्द्रियाणि प्रमाथीनि हरन्ति प्रसभं मन: || 2.60 ||', 'The senses are so strong and impetuous, O Arjuna, that they forcibly carry away the mind even of a man of discrimination who is endeavoring to control them.'),
(108, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 61, 'तानि सर्वाणि संयम्य युक्त आसीत मत्पर: |\nवशे हि यस्येन्द्रियाणि तस्य प्रज्ञा प्रतिष्ठिता || 2.61 ||', 'One who restrains his senses and fixes his consciousness upon Me is known as a man of steady intelligence.'),
(109, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 62, 'ध्यायतो विषयान्पुंस: सङ्गस्तेषूपजायते |\nसङ्गात्सञ्जायते काम: कामात्क्रोधोऽभिजायते || 2.62 ||', 'While contemplating the objects of the senses, a person develops attachment for them, and from such attachment lust develops, and from lust anger arises.'),
(110, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 63, 'क्रोधाद्भवति संमोह: संमोहात्स्मृतिविभ्रम: |\nस्मृतिभ्रंशाद्बुद्धिनाशो बुद्धिनाशात्प्रणश्यति || 2.63 ||', 'From anger, delusion arises, and from delusion bewilderment of memory. When memory is bewildered, intelligence is lost, and when intelligence is lost, one falls down again into the material pool.'),
(111, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 64, 'रागद्वेषवियुक्तैस्तु विषयानिन्द्रियैश्चरन् |\nआत्मवश्यैर्विधेयात्मा प्रसादमधिगच्छति || 2.64 ||', 'But a person free from all attachment and aversion and able to control his senses through regulative principles of freedom can obtain the complete mercy of the Lord.'),
(112, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 65, 'प्रसादे सर्वदु:खानां हानिरस्योपजायते |\nप्रसन्नचेतसो ह्याशु बुद्धि: पर्यवतिष्ठते || 2.65 ||', 'For one thus satisfied [in Krishna consciousness], the threefold miseries of material existence exist no longer; in such satisfied consciousness, one’s intelligence is soon well established.'),
(113, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 66, 'नास्ति बुद्धिरयुक्तस्य न चायुक्तस्य भावना |\nन चाभावयतः शान्तिरशान्तस्य कुत: सुखम् || 2.66 ||', 'One who is not connected with the Supreme [in Krishna consciousness] can have neither transcendental intelligence nor a steady mind, without which there is no possibility of peace. And how can there be any happiness without peace?'),
(114, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 67, 'इन्द्रियाणां हि चरतां यन्मनोऽनुविधीयते |\nतदस्य हरति प्रज्ञां वायुर्नावमिवाम्भसि || 2.67 ||', 'As a strong wind sweeps away a boat on the water, even one of the roaming senses on which the mind focuses can carry away a man’s intelligence.'),
(115, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 68, 'तस्माद्यस्य महाबाहो निगृहीतानि सर्वश: |\nइन्द्रियाणीन्द्रियार्थेभ्यस्तस्य प्रज्ञा प्रतिष्ठिता || 2.68 ||', 'Therefore, O mighty-armed, one whose senses are restrained from their objects is certainly of steady intelligence.'),
(116, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 69, 'या निशा सर्वभूतानां तस्यां जागर्ति संयमी |\nयस्यां जाग्रति भूतानि सा निशा पश्यतो मुने: || 2.69 ||', 'What is night for all beings is the time of awakening for the self-controlled; and the time of awakening for all beings is night for the introspective sage.'),
(117, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 70, 'आपूर्यमाणमचलप्रतिष्ठं\nसमुद्रमाप: प्रविशन्ति यद्वत् |\nतद्वत्कामा यं प्रविशन्ति सर्वे\nस शान्तिमाप्नोति न कामकामी || 2.70 ||', 'A person who is not disturbed by the incessant flow of desires—that enter like rivers into the ocean, which is ever being filled but is always still—can alone achieve peace, and not the man who strives to satisfy such desires.'),
(118, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 71, 'विहाय कामान्य: सर्वान्पुमांश्चरति नि:स्पृह: |\nनिर्ममो निरहङ्कार: स शान्तिमधिगच्छति || 2.71 ||', 'A person who has given up all desires for sense gratification, who lives free from desires, who has given up all sense of proprietorship and is devoid of false ego—he alone can attain real peace.'),
(119, 2, 'Sankhya Yoga', 72, 'एषा ब्राह्मी स्थितिः पार्थ नैनां प्राप्य विमुह्यति |\nस्थित्वास्यामन्तकालेऽपि ब्रह्मनिर्वाणमृच्छति || 2.72 ||', 'That is the way of the spiritual and godly life, after attaining which a man is not bewildered. If one is thus situated even at the hour of death, one can enter into the kingdom of God.'),
(120, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच |\nज्यायसी चेत्कर्मणस्ते मता बुद्धिर्जनार्दन |\nतत्किं कर्मणि घोरे मां नियोजयसि केशव || 3.1 ||', 'Arjuna said: O Janardana, O Keshava, why do You want to engage me in this ghastly warfare, if You think that intelligence is better than fruitive work?'),
(121, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 2, 'व्यमिश्रेणेव वाक्येन बुद्धिं मोहयसीव मे |\nतदेकं वद निश्चित्य येन श्रेयोऽहमाप्नुयाम् || 3.2 ||', 'My intelligence is bewildered by Your equivocal instructions. Therefore, please tell me decisively what is most beneficial for me.'),
(122, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 3, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nलोकेऽस्मिन्द्विविधा निष्ठा पुरा प्रोक्ता मयानघ |\nज्ञानयोगेन साङ्ख्यानां कर्मयोगेन योगिनाम् || 3.3 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: O sinless Arjuna, I have already explained that there are two classes of men who try to realize the self. Some are inclined to understand it by empirical, philosophical speculation, and others by devotional service.'),
(123, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 4, 'न कर्मणामनारम्भान्नैष्कर्म्यं पुरुषोऽश्नुते |\nन च सन्न्यसनादेव सिद्धिं समधिगच्छति || 3.4 ||', 'Not by merely abstaining from work can one achieve freedom from reaction, nor by renunciation alone can one attain perfection.'),
(124, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 5, 'न हि कश्चित्क्षणमपि जातु तिष्ठत्यकर्मकृत् |\nकार्यते ह्यवश: कर्म सर्व: प्रकृतिजैर्गुणै: || 3.5 ||', 'Everyone is forced to act helplessly according to the qualities he has acquired from the modes of material nature; therefore, no one can refrain from doing something, not even for a moment.'),
(125, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 6, 'कर्मेन्द्रियाणि संयम्य य आस्ते मनसा स्मरन् |\nइन्द्रियार्थान्विमूढात्मा मिथ्याचार: स उच्यते || 3.6 ||', 'One who restrains the senses and organs of action, but whose mind dwells on sense objects, certainly deludes himself and is called a pretender.'),
(126, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 7, 'यस्त्विन्द्रियाणि मनसा नियम्यारभतेऽर्जुन |\nकर्मेन्द्रियै: कर्मयोगमसक्त: स विशिष्यते || 3.7 ||', 'On the other hand, if a sincere person tries to control the active senses by the mind and begins karma-yoga [in Krishna consciousness] without attachment, he is by far superior.'),
(127, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 8, 'नियतं कुरु कर्म त्वं कर्म ज्यायो ह्यकर्मण: |\nशरीरयात्रापि च ते न प्रसिद्ध्येदकर्मण: || 3.8 ||', 'Perform your prescribed duty, for doing so is better than not working. One cannot even maintain one’s physical body without work.'),
(128, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 9, 'यज्ञार्थात्कर्मणोऽन्यत्र लोकोऽयं कर्मबन्धन: |\nतदर्थं कर्म कौन्तेय मुक्तसङ्ग: समाचर || 3.9 ||', 'Work done as a sacrifice for Vishnu has to be performed; otherwise, work binds one to this material world. Therefore, O son of Kunti, perform your prescribed duties for His satisfaction, and in that way you will always remain free from bondage.'),
(129, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 10, 'सहयज्ञा: प्रजा: सृष्ट्वा पुरोवाच प्रजापति: |\nअनेन प्रसविष्यध्वमेष वोऽस्त्विष्टकामधुक् || 3.10 ||', 'In the beginning of creation, the Lord of all creatures sent forth generations of men and demigods, along with sacrifices for Vishnu, and blessed them by saying, \"Be thou happy by this yajna [sacrifice], because its performance will bestow upon you everything desirable for living happily and achieving liberation.\"'),
(130, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 11, 'देवान्भावयतानेन ते देवा भावयन्तु व: |\nपरस्परं भावयन्त: श्रेय: परमवाप्स्यथ || 3.11 ||', 'The demigods, being pleased by sacrifices, will also please you, and thus by cooperation between men and demigods, prosperity will reign for all.'),
(131, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 12, 'इष्टान्भोगान्हि वो देवा दास्यन्ते यज्ञभाविता: |\nतैर्दत्तानप्रदायैभ्यो यो भुङ्क्ते स्तेन एव स: || 3.12 ||', 'In charge of the various necessities of life, the demigods, being satisfied by the performance of yajna [sacrifice], will supply all necessities to you. But he who enjoys these gifts, without offering them to the demigods in return, is certainly a thief.'),
(132, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 13, 'यज्ञशिष्टाशिन: सन्तो मुच्यन्ते सर्वकिल्बिषै: |\nभुञ्जते ते त्वघं पापा ये पचन्त्यात्मकारणात् || 3.13 ||', 'The devotees of the Lord are released from all kinds of sins because they eat food that is first offered for sacrifice. Others, who prepare food for personal sense enjoyment, verily eat only sin.'),
(133, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 14, 'अन्नाद्भवन्ति भूतानि पर्जन्यादन्नसम्भव: |\nयज्ञाद्भवति पर्जन्यो यज्ञ: कर्मसमुद्भव: || 3.14 ||', 'All living bodies subsist on food grains, which are produced from rains. Rains are produced by performance of yajna [sacrifice], and yajna is born of prescribed duties.'),
(134, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 15, 'कर्म ब्रह्मोद्भवं विद्धि ब्रह्माक्षरसमुद्भवम् |\nतस्मात्सर्वगतं ब्रह्म नित्यं यज्ञे प्रतिष्ठितम् || 3.15 ||', 'Regulated activities are prescribed in the Vedas, and the Vedas are directly manifested from the Supreme Personality of Godhead. Consequently, the all-pervading Transcendence is eternally situated in acts of sacrifice.'),
(135, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 16, 'एवं प्रवर्तितं चक्रं नानुवर्तयतीह य: |\nअघायुरिन्द्रियारामो मोघं पार्थ स जीवति || 3.16 ||', 'My dear Arjuna, one who does not follow in human life the cycle of sacrifice thus established by the Vedas certainly leads a life full of sin. Living only for the satisfaction of the senses, such a person lives in vain.'),
(136, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 17, 'यस्त्वात्मरतिरेव स्यादात्मतृप्तश्च मानव: |\nआत्मन्येव च सन्तुष्टस्तस्य कार्यं न विद्यते || 3.17 ||', 'But for one who takes pleasure in the self, whose human life is one of self-realization, and who is satisfied in the self only, fully satiated—for him there is no duty.'),
(137, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 18, 'नैव तस्य कृतेनार्थो नाकृतेनेह कश्चन |\nन चास्य सर्वभूतेषु कश्चिदर्थव्यपाश्रय: || 3.18 ||', 'A self-realized man has no purpose to fulfill in the discharge of his prescribed duties, nor has he any reason not to perform such work. Nor has he any need to depend on any other living being.'),
(138, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 19, 'तस्मादसक्त: सततं कार्यं कर्म समाचर |\nअसक्तो ह्याचरन्कर्म परमाप्नोति पूरुष: || 3.19 ||', 'Therefore, without being attached to the fruits of activities, one should act as a matter of duty, for by working without attachment one attains the Supreme.'),
(139, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 20, 'कर्मणैव हि संसिद्धिमास्थिता जनकादय: |\nलोकसंग्रहमेवापि सम्पश्यन्कर्तुमर्हसि || 3.20 ||', 'Kings such as Janaka attained perfection solely by performance of prescribed duties. Therefore, just for the sake of educating the people in general, you should perform your work.'),
(140, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 21, 'यद्यदाचरति श्रेष्ठस्तत्तदेवेतरो जन: |\nस यत्प्रमाणं कुरुते लोकस्तदनुवर्तते || 3.21 ||', 'Whatever action is performed by a great man, common men follow. And whatever standards he sets by exemplary acts, all the world pursues.'),
(141, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 22, 'न मे पार्थास्ति कर्तव्यं त्रिषु लोकेषु किञ्चन |\nनानवाप्तमवाप्तव्यं वर्त एव च कर्मणि || 3.22 ||', 'O son of Pritha, there is no work prescribed for Me within all the three planetary systems. Nor am I in want of anything, nor have I a need to obtain anything—and yet I am engaged in work.'),
(142, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 23, 'यदि ह्यहं न वर्तेयं जातु कर्मण्यतन्द्रित: |\nमम वर्त्मानुवर्तन्ते मनुष्या: पार्थ सर्वश: || 3.23 ||', 'For if I ever failed to engage in carefully performing prescribed duties, O Partha, certainly all men would follow My path.'),
(143, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 24, 'उत्सीदेयुरिमे लोका न कुर्यां कर्म चेदहम् |\nसङ्करस्य च कर्ता स्यामुपहन्यामिमाः प्रजा: || 3.24 ||', 'If I did not perform prescribed duties, all these worlds would be put to ruination. I would be the cause of creating unwanted population, and I would thereby destroy the peace of all living beings.'),
(144, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 25, 'सक्ताः कर्मण्यविद्वांसो यथा कुर्वन्ति भारत |\nकुर्याद्विद्वांस्तथासक्तश्चिकीर्षुर्लोकसंग्रहम् || 3.25 ||', 'As the ignorant perform their duties with attachment to results, similarly, the learned may also act, but without attachment, for the sake of leading people on the right path.'),
(145, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 26, 'न बुद्धिभेदं जनयेदज्ञानां कर्मसङ्गिनाम् |\nजोषयेत्सर्वकर्माणि विद्वान्युक्त: समाचरन् || 3.26 ||', 'Let not the wise disrupt the minds of the ignorant, who are attached to fruitive work. They should not be discouraged from their duties, but should be encouraged to work in the spirit of devotion.'),
(146, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 27, 'प्रकृते: क्रियमाणानि गुणै: कर्माणि सर्वश: |\nअहङ्कारविमूढात्मा कर्ताहमिति मन्यते || 3.27 ||', 'The bewildered spirit soul, under the influence of the three modes of material nature, thinks himself the doer of activities that are in actuality carried out by nature.'),
(147, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 28, 'तत्त्ववित्तु महाबाहो गुणकर्मविभागयो: |\nगुणा गुणेषु वर्तन्त इति मत्वा न सज्जते || 3.28 ||', 'One who is in knowledge of the Absolute Truth, O mighty-armed, does not engage himself in the senses and sense gratification, knowing well the differences between work in devotion and work for fruitive results.'),
(148, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 29, 'प्रकृतेर्गुणसम्मूढा: सज्जन्ते गुणकर्मसु |\nतानकृत्स्नविदो मन्दान्कृत्स्नविन्न विचालयेत् || 3.29 ||', 'Bewildered by the modes of material nature, the ignorant fully engage themselves in material activities and become attached. But the wise should not unsettle them, although these duties are inferior due to the performers’ lack of knowledge.'),
(149, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 30, 'मयि सर्वाणि कर्माणि संन्यस्याध्यात्मचेतसा |\nनिराशीर्निर्ममो भूत्वा युध्यस्व विगतज्वर: || 3.30 ||', 'Therefore, O Arjuna, surrendering all your works unto Me, with full knowledge of Me, without desires for profit, with no claims to proprietorship, and free from lethargy, fight.'),
(150, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 31, 'ये मे मतमिदं नित्यमनुतिष्ठन्ति मानवाः |\nश्रद्धावन्तोऽनसूयन्तो मुच्यन्ते तेऽपि कर्मभि: || 3.31 ||', 'Those persons who execute their duties according to My injunctions and who follow this teaching faithfully, without envy, become free from the bondage of fruitive actions.'),
(151, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 32, 'ये त्वेतदभ्यसूयन्तो नानुतिष्ठन्ति मे मतम् |\nसर्वज्ञानविमूढांस्तान्विद्धि नष्टानचेतस: || 3.32 ||', 'But those who, out of envy, disregard these teachings and do not practice them regularly are to be considered bereft of all knowledge, befooled, and doomed to ignorance and bondage.'),
(152, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 33, 'सदृशं चेष्टते स्वस्याः प्रकृतेर्ज्ञानवानपि |\nप्रकृतिं यान्ति भूतानि निग्रह: किं करिष्यति || 3.33 ||', 'Even a man of knowledge acts according to his own nature, for everyone follows the nature he has acquired from the three modes. What can repression accomplish?'),
(153, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 34, 'इन्द्रियस्येन्द्रियस्यार्थे रागद्वेषौ व्यवस्थितौ |\nतयोर्न वशमागच्छेत्तौ ह्यस्य परिपन्थिनौ || 3.34 ||', 'There are principles to regulate attachment and aversion pertaining to the senses and their objects. One should not come under the control of such attachment and aversion because they are stumbling blocks on the path of self-realization.'),
(154, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 35, 'श्रेयान्स्वधर्मो विगुण: परधर्मात्स्वनुष्ठितात् |\nस्वधर्मे निधनं श्रेय: परधर्मो भयावह: || 3.35 ||', 'It is far better to discharge one’s prescribed duties, even though faultily, than another’s duties perfectly. Destruction in the course of performing one’s own duty is better than engaging in another’s duties, for to follow another’s path is dangerous.'),
(155, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 36, 'अर्जुन उवाच |\nअथ केन प्रयुक्तोऽयं पापं चरति पूरुष: |\nअनिच्छन्नपि वार्ष्णेय बलादिव नियोजित: || 3.36 ||', 'Arjuna said: O descendant of Vrishni, by what is one impelled to sinful acts, even unwillingly, as if engaged by force?'),
(156, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 37, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nकाम एष क्रोध एष रजोगुणसमुद्भव: |\nमहाशनो महापाप्मा विद्ध्येनमिह वैरिणम् || 3.37 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: It is lust only, Arjuna, which is born of contact with the material mode of passion and later transformed into wrath, and which is the all-devouring sinful enemy of this world.'),
(157, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 38, 'धूमेनाव्रियते वह्निर्यथादर्शो मलेन च |\nयथोल्बेनावृतो गर्भस्तथा तेनेदमावृतम् || 3.38 ||', 'As fire is covered by smoke, as a mirror is covered by dust, or as the embryo is covered by the womb, similarly, the living entity is covered by different degrees of this lust.'),
(158, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 39, 'आवृतं ज्ञानमेतेन ज्ञानिनो नित्यवैरिणा |\nकामरूपेण कौन्तेय दुष्पूरेणानलेन च || 3.39 ||', 'Thus, the wise man’s knowledge is covered by this eternal enemy in the form of lust, which is never satisfied and which burns like fire.'),
(159, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 40, 'इन्द्रियाणि मनो बुद्धिरस्याधिष्ठानमुच्यते |\nएतैर्विमोहयत्येष ज्ञानमावृत्य देहिनम् || 3.40 ||', 'The senses, the mind, and the intelligence are the sitting places of this lust. Through them, lust covers the real knowledge of the living entity and bewilders him.'),
(160, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 41, 'तस्मात्त्वमिन्द्रियाण्यादौ नियम्य भरतर्षभ |\nपाप्मानं प्रजहि ह्येनं ज्ञानविज्ञाननाशनम् || 3.41 ||', 'Therefore, O Arjuna, best of the Bharatas, in the very beginning curb this great symbol of sin [lust] by regulating the senses, and slay this destroyer of knowledge and self-realization.'),
(161, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 42, 'इन्द्रियाणि पराण्याहुरिन्द्रियेभ्य: परं मन: |\nमनसस्तु परा बुद्धिर्यो बुद्धे: परतस्तु स: || 3.42 ||', 'The working senses are superior to dull matter; mind is higher than the senses; intelligence is still higher than the mind; and he [the soul] is even higher than the intelligence.'),
(162, 3, 'Karma Yoga', 43, 'एवं बुद्धे: परं बुद्ध्वा संस्तभ्यात्मानमात्मना |\nजहि शत्रुं महाबाहो कामरूपं दुरासदम् || 3.43 ||', 'Thus knowing oneself to be transcendental to material intelligence, O mighty-armed Arjuna, subdue the desire, which is the formidable enemy, by controlling the mind with deliberate intelligence.'),
(163, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nइमं विवस्वते योगं प्रोक्तवानहमव्ययम् |\nविवस्वान्मनवे प्राह मनुरिक्ष्वाकवेऽब्रवीत् || 4.1 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: I instructed this imperishable science of yoga to the sun-god, Vivasvan, and Vivasvan instructed it to Manu, the father of mankind, and Manu in turn instructed it to Ikshvaku.'),
(164, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 2, 'एवं परम्पराप्राप्तमिमं राजर्षयो विदु: |\nस कालेनेह महता योगो नष्ट: परन्तप || 4.2 ||', 'This supreme science was thus received through the chain of disciplic succession, and the saintly kings understood it in that way. But in course of time the succession was broken, and therefore the science as it is appears to be lost.'),
(165, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 3, 'स एवायं मया तेऽद्य योग: प्रोक्त: पुरातन: |\nभक्तोऽसि मे सखा चेति रहस्यं ह्येतदुत्तमम् || 4.3 ||', 'That very ancient science of the relationship with the Supreme is today told by Me to you because you are My devotee as well as My friend and can therefore understand the transcendental mystery of this science.');
INSERT INTO `gita` (`id`, `chapter_number`, `chapter_name`, `verse_number`, `verse`, `translation`) VALUES
(166, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 4, 'अर्जुन उवाच |\nअपरं भवतो जन्म परं जन्म विवस्वत: |\nकथमेतद्विजानीयां त्वमादौ प्रोक्तवानिति || 4.4 ||', 'Arjuna said: The sun-god Vivasvan is senior by birth to You. How am I to understand that in the beginning You instructed this science to him?'),
(167, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 5, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच |\nबहूनि मे व्यतीतानि जन्मानि तव चार्जुन |\nतान्यहं वेद सर्वाणि न त्वं वेत्थ परन्तप || 4.5 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: Many, many births both you and I have passed. I can remember all of them, but you cannot, O subduer of the enemy!'),
(168, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 6, 'अजोऽपि सन्नव्ययात्मा भूतानामीश्वरोऽपि सन् |\nप्रकृतिं स्वामधिष्ठाय सम्भवाम्यात्ममायया || 4.6 ||', 'Although I am unborn and My transcendental body never deteriorates, and although I am the Lord of all living entities, by My internal potency I still appear in every millennium in My original transcendental form.'),
(169, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 7, 'यदा यदा हि धर्मस्य ग्लानिर्भवति भारत |\nअभ्युत्थानमधर्मस्य तदात्मानं सृजाम्यहम् || 4.7 ||', 'Whenever and wherever there is a decline in religious practice, O descendant of Bharata, and a predominant rise of irreligion—at that time I descend Myself.'),
(170, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 8, 'परित्राणाय साधूनां विनाशाय च दुष्कृताम् |\nधर्मसंस्थापनार्थाय सम्भवामि युगे युगे || 4.8 ||', 'To deliver the pious and to annihilate the miscreants, as well as to reestablish the principles of religion, I Myself appear, millennium after millennium.'),
(171, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 9, 'जन्म कर्म च मे दिव्यमेवं यो वेत्ति तत्वत: |\nत्यक्त्वा देहं पुनर्जन्म नैति मामेति सोऽर्जुन || 4.9 ||', 'One who knows the transcendental nature of My appearance and activities does not, upon leaving the body, take his birth again in this material world, but attains My eternal abode, O Arjuna.'),
(172, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 10, 'वीतरागभयक्रोधा मन्मया मामुपाश्रिता: |\nबहवो ज्ञानतपसा पूता मद्भावमागता: || 4.10 ||', 'Being freed from attachment, fear, and anger, being fully absorbed in Me and taking refuge in Me, many, many persons in the past became purified by knowledge of Me—and thus they all attained transcendental love for Me.'),
(173, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 11, 'ये यथा मां प्रपद्यन्ते तांस्तथैव भजाम्यहम् |\nमम वर्त्मानुवर्तन्ते मनुष्या: पार्थ सर्वश: || 4.11 ||', 'As all surrender unto Me, I reward them accordingly. Everyone follows My path in all respects, O son of Pritha.'),
(174, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 12, 'काङ्क्षन्त: कर्मणां सिद्धिं यजन्त इह देवता: |\nक्षिप्रं हि मानुषे लोके सिद्धिर्भवति कर्मजा || 4.12 ||', 'Men in this world desire success in fruitive activities, and therefore they worship the demigods. Quickly, of course, men get results from fruitive work in this world.'),
(175, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 13, 'चातुर्वर्ण्यं मया सृष्टं गुणकर्मविभागश: |\nतस्य कर्तारमपि मां विद्ध्यकर्तारमव्ययम् || 4.13 ||', 'According to the three modes of material nature and the work associated with them, the four divisions of human society are created by Me. And although I am the creator of this system, you should know that I am yet the non-doer, being unchangeable.'),
(176, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 14, 'न मां कर्माणि लिम्पन्ति न मे कर्मफले स्पृहा |\nइति मां योऽभिजानाति कर्मभिर्न स बध्यते || 4.14 ||', 'There is no work that affects Me; nor do I aspire for the fruits of action. One who understands this truth about Me also does not become entangled in the fruitive reactions of work.'),
(177, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 15, 'एवं ज्ञात्वा कृतं कर्म पूर्वैरपि मुमुक्षुभि: |\nकुरु कर्मैव तस्मात्त्वं पूर्वै: पूर्वतरं कृतम् || 4.15 ||', 'All the liberated souls in ancient times acted with this understanding of My transcendental nature. Therefore, you should perform your duty, following in their footsteps.'),
(178, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 16, 'किं कर्म किमकर्मेति कवयोऽप्यत्र मोहिताः |\nतत्ते कर्म प्रवक्ष्यामि यज्ज्ञात्वा मोक्ष्यसेऽशुभात् || 4.16 ||', 'Even the intelligent are bewildered in determining what is action and what is inaction. Now I shall explain to you what action is, knowing which you shall be liberated from all misfortune.'),
(179, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 17, 'कर्मणो ह्यपि बोद्धव्यं बोद्धव्यं च विकर्मण: |\nअकर्मणश्च बोद्धव्यं गहना कर्मणो गतिः || 4.17 ||', 'The intricacies of action are very hard to understand. Therefore one should know properly what action is, what forbidden action is, and what inaction is.'),
(180, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 18, 'कर्मण्यकर्म य: पश्येदकर्मणि च कर्म य: |\nस बुद्धिमान्मनुष्येषु स युक्त: कृत्स्नकर्मकृत् || 4.18 ||', 'One who sees inaction in action, and action in inaction, is intelligent among men, and he is in the transcendental position, although engaged in all sorts of activities.'),
(181, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 19, 'यस्य सर्वे समारम्भा: कामसङ्कल्पवर्जिता: |\nज्ञानाग्निदग्धकर्माणं तमाहु: पण्डितं बुधा: || 4.19 ||', 'One is understood to be in full knowledge whose every act is devoid of desire for sense gratification. He is said by sages to be a worker whose fruitive action is burned up by the fire of perfect knowledge.'),
(182, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 20, 'त्यक्त्वा कर्मफलासङ्गं नित्यतृप्तो न सङ्ग्रहम् |\nस्वकर्मण्यभिरत: समेचित्तो मानुष: || 4.20 ||', 'The person who is fully satisfied with knowledge and wisdom, who is unentangled, and who is free from all desires for sense gratification, is certainly eligible for liberation.'),
(183, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 21, 'निराशीः यतचित्तात्मा त्यक्तसर्वपरिग्रहः | शारीरं केवलं कर्म कुर्वन्नाप्नोति किल्बिषम् || 4.21 ||', 'Without desire, with the mind and self-controlled, having relinquished all sense of possession, performing actions merely by the body, one does not incur sin.'),
(184, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 22, 'यदृच्छालाभसन्तुष्टो द्वन्द्वातीतो विमत्सरः | समः सिद्धावसिद्धौ च कृत्वापि न निबध्यते || 4.22 ||', 'Content with whatever comes unasked, free from dualities and envy, balanced in success and failure, one is never bound by action.'),
(185, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 23, 'गतसङ्गस्य मुक्तस्य ज्ञानावस्थितचेतसः | यज्ञायाचरतः कर्म समग्रं प्रविलीयते || 4.23 ||', 'For one who is free from attachment, liberated, with a mind established in knowledge, all actions dissolve into the act of sacrifice.'),
(186, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 24, 'ब्रह्मार्पणं ब्रह्म हविर्ब्रह्माग्नौ ब्रह्मणा हुतम् | ब्रह्मैव तेन गन्तव्यं ब्रह्मकर्मसमाधिना || 4.24 ||', 'The offering is Brahman, the oblation is Brahman, and it is offered into the fire of Brahman by Brahman. One who sees Brahman in every action reaches Brahman.'),
(187, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 25, 'दैवमेवापरे यज्ञं योगिनः पर्युपासते | ब्रह्माग्नावपरे यज्ञं यज्ञेनैवोपजुह्वति || 4.25 ||', 'Some yogis perform sacrifice to the gods, while others offer the self as a sacrifice into the fire of Brahman.'),
(188, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 26, 'श्रोत्रादीनीन्द्रियाण्यन्ये संयमाग्निषु जुह्वति | शब्दादीन्विषयानन्य इन्द्रियाग्निषु जुह्वति || 4.26 ||', 'Some offer their senses like hearing into the fire of restraint, while others offer the objects of the senses like sound into the fire of the senses.'),
(189, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 27, 'सर्वाणीन्द्रियकर्माणि प्राणकर्माणि चापरे | आत्मसंयमयोगाग्नौ जुह्वति ज्ञानदीपिते || 4.27 ||', 'Others offer all the functions of the senses and the functions of the breath into the fire of the yoga of self-control, kindled by knowledge.'),
(190, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 28, 'द्रव्ययज्ञास्तपोयज्ञा योगयज्ञास्तथापरे | स्वाध्यायज्ञानयज्ञाश्च यतयः संशितव्रताः || 4.28 ||', 'Some perform sacrifice with material possessions, some through austerities, others through the practice of yoga, and still others by studying and gaining knowledge.'),
(191, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 29, 'अपाने जुह्वति प्राणं प्राणेऽपानं तथापरे | प्राणापानगती रुद्ध्वा प्राणायामपरायणाः || 4.29 ||', 'Some offer the outgoing breath into the incoming breath and the incoming into the outgoing, by stopping the flow of both, absorbed in the regulation of the breath.'),
(192, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 30, 'अपरे नियताहाराः प्राणान्प्राणेषु जुह्वति | सर्वेऽप्येते यज्ञविदो यज्ञक्षपितकल्मषाः || 4.30 ||', 'Others, with regulated diet, offer the breaths into the breaths. All these performers of sacrifice, knowing its true meaning, have their sins destroyed by sacrifice.'),
(193, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 31, 'यज्ञशिष्टामृतभुजो यान्ति ब्रह्म सनातनम् | नायं लोकोऽस्त्ययज्ञस्य कुतोऽन्यः कुरुसत्तम || 4.31 ||', 'Those who partake of the nectar of the remnants of sacrifice go to the eternal Brahman. But for one who does not perform sacrifice, this world is lost; how then can the next be attained?'),
(194, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 32, 'एवं बहुविधा यज्ञा वितता ब्रह्मणो मुखे | कर्मजान्विद्धि तान्सर्वानेवं ज्ञात्वा विमोक्ष्यसे || 4.32 ||', 'In this way, various kinds of sacrifices are spread out before Brahman. Know them all to be born of action, and having known this, you shall be liberated.'),
(195, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 33, 'श्रेयान्द्रव्यमयाद्यज्ञाज्ज्ञानयज्ञः परन्तप | सर्वं कर्माखिलं पार्थ ज्ञाने परिसमाप्यते || 4.33 ||', 'O Arjuna, the sacrifice of knowledge is superior to material sacrifice. For all actions culminate in knowledge, O Partha.'),
(196, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 34, 'तद्विद्धि प्रणिपातेन परिप्रश्नेन सेवया | उपदेक्ष्यन्ति ते ज्ञानं ज्ञानिनस्तत्त्वदर्शिनः || 4.34 ||', 'Understand this knowledge by approaching wise teachers, inquiring from them with reverence, and serving them. The wise who have realized the truth will impart knowledge to you.'),
(197, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 35, 'यज्ज्ञात्वा न पुनर्मोहमेवं यास्यसि पाण्डव | येन भूतान्यशेषेण द्रक्ष्यस्यात्मन्यथो मयि || 4.35 ||', 'Having obtained this knowledge, O Pandava, you will never fall into delusion again, and by this knowledge, you will see all beings in your Self, and also in Me.'),
(198, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 36, 'अपि चेदसि पापेभ्यः सर्वेभ्यः पापकृत्तमः | सर्वं ज्ञानप्लवेनैव वृजिनं सन्तरिष्यसि || 4.36 ||', 'Even if you are the most sinful among all sinners, you will cross over all sin by the raft of knowledge.'),
(199, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 37, 'यथैधांसि समिद्धोऽग्निर्भस्मसात्कुरुतेऽर्जुन | ज्ञानाग्निः सर्वकर्माणि भस्मसात्कुरुते तथा || 4.37 ||', 'Just as a blazing fire reduces wood to ashes, O Arjuna, so does the fire of knowledge burn all actions to ashes.'),
(200, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 38, 'न हि ज्ञानेन सदृशं पवित्रमिह विद्यते | तत्स्वयं योगसंसिद्धः कालेनात्मनि विन्दति || 4.38 ||', 'In this world, there is nothing as purifying as knowledge. One who is perfected in yoga finds this knowledge within himself in due time.'),
(201, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 39, 'श्रद्धावाँल्लभते ज्ञानं तत्परः संयतेन्द्रियः | ज्ञानं लब्ध्वा परां शान्तिमचिरेणाधिगच्छति || 4.39 ||', 'A person full of faith, who is devoted and who has mastered his senses, attains knowledge. Having attained knowledge, he quickly finds supreme peace.'),
(202, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 40, 'अज्ञश्चाश्रद्दधानश्च संशयात्मा विनश्यति | नायं लोकोऽस्ति न परो न सुखं संशयात्मनः || 4.40 ||', 'But the ignorant, the faithless, and the doubting soul perishes. Neither this world, nor the next, nor happiness exists for one who doubts.'),
(203, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 41, 'योगसंन्यस्तकर्माणं ज्ञानसञ्छिन्नसंशयम् | आत्मवन्तं न कर्माणि निबध्नन्ति धनञ्जय || 4.41 ||', 'O Dhananjaya, actions do not bind one who has renounced actions through yoga, whose doubts are destroyed by knowledge, and who is self-possessed.'),
(204, 4, 'Jnana Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 42, 'तस्मादज्ञानसम्भूतं हृत्स्थं ज्ञानासिनात्मनः | छित्त्वैनं संशयं योगमातिष्ठोत्तिष्ठ भारत || 4.42 ||', 'Therefore, with the sword of knowledge, cut asunder the doubt born of ignorance in your heart, and establish yourself in yoga. Arise, O Bharata.'),
(205, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | संन्यासं कर्मणां कृष्ण पुनर्योगं च शंससि | यच्छ्रेय एतयोरेकं तन्मे ब्रूहि सुनिश्चितम् || 5.1 ||', 'Arjuna said: O Krishna, You praise renunciation of actions, and then again, You recommend work with devotion. Please tell me for certain which of the two is better.'),
(206, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | संन्यासः कर्मयोगश्च निष्श्रेयसकरावुभौ | तयोस्तु कर्मसंन्यासात्कर्मयोगो विशिष्यते || 5.2 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: Renunciation of action and yoga of action both lead to the highest bliss. But of the two, the yoga of action is superior to the renunciation of action.'),
(207, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 3, 'ज्ञेयः स नित्यसंन्यासी यो न द्वेष्टि न काङ्क्षति | निर्द्वन्द्वो हि महाबाहो सुखं बन्धात्प्रमुच्यते || 5.3 ||', 'He should be known as a perpetual renunciate who neither hates nor desires; free from dualities, O mighty-armed Arjuna, he is easily liberated from bondage.'),
(208, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 4, 'साङ्ख्ययोगौ पृथग्बालाः प्रवदन्ति न पण्डिताः | एकमप्यास्थितः सम्यगुभयोर्विन्दते फलम् || 5.4 ||', 'Only the ignorant speak of Sankhya (knowledge) and yoga (action) as different, not the wise. One who is properly established in one attains the fruits of both.'),
(209, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 5, 'यत्साङ्ख्यैः प्राप्यते स्थानं तद्योगैरपि गम्यते | एकं साङ्ख्यं च योगं च यः पश्यति स पश्यति || 5.5 ||', 'The state attained by those who follow the path of knowledge is also reached by those who follow the path of action. He who sees that knowledge and action are one, truly sees.'),
(210, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 6, 'संन्यासस्तु महाबाहो दुःखमाप्तुमयोगतः | योगयुक्तो मुनिर्ब्रह्म नचिरेणाधिगच्छति || 5.6 ||', 'Renunciation is difficult to attain without yoga, O mighty-armed one. But the sage who is devoted to yoga quickly attains Brahman.'),
(211, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 7, 'योगयुक्तो विशुद्धात्मा विजितात्मा जितेन्द्रियः | सर्वभूतात्मभूतात्मा कुर्वन्नपि न लिप्यते || 5.7 ||', 'One who is devoted to the yoga of action, whose mind is purified, who has controlled the self, who has conquered the senses, and who sees his self in all beings, remains unaffected by action even while performing it.'),
(212, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 8, 'नैव किंचित्करोमीति युक्तो मन्येत तत्त्ववित् | पश्यञ्शृण्वन्स्पृशञ्जिघ्रन्नश्नन्गच्छन्स्वपन्श्वसन् || 5.8 ||', 'A person in the yogic state of realization should think, “I do nothing at all” even while seeing, hearing, touching, smelling, eating, walking, sleeping, and breathing.'),
(213, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 9, 'प्रलपन्विसृजन्गृह्णन्नुन्मिषन्निमिषन्नपि | इन्द्रियाणीन्द्रियार्थेषु वर्तन्त इति धारयन् || 5.9 ||', 'While talking, giving up, grasping, opening and closing the eyes, one should think that the senses are moving among sense objects.'),
(214, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 10, 'ब्रह्मण्याधाय कर्माणि सङ्गं त्यक्त्वा करोति यः | लिप्यते न स पापेन पद्मपत्रमिवाम्भसा || 5.10 ||', 'One who performs actions, abandoning attachment, dedicating them to Brahman, is not tainted by sin, just as a lotus leaf is untouched by water.'),
(215, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 11, 'कायेन मनसा बुद्ध्या केवलैरिन्द्रियैरपि | योगिनः कर्म कुर्वन्ति सङ्गं त्यक्त्वात्मशुद्धये || 5.11 ||', 'Yogis perform actions with the body, mind, intellect, and senses, abandoning attachment, only for the purification of the self.'),
(216, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 12, 'युक्तः कर्मफलं त्यक्त्वा शान्तिमाप्नोति नैष्ठिकीम् | अयुक्तः कामकारेण फले सक्तो निबध्यते || 5.12 ||', 'The steadfast person, renouncing the fruits of action, attains lasting peace. The unsteady, impelled by desire, is attached to the fruits and is bound.'),
(217, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 13, 'सर्वकर्माणि मनसा संन्यस्यास्ते सुखं वशी | नवद्वारे पुरे देही नैव कुर्वन्न कारयन् || 5.13 ||', 'The self-controlled person, having renounced all actions by the mind, dwells happily in the city of nine gates (the body), neither acting nor causing action.'),
(218, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 14, 'न कर्तृत्वं न कर्माणि लोकस्य सृजति प्रभुः | न कर्मफलसंयोगं स्वभावस्तु प्रवर्तते || 5.14 ||', 'The Lord creates neither the sense of doership nor the actions of people, nor the connection of actions with their results. All these are governed by nature.'),
(219, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 15, 'नादत्ते कस्यचित्पापं न चैव सुकृतं विभुः | अज्ञानेनावृतं ज्ञानं तेन मुह्यन्ति जन्तवः || 5.15 ||', 'The omnipresent Spirit does not receive anyone’s sin or merit. People are deluded because knowledge is covered by ignorance.'),
(220, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 16, 'ज्ञानेन तु तदज्ञानं येषां नाशितमात्मनः | तेषामादित्यवज्ज्ञानं प्रकाशयति तत्परम् || 5.16 ||', 'But for those whose ignorance is destroyed by knowledge of the self, like the sun, their knowledge reveals the supreme.'),
(221, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 17, 'तद्बुद्धयस्तदात्मानस्तन्निष्ठास्तत्परायणाः | गच्छन्त्यपुनरावृत्तिं ज्ञाननिर्धूतकल्मषाः || 5.17 ||', 'Those who have their intellect absorbed in that, their self established in that, their faith focused on that, and who strive with that as their supreme goal, are purified by knowledge and go to the state of non-return.'),
(222, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 18, 'विद्याविनयसम्पन्ने ब्राह्मणे गवि हस्तिनि | शुनि चैव श्वपाके च पण्डिताः समदर्शिनः || 5.18 ||', 'The wise see with equal vision a learned and humble Brahmin, a cow, an elephant, a dog, and an outcaste.'),
(223, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 19, 'इहैव तैर्जितः सर्गो येषां साम्ये स्थितं मनः | निर्दोषं हि समं ब्रह्म तस्माद्ब्रह्मणि ते स्थिताः || 5.19 ||', 'Even here in this world, the cycle of birth and death is overcome by those whose minds are established in equality. Brahman is without defect and the same in all. Therefore, they are established in Brahman.'),
(224, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 20, 'न प्रहृष्येत्प्रियं प्राप्य नोद्विजेत्प्राप्य चाप्रियम् | स्थिरबुद्धिरसम्मूढो ब्रह्मविद् ब्रह्मणि स्थितः || 5.20 ||', 'One who does not rejoice upon obtaining something pleasant nor laments upon obtaining something unpleasant, who is self-intelligent, unbewildered, and who knows Brahman, is situated in Brahman.'),
(225, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 21, 'बाह्यस्पर्शेष्वसक्तात्मा विन्दत्यात्मनि यत्सुखम् | स ब्रह्मयोगयुक्तात्मा सुखमक्षयमश्नुते || 5.21 ||', 'One whose happiness is within, who is active within, and who illumines himself within, such a yogi, united with Brahman, attains unlimited happiness.'),
(226, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 22, 'ये हि संस्पर्शजा भोगा दुःखयोनय एव ते | आद्यन्तवन्तः कौन्तेय न तेषु रमते बुधः || 5.22 ||', 'The pleasures that are born of contact with sense objects are sources of misery, for they have a beginning and an end. O son of Kunti, the wise do not delight in them.'),
(227, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 23, 'शक्नोतीहैव यः सोढुं प्राक्शरीरविमोक्षणात् | कामक्रोधोद्भवं वेगं स युक्तः स सुखी नरः || 5.23 ||', 'One who is able to withstand the force of desire and anger before death is a yogi and a happy person.'),
(228, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 24, 'योऽन्तःसुखोऽन्तरारामस्तथान्तर्ज्योतिरेव यः | स योगी ब्रह्मनिर्वाणं ब्रह्मभूतोऽधिगच्छति || 5.24 ||', 'One who finds happiness within, who enjoys within, and who illumines within, such a yogi attains Brahman, becoming Brahman himself.'),
(229, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 25, 'लभन्ते ब्रह्मनिर्वाणमृषयः क्षीणकल्मषाः | छिन्नद्वैधा यतात्मानः सर्वभूतहिते रताः || 5.25 ||', 'The sages, whose sins are destroyed, whose doubts are eliminated, who are self-controlled and engaged in the welfare of all beings, attain Brahman.'),
(230, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 26, 'कामक्रोधवियुक्तानां यतीनां यतचेतसाम् | अभितो ब्रह्मनिर्वाणं वर्तते विदितात्मनाम् || 5.26 ||', 'For those who are free from desire and anger, who are self-controlled, and who have realized the Self, Brahman is very near.'),
(231, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 27, 'स्पर्शान्कृत्वा बहिर्बाह्यांश्चक्षुश्चैवान्तरे भ्रुवोः | प्राणापानौ समौ कृत्वा नासाभ्यन्तरचारिणौ || 5.27 ||', 'Shutting out all external contacts and fixing the gaze between the eyebrows, equalizing the inward and outward breaths moving within the nostrils,'),
(232, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 28, 'यतेन्द्रियमनोबुद्धिर्मुनिर्मोक्षपरायणः | विगतेच्छाभयक्रोधो यः सदा मुक्त एव सः || 5.28 ||', 'The sage who controls his senses, mind, and intellect, who is always focused on liberation, and who is free from desire, fear, and anger, is ever liberated.'),
(233, 5, 'Karma Sanyasa Yoga', 29, 'भोक्तारं यज्ञतपसां सर्वलोकमहेश्वरम् | सुहृदं सर्वभूतानां ज्ञात्वा मां शान्तिमृच्छति || 5.29 ||', 'Knowing Me to be the enjoyer of sacrifices and austerities, the Supreme Lord of all worlds, and the friend of all beings, one attains peace.'),
(234, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | अनाश्रितः कर्मफलं कार्यं कर्म करोति यः | स संन्यासी च योगी च न निरग्निर्न चाक्रियः || 6.1 ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: He who performs his duty without dependence on the fruits of action, he is a true renunciate and a true yogi, not the one who has merely given up all activities.'),
(235, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 2, 'यं संन्यासमिति प्राहुर्योगं तं विद्धि पाण्डव | न ह्यसंन्यस्तसङ्कल्पो योगी भवति कश्चन || 6.2 ||', 'O Pandava, know that what is called renunciation is the same as yoga, for no one becomes a yogi without renouncing desires.'),
(236, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 3, 'आरुरुक्षोर्मुनेर्योगं कर्म कारणमुच्यते | योगारूढस्य तस्यैव शमः कारणमुच्यते || 6.3 ||', 'For one who is a beginner in the yoga of action, action is said to be the means; for one who is elevated in yoga, cessation of action is said to be the means.'),
(237, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 4, 'यदा हि नेन्द्रियार्थेषु न कर्मस्वनुषज्जते | सर्वसङ्कल्पसंन्यासी योगारूढस्तदोच्यते || 6.4 ||', 'When a person is not attached to sense objects or to actions and has renounced all desires, then he is said to be elevated in yoga.'),
(238, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 5, 'उद्धरेदात्मनात्मानं नात्मानमवसादयेत् | आत्मैव ह्यात्मनो बन्धुरात्मैव रिपुरात्मनः || 6.5 ||', 'One must elevate oneself by one’s own mind, not degrade oneself. The mind is the friend of the conditioned soul, and its enemy as well.'),
(239, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 6, 'बन्धुरात्मात्मनस्तस्य येनात्मैवात्मना जितः | अनात्मनस्तु शत्रुत्वे वर्तेतात्मैव शत्रुवत् || 6.6 ||', 'For one who has conquered the mind, the mind is the best of friends; but for one who has failed to do so, the mind will remain the greatest enemy.'),
(240, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 7, 'ज्ञानेनात्मनः शान्तिः यस्यात्मा त्रप्त आत्मना | सुखं तिष्ठति संन्यासी न दुःखेषु न कामसु || 6.7 ||', 'The yogi who is satisfied with knowledge and wisdom, who is unchanging and controls the senses, finds satisfaction in the self alone. He is said to be established in yoga and is not affected by happiness or distress.'),
(241, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 8, 'ज्ञेयाः शीतोष्णसुखदुःखेषु तथा मानापमानयोः | जितेन्द्रियः समः युक्तः योगी स्थिरमत्युः || 6.8 ||', 'A person is said to be established in self-realization and is called a yogi when he is fully satisfied by virtue of knowledge and wisdom, and is unchanging, having conquered the senses, viewing a lump of earth, a stone, and gold as the same.'),
(242, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 9, 'सुखिनोऽर्विणकर्मणः संयोगं कर्मणा कुरुते | मित्रार्येउदासीनस्य पण्डितस्य च पश्यति समम् || 6.9 ||', 'One who is impartial to friends, companions, enemies, and indifferent persons, as well as to those who are neutral, hateful, relatives, and to those who are both pious and sinful, is said to be superior.'),
(243, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 10, 'योगी युञ्जीत सततमात्मानं रहसि स्थितः | एकाकी यतचित्तात्मा निराशीरपरिग्रहः || 6.10 ||', 'A yogi should constantly engage in yoga practice, remaining alone in a secluded place, controlling the mind and body, and having no desires and possessions.'),
(244, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 11, 'शुचौ देशे प्रतिष्ठाप्य स्थिरमासनमात्मनः | नात्युच्छ्रितं नातिनीचं चैलाजिनकुशोत्तरम् || 6.11 ||', 'In a clean and sacred place, establish a firm seat for yourself, neither too high nor too low, made of a cloth, deerskin, and kusa grass one over the other.'),
(245, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 12, 'तत्रैकाग्रं मनः कृत्वा यतचित्तेन्द्रियक्रियाः | उपविश्यासने युञ्ज्याद्योगमात्मविशुद्धये || 6.12 ||', 'There, having established oneself on that seat, making the mind one-pointed and controlling the activities of the mind and senses, one should practice yoga for the purification of the self.'),
(246, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 13, 'समं कायशिरोग्रीवं धारयन्नचलं स्थिरः | सम्प्रेक्ष्य नासिकाग्रं स्वं दिशश्चानवलोकयन् || 6.13 ||', 'Holding the body, head, and neck straight and steady, looking at the tip of the nose, without looking in any direction.'),
(247, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 14, 'प्रशान्तात्मा विगतभीर्ब्रह्मचारिव्रते स्थितः | मनः संयम्य मच्चित्तो युक्त आसीत मत्परः || 6.14 ||', 'One should sit with a peaceful mind, free from fear, firm in the vow of celibacy, controlling the mind, and fixing it on Me, absorbed in Me.'),
(248, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 15, 'युञ्जन्नेवं सदात्मानं योगी नियतमानसः | शान्तिं निर्वाणपरमां मत्संस्थामधिगच्छति || 6.15 ||', 'Thus, always keeping the mind absorbed in the practice of yoga, with the mind restrained, the yogi attains the supreme peace of Nirvana, which abides in Me.'),
(249, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 16, 'नात्यश्नतस्तु योगोऽस्ति न चैकान्तमनश्नतः | न चातिस्वप्नशीलस्य जाग्रतो नैव चार्जुन || 6.16 ||', 'O Arjuna, yoga is not for one who eats too much or too little, nor for one who sleeps too much or too little.'),
(250, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 17, 'युक्ताहारविहारस्य युक्तचेष्टस्य कर्मसु | युक्तस्वप्नावबोधस्य योगो भवति दुःखहा || 6.17 ||', 'For one who is moderate in eating, recreation, work, sleep, and wakefulness, yoga becomes the destroyer of sorrow.'),
(251, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 18, 'यदा विनियतं चित्तमात्मन्येवावतिष्ठते | निःस्पृहः सर्वकामेभ्यो युक्त इत्युच्यते तदा || 6.18 ||', 'When the perfectly controlled mind rests in the self alone, free from all material desires, then one is said to be established in yoga.'),
(252, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 19, 'यथा दीपो निवातस्थो नेङ्गते सोपमा स्मृता | योगिनो यतचित्तस्य युञ्जतो योगमात्मनः || 6.19 ||', 'As a lamp in a windless place does not flicker, this is the comparison used for a yogi whose mind is controlled, practicing yoga in the self.'),
(253, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 20, 'यत्रोपरमते चित्तं निरुद्धं योगसेवया | यत्र चैवात्मनात्मानं पश्यन्नात्मनि तुष्यति || 6.20 ||', 'When the mind, restrained by the practice of yoga, becomes still, and when one realizes the self within, one is content in the self alone.'),
(254, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 21, 'सुखमात्यन्तिकं यत्तद् बुद्धिग्राह्यमतीन्द्रियम् | वेत्ति यत्र न चैवायं स्थितश्चलति तत्त्वतः ||', 'The state of ultimate happiness, which can be perceived by the intellect and is beyond the reach of the senses, is realized in that state, and once established in this truth, one never moves away from it.'),
(255, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 22, 'यं लब्ध्वा चापरं लाभं मन्यते नाधिकं ततः | यस्मिन्स्थितो न दुःखेन गुरुणापि विचाल्यते ||', 'Having gained this state, one does not consider any greater gain beyond it. Being established in this, even the greatest of sorrows cannot disturb one.'),
(256, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 23, 'तं विद्याद्दुःखसंयोगवियोगं योगसञ्ज्ञितम् | स निश्चयेन योक्तव्यो योगोऽनिर्विण्णचेतसा ||', 'Know this to be the state of disconnection from union with sorrow. This yoga must be practiced with determination and an unwavering mind.'),
(257, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 24, 'सङ्कल्पप्रभवान्कामांस्त्यक्त्वा सर्वानशेषतः | मनसैवेदमात्मन्यद्धारयन्न निश्चला ||', 'Completely renouncing all desires born of mental imagination, and restraining the mind from all sides by the intellect, one should remain steady.'),
(258, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 25, 'शनैः शनैरुपरमेद्बुद्ध्या धृतिगृहीतया | आत्मसंस्थं मनः कृत्वा न किञ्चिदपि चिन्तयेत् ||', 'Gradually, step by step, one should withdraw the mind with determination, and having brought it under control, one should fix it on the Self and not think of anything else.'),
(259, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 26, 'यतो यतो निश्चरति मनश्चञ्चलमस्थिरम् | ततस्ततो नियम्यैतदात्मन्येव वशं नयेत् ||', 'Wherever the restless and unsteady mind wanders, one should bring it back and focus it again on the Self.'),
(260, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 27, 'प्रशान्तमनसं ह्येनं योगिनं सुखमुत्तमम् | उपैति शान्तरजसं ब्रह्मभूतमकल्मषम् ||', 'The yogi whose mind is peaceful, whose passions are subdued, and who is free from sin, attains supreme bliss and becomes one with Brahman.'),
(261, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 28, 'युञ्जन्नेवं सदात्मानं योगी विगतकल्मषः | सुखेन ब्रह्मसंस्पर्शमत्यन्तं सुखमश्नुते ||', 'By thus constantly engaging the mind in yoga, the yogi, freed from sin, easily attains contact with Brahman and experiences boundless bliss.'),
(262, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 29, 'सर्वभूतस्थमात्मानं सर्वभूतानि चात्मनि | ईक्षते योगयुक्तात्मा सर्वत्र समदर्शनः ||', 'With the mind harmonized by yoga, the yogi sees the Self present in all beings and all beings in the Self. He sees the same everywhere.'),
(263, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 30, 'यो मां पश्यति सर्वत्र सर्वं च मयि पश्यति | तस्याहं न प्रणश्यामि स च मे न प्रणश्यति ||', 'For one who sees Me everywhere and sees everything in Me, I am never lost, nor is he ever lost to Me.'),
(264, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 31, 'सर्वभूतस्थितं यो मां भजत्येकत्वमास्थितः | सर्वथा वर्तमानोऽपि स योगी मयि वर्तते ||', 'He who, being established in oneness, worships Me abiding in all beings, that yogi lives in Me, no matter how he lives.'),
(265, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 32, 'आत्मौपम्येन सर्वत्र समं पश्यति योऽर्जुन | सुखं वा यदि वा दुःखं स योगी परमो मतः ||', 'O Arjuna, the highest yogi is one who regards all beings as he regards himself, and sees their happiness and distress as his own.'),
(266, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 33, 'अर्जुन उवाच | योऽयं योगस्त्वया प्रोक्तः साम्येन मधुसूदन | एतस्याहं न पश्यामि चञ्चलत्वात्स्थितिं स्थिराम् ||', 'Arjuna said: O Madhusudana, this yoga of equanimity, which You have spoken of, I do not see how it can endure due to the restlessness of the mind.'),
(267, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 34, 'चञ्चलं हि मनः कृष्ण प्रमाथि बलवद् दृढम् | तस्याहं निग्रहं मन्ये वायोरिव सुदुष्करम् ||', 'O Krishna, the mind is very restless, turbulent, strong, and obstinate. To control it, I think, is as difficult as controlling the wind.'),
(268, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 35, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | असंशयं महाबाहो मनो दुर्निग्रहं चलम् | अभ्यासेन तु कौन्तेय वैराग्येण च गृह्यते ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: O mighty-armed Arjuna, undoubtedly, the mind is difficult to control and restless, but it can be restrained by practice and detachment.'),
(269, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 36, 'असंयतात्मना योगो दुष्प्राप इति मे मतिः | वश्यात्मना तु यतता शक्योऽवाप्तुमुपायतः ||', 'For one whose mind is uncontrolled, yoga is difficult to attain; but for one who is self-controlled and strives with the proper means, it is possible to reach.'),
(270, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 37, 'अर्जुन उवाच | अयतिः श्रद्धयोपेतो योगाच्चलितमानसः | अप्राप्य योगसंसिद्धिं कां गतिं कृष्ण गच्छति ||', 'Arjuna said: O Krishna, what is the fate of the unsuccessful yogi who has faith but whose mind deviates from the path of self-realization before attaining perfection in yoga?'),
(271, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 38, 'कच्चिन्नोभयविभ्रष्टश्छिन्नाभ्रमिव नश्यति | अप्रतिष्ठो महाबाहो विमूढो ब्रह्मणः पथि ||', 'O mighty-armed Krishna, does not such a person, deviating from both material and spiritual pursuits, perish like a broken cloud, without any foundation?'),
(272, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 39, 'एतन्मे संशयं कृष्ण छेत्तुमर्हस्यशेषतः | त्वदन्यः संशयस्यास्य छेत्ता न ह्युपपद्यते ||', 'This doubt of mine, O Krishna, You must completely dispel, for there is no one other than You who can do so.'),
(273, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 40, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | पार्थ नैवेह नामुत्र विनाशस्तस्य विद्यते | न हि कल्याणकृत्कश्चिद् दुर्गतिं तात गच्छति ||', 'The Blessed Lord said: O Partha, neither in this world nor in the next is there destruction for him; for one who does good, My dear friend, never comes to misfortune.'),
(274, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 41, 'प्राप्य पुण्यकृतां लोकानुषित्वा शाश्वतीः समाः | शुचीनां श्रीमतां गेहे योगभ्रष्टोऽभिजायते ||', 'Having attained the worlds of the righteous and living there for many years, the unsuccessful yogi is reborn into a home of the pure and prosperous.'),
(275, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 42, 'अथवा योगिनामेव कुले भवति धीमताम् | एतद्धि दुर्लभतरं लोके जन्म यदीदृशम् ||', 'Or he is born into a family of wise yogis. Such a birth is indeed very rare in this world.'),
(276, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 43, 'तत्र तं बुद्धिसंयोगं लभते पौर्वदेहिकम् | यतते च ततो भूयः संसिद्धौ कुरुनन्दन ||', 'There, he regains the knowledge from his previous birth and strives again for perfection, O son of the Kurus.'),
(277, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 44, 'पूर्वाभ्यासेन तेनैव ह्रियते ह्यवशोऽपि सः | जिज्ञासुरपि योगस्य शब्दब्रह्मातिवर्तते ||', 'By the power of his previous practice, he is irresistibly carried forward. Even the inquirer into yoga rises above the words of the Vedas.'),
(278, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 45, 'प्रयत्नाद्यतमानस्तु योगी संशुद्धकिल्बिषः | अनेकजन्मसंसिद्धस्ततो याति परां गतिम् ||', 'With determined effort, the yogi who is purified of all sins, having perfected himself over many lifetimes, finally reaches the supreme goal.'),
(279, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 46, 'तपस्विभ्योऽधिको योगी ज्ञानिभ्योऽपि मतोऽधिकः | कर्मिभ्यश्चाधिको योगी तस्माद्योगी भवाजुन ||', 'The yogi is superior to the ascetic, superior to the wise, and superior to the person who performs rituals. Therefore, O Arjuna, be a yogi.'),
(280, 6, 'Dhyana Yoga', 47, 'योगिनामपि सर्वेषां मद्गतेनान्तरात्मना | श्रद्धावान्भजते यो मां स मे युक्ततमो मतः ||', 'And of all yogis, the one who worships Me with faith, his inner self absorbed in Me, is considered by Me to be the most united with Me.'),
(281, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 1, 'मय्यासक्तमना: पार्थ योगं युञ्जन्मदाश्रय:। असंशयं समग्रं मां यथा ज्ञास्यसि तच्छृणु।।', 'With your mind attached to Me and taking shelter in Me, practice yoga. Listen to how you can know Me fully, free from doubt.'),
(282, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 2, 'ज्ञानं तेऽहं सविज्ञानमिदं वक्ष्याम्यशेषत:। यज्ज्ञात्वा नेह भूयोऽन्यज्ज्ञातव्यमवशिष्यते।।', 'I will impart to you knowledge and realization in full. Knowing this, nothing else remains to be known.'),
(283, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 3, 'मनुष्याणां सहस्रेषु कश्चिद्यतति सिद्धये। यततामपि सिद्धानां कश्चिन्मां वेत्ति तत्त्वत:।।', 'Among thousands of men, perhaps one strives for perfection, and among those who strive, scarcely one knows Me in truth.'),
(284, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 4, 'भूमिरापोऽनलो वायु: खं मनो बुद्धिरेव च। अहंकार इतीयं मे भिन्ना प्रकृतिरष्टधा।।', 'Earth, water, fire, air, ether, mind, intelligence, and ego—these constitute My eightfold separated material energy.'),
(285, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 5, 'अपरेयमितस्त्वन्यां प्रकृतिं विद्धि मे पराम्। जीवभूतां महाबाहो ययेदं धार्यते जगत्।।', 'Beyond this inferior energy, O mighty-armed Arjuna, know that I have another, superior energy. This is the living beings who sustain the universe.'),
(286, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 6, 'एतद्योनीनि भूतानि सर्वाणीत्युपधारय। अहं कृत्स्नस्य जगत: प्रभव: प्रलयस्तथा।।', 'Understand that all living beings are born from these two natures. I am the origin and dissolution of the entire universe.'),
(287, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 7, 'मत्त: परतरं नान्यत्किंचिदस्ति धनंजय। मयि सर्वमिदं प्रोतं सूत्रे मणिगणा इव।।', 'There is nothing superior to Me, O Arjuna. Everything rests upon Me, like pearls strung on a thread.'),
(288, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 8, 'रसोऽहमप्सु कौन्तेय प्रभास्मि शशिसूर्ययो:। प्रणव: सर्ववेदेषु शब्द: खे पौरुषं नृषु।।', 'I am the taste of water, the light of the sun and moon, the Om in the Vedas, the sound in ether, and the ability in men.'),
(289, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 9, 'पुण्यो गन्ध: पृथिव्यां च तेजश्चास्मि विभावसौ। जीवनं सर्वभूतेषु तपश्चास्मि तपस्विषु।।', 'I am the fragrance of the earth, the heat in fire, the life in all beings, and the penance of the ascetics.'),
(290, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 10, 'बीजं मां सर्वभूतानां विद्धि पार्थ सनातनम्। बुद्धिर्बुद्धिमतामस्मि तेजस्तेजस्विनामहम्।।', 'Know that I am the eternal seed of all beings, O Arjuna. I am the intelligence of the intelligent and the splendor of the splendid.'),
(291, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 11, 'बलं बलवतां चाहं कामरागविवर्जितम्। धर्माविरुद्धो भूतेषु कामोऽस्मि भरतर्षभ।।', 'I am the strength of the strong, devoid of desire and passion. In all beings, I am the desire that is not contrary to dharma, O Arjuna.'),
(292, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 12, 'ये चैव सात्त्विका भावा राजसास्तामसाश्च ये। मत्त एवेति तान्विद्धि न त्वहं तेषु ते मयि।।', 'Whatever states of being—goodness, passion, or ignorance—exist, they are all born of Me. But I am not in them; they are in Me.'),
(293, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 13, 'त्रिभिर्गुणमयैर्भावैरेभि: सर्वमिदं जगत्। मोहितं नाभिजानाति मामेभ्य: परमव्ययम्।।', 'Deluded by the three modes of nature, the world does not know Me, who am above these modes and inexhaustible.'),
(294, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 14, 'दैवी ह्येषा गुणमयी मम माया दुरत्यया। मामेव ये प्रपद्यन्ते मायामेतां तरन्ति ते।।', 'This divine energy of Mine, consisting of the three modes of nature, is difficult to overcome. But those who take shelter of Me cross beyond it.'),
(295, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 15, 'न मां दुष्कृतिनो मूढा: प्रपद्यन्ते नराधमा:। माययापहृतज्ञाना आसुरं भावमाश्रिता:।।', 'The foolish and the wicked do not surrender to Me. Deluded by Maya, they adopt the nature of demons.'),
(296, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 16, 'चतुर्विधा भजन्ते मां जना: सुकृतिनोऽर्जुन। आर्तो जिज्ञासुरर्थार्थी ज्ञानी च भरतर्षभ।।', 'Four kinds of people worship Me, O Arjuna—the distressed, the seeker of knowledge, the seeker of wealth, and the wise.'),
(297, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 17, 'तेषां ज्ञानी नित्ययुक्त एकभक्तिर्विशिष्यते। प्रियो हि ज्ञानिनोऽत्यर्थमहं स च मम प्रिय:।।', 'Among them, the wise, who are always united with Me in devotion, are superior. For them, I am very dear, and they are dear to Me.'),
(298, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 18, 'उदाराः सर्व एवैते ज्ञानी त्वात्मैव मे मतम्। आस्थित: स हि युक्तात्मा मामेवानुत्तमां गतिम्।।', 'All these are noble, but the wise one is as Myself. Being perfectly established in Me, they attain the highest goal.'),
(299, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 19, 'बहूनां जन्मनामन्ते ज्ञानवान्मां प्रपद्यते। वासुदेव: सर्वमिति स महात्मा सुदुर्लभ:।।', 'After many births, the wise surrender unto Me, knowing that Vasudeva is everything. Such a great soul is very rare.'),
(300, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 20, 'कामैस्तैस्तैर्हृतज्ञानाः प्रपद्यन्तेऽन्यदेवताः। तं तं नियममास्थाय प्रकृत्या नियता स्वया।।', 'Those whose knowledge has been stolen by material desires surrender to demigods and follow the particular rules and regulations of worship according to their own natures.'),
(301, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 21, 'यो यो यां यां तनुं भक्तः श्रद्धयार्चितुमिच्छति। तस्य तस्याचलां श्रद्धां तामेव विदधाम्यहम्।।', 'I make the faith of that devotee steady in whichever deity they choose to worship with faith.'),
(302, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 22, 'स तया श्रद्धया युक्तस्तस्याराधनमीहते। लभते च ततः कामान्मयैव विहितान्हि तान्।।', 'Endowed with that faith, they engage in the worship of that deity and obtain their desires, which are indeed ordained by Me.'),
(303, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 23, 'अन्तवत्तु फलं तेषां तद्भवत्यल्पमेधसाम्। देवान्देवयजो यान्ति मद्भक्ता यान्ति मामपि।।', 'The fruits gained by these people of small understanding are temporary. Those who worship demigods go to them, but My devotees reach Me.'),
(304, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 24, 'अव्यक्तं व्यक्तिमापन्नं मन्यन्ते मामबुद्धयः। परं भावमजानन्तो ममाव्ययमनुत्तमम्।।', 'The unintelligent think of Me, the unmanifested, as having assumed a manifest form, not knowing My higher, imperishable, and supreme nature.'),
(305, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 25, 'नाहं प्रकाशः सर्वस्य योगमायासमावृतः। मूढोऽयं नाभिजानाति लोको मामजमव्ययम्।।', 'I am never manifest to the foolish and unintelligent. For them, I am covered by My internal potency, and they do not know that I am unborn and infallible.'),
(306, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 26, 'वेदाहं समतीतानि वर्तमानानि चार्जुन। भविष्याणि च भूतानि मां तु वेद न कश्चन।।', 'I know everything about the past, present, and future, O Arjuna, and I know all living beings, but Me no one knows.'),
(307, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 27, 'इच्छाद्वेषसमुत्थेन द्वन्द्वमोहेन भारत। सर्वभूतानि सम्मोहं सर्गे यान्ति परन्तप।।', 'O descendant of Bharata, all living beings are born into delusion, overcome by the dualities of desire and hate.'),
(308, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 28, 'येषां त्वन्तगतं पापं जनानां पुण्यकर्मणाम्। ते द्वन्द्वमोहनिर्मुक्ता भजन्ते मां दृढव्रता:।।', 'But those whose sins are destroyed, who are firmly engaged in pious acts and are free from the delusion of dualities, worship Me with firm determination.'),
(309, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 29, 'जरामरणमोक्षाय मामाश्रित्य यतन्ति ये। ते ब्रह्म तद्विदु: कृत्स्नमध्यात्मं कर्म चाखिलम्।।', 'Those who strive for liberation from old age and death by taking refuge in Me come to know Brahman, the self, and the entirety of action.'),
(310, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 30, 'साधिभूताधिदैवं मां साधियज्ञं च ये विदु:। प्रयाणकालेऽपि च मां ते विदुर्युक्तचेतस:।।', 'Those who know Me as the governing principle of material manifestation, demigods, and sacrifices, can understand and know Me even at the time of death.'),
(311, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 20, 'कामैस्तैस्तैर्हृतज्ञानाः प्रपद्यन्तेऽन्यदेवताः। तं तं नियममास्थाय प्रकृत्या नियता स्वया।।', 'Those whose knowledge has been stolen by material desires surrender to demigods and follow the particular rules and regulations of worship according to their own natures.'),
(312, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 21, 'यो यो यां यां तनुं भक्तः श्रद्धयार्चितुमिच्छति। तस्य तस्याचलां श्रद्धां तामेव विदधाम्यहम्।।', 'I make the faith of that devotee steady in whichever deity they choose to worship with faith.'),
(313, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 22, 'स तया श्रद्धया युक्तस्तस्याराधनमीहते। लभते च ततः कामान्मयैव विहितान्हि तान्।।', 'Endowed with that faith, they engage in the worship of that deity and obtain their desires, which are indeed ordained by Me.'),
(314, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 23, 'अन्तवत्तु फलं तेषां तद्भवत्यल्पमेधसाम्। देवान्देवयजो यान्ति मद्भक्ता यान्ति मामपि।।', 'The fruits gained by these people of small understanding are temporary. Those who worship demigods go to them, but My devotees reach Me.'),
(315, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 24, 'अव्यक्तं व्यक्तिमापन्नं मन्यन्ते मामबुद्धयः। परं भावमजानन्तो ममाव्ययमनुत्तमम्।।', 'The unintelligent think of Me, the unmanifested, as having assumed a manifest form, not knowing My higher, imperishable, and supreme nature.'),
(316, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 25, 'नाहं प्रकाशः सर्वस्य योगमायासमावृतः। मूढोऽयं नाभिजानाति लोको मामजमव्ययम्।।', 'I am never manifest to the foolish and unintelligent. For them, I am covered by My internal potency, and they do not know that I am unborn and infallible.'),
(317, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 26, 'वेदाहं समतीतानि वर्तमानानि चार्जुन। भविष्याणि च भूतानि मां तु वेद न कश्चन।।', 'I know everything about the past, present, and future, O Arjuna, and I know all living beings, but Me no one knows.'),
(318, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 27, 'इच्छाद्वेषसमुत्थेन द्वन्द्वमोहेन भारत। सर्वभूतानि सम्मोहं सर्गे यान्ति परन्तप।।', 'O descendant of Bharata, all living beings are born into delusion, overcome by the dualities of desire and hate.'),
(319, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 28, 'येषां त्वन्तगतं पापं जनानां पुण्यकर्मणाम्। ते द्वन्द्वमोहनिर्मुक्ता भजन्ते मां दृढव्रता:।।', 'But those whose sins are destroyed, who are firmly engaged in pious acts and are free from the delusion of dualities, worship Me with firm determination.'),
(320, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 29, 'जरामरणमोक्षाय मामाश्रित्य यतन्ति ये। ते ब्रह्म तद्विदु: कृत्स्नमध्यात्मं कर्म चाखिलम्।।', 'Those who strive for liberation from old age and death by taking refuge in Me come to know Brahman, the self, and the entirety of action.'),
(321, 7, 'Jnana Vijnana Yoga', 30, 'साधिभूताधिदैवं मां साधियज्ञं च ये विदु:। प्रयाणकालेऽपि च मां ते विदुर्युक्तचेतस:।।', 'Those who know Me as the governing principle of material manifestation, demigods, and sacrifices, can understand and know Me even at the time of death.'),
(322, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | किं तद्ब्रह्म किमध्यात्मं किं कर्म पुरुषोत्तम। अधिभूतं च किं प्रोक्तमधिदैवं किमुच्यते।।', 'Arjuna said: O Supreme Person, what is Brahman? What is the self? What are actions? What is the material manifestation, and what are the demigods?'),
(323, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 2, 'अधियज्ञः कथं कोऽत्र देहेऽस्मिन्मधुसूदन। प्रयाणकाले च कथं ज्ञेयोऽसि नियतात्मभिः।।', 'Who is the lord of sacrifice in this body, and how is He known at the time of death, O Madhusudana?'),
(324, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 3, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | अक्षरं ब्रह्म परमं स्वभावोऽध्यात्ममुच्यते। भूतभावोद्भवकरो विसर्ग: कर्मसञ्ज्ञित:।।', 'The Supreme Personality of Godhead said: The indestructible, transcendental living entity is called Brahman, and his eternal nature is called the self. Action, or karma, is the activity of the living entity that creates material bodies.'),
(325, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 4, 'अधिभूतं क्षरो भाव: पुरुषश्चाधिदैवतम्। अधियज्ञोऽहमेवात्र देहे देहभृतां वर।।', 'The physical nature is known to be endlessly mutable. The universal form of the Lord, which includes all the demigods, is called Adhidaiva. And I am the lord of sacrifice, known as Adhiyajna, residing in the body, O best of the embodied.'),
(326, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 5, 'अन्तकाले च मामेव स्मरन्मुक्त्वा कलेवरम्। य: प्रयाति स मद्भावं याति नास्त्यत्र संशय:।।', 'Whoever, at the time of death, remembers Me alone and leaves the body, attains My nature. Of this, there is no doubt.'),
(327, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 6, 'यं यं वाऽपि स्मरन्भावं त्यजत्यन्ते कलेवरम्। तं तमेवैति कौन्तेय सदा तद्भावभावित:।।', 'Whatever state of being one remembers when he quits his body, that state he will attain without fail, O son of Kunti.'),
(328, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 7, 'तस्मात्सर्वेषु कालेषु मामनुस्मर युध्य च। मय्यर्पितमनोबुद्धिर्मामेवैष्यस्यसंशयम्।।', 'Therefore, Arjuna, think of Me always and fight. With your mind and intelligence fixed on Me, you will attain Me without doubt.'),
(329, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 8, 'अभ्यासयोगयुक्तेन चेतसा नान्यगामिना। परमं पुरुषं दिव्यं याति पार्थानुचिन्तयन्।।', 'By meditating on Me with a mind focused by the practice of yoga and not diverted to anything else, one achieves the Supreme Person, who is beyond everything.'),
(330, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 9, 'कविं पुराणमनुशासितारमणोरणीयांसमनुस्मरेद्य:। सर्वस्य धातारमचिन्त्यरूपमादित्यवर्णं तमस: परस्तात्।।', 'One should meditate upon the Supreme Person as the one who knows everything, the oldest, the controller, smaller than the smallest, the sustainer of everything, beyond all material conception, inconceivable, and luminous like the sun, and beyond the darkness of matter.'),
(331, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 10, 'प्रयाणकाले मनसाचलेन भक्त्या युक्तो योगबलेन चैव। भ्रुवोर्मध्ये प्राणमावेश्य सम्यक् स तं परं पुरुषमुपैति दिव्यम्।।', 'At the time of death, with an unflinching mind engaged by yoga and devotion, and by fixing the life air between the eyebrows, one attains the Supreme Person.'),
(332, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 11, 'यदक्षरं वेदविदो वदन्ति विशन्ति यद्यतयो वीतरागाः। यदिच्छन्तो ब्रह्मचर्यं चरन्ति तत्ते पदं संग्रहेण प्रवक्ष्ये।।', 'I shall now explain to you the process to attain that which the knowers of the Vedas describe as the imperishable, which the great sages, freed from all attachments, enter into, and desiring which they practice celibacy.'),
(333, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 12, 'सर्वद्वाराणि संयम्य मनो हृदि निरुध्य च। मूर्ध्न्याधायात्मन: प्राणमास्थितो योगधारणाम्।।', 'Controlling all the doors of the body, fixing the mind on the heart and the life air at the top of the head, one establishes himself in yoga.'),
(334, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 13, 'ओमित्येकाक्षरं ब्रह्म व्याहरन्मामनुस्मरन्। य: प्रयाति त्यजन्देहं स याति परमां गतिम्।।', 'Uttering the sacred syllable Om, the symbol of Brahman, and remembering Me, one who departs, leaving the body, attains the supreme goal.'),
(335, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 14, 'अनन्यचेताः सततं यो मां स्मरति नित्यशः। तस्याहं सुलभः पार्थ नित्ययुक्तस्य योगिनः।।', 'For one who remembers Me without deviation, I am easy to obtain, O Arjuna, because of their constant engagement in devotional service.'),
(336, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 15, 'मामुपेत्य पुनर्जन्म दुःखालयमशाश्वतम्। नाप्नुवन्ति महात्मान: संसिद्धिं परमां गताः।।', 'Having attained Me, the great souls do not return to this place of sorrow and impermanence, for they have reached the highest perfection.'),
(337, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 16, 'आब्रह्मभुवनाल्लोका: पुनरावर्तिनोऽर्जुन। मामुपेत्य तु कौन्तेय पुनर्जन्म न विद्यते।।', 'From the highest planet in the material world down to the lowest, all are places of misery where repeated birth and death occur. But one who attains My abode never takes birth again.'),
(338, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 17, 'सहस्रयुगपर्यन्तमहर्यद्ब्रह्मणो विदु:। रात्रिं युगसहस्रान्तां तेऽहोरात्रविदो जना:।।', 'By human calculation, one day of Brahma is equal to a thousand cycles of the four ages, and his night is also of the same duration.'),
(339, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 18, 'अव्यक्ताद्व्यक्तय: सर्वा: प्रभवन्त्यहरागमे। रात्र्यागमे प्रलीयन्ते तत्रैवाव्यक्तसञ्ज्ञके।।', 'At the beginning of Brahma’s day, all living entities become manifest from the unmanifest state, and thereafter, when night falls, they are merged back into the unmanifest again.'),
(340, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 19, 'भूतग्राम: स एवायं भूत्वा भूत्वा प्रलीयते। रात्र्यागमेऽवश: पार्थ प्रभवत्यहरागमे।।', 'Again and again, when Brahma’s day arrives, all living entities come into being, and with the arrival of his night, they are helplessly annihilated.'),
(341, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 20, 'परस्तस्मात्तु भावोऽन्योऽव्यक्तोऽव्यक्तात्सनातन:। य: स सर्वेषु भूतेषु नश्यत्सु न विनश्यति।।', 'Yet there is another unmanifest nature, eternal and transcendental to this manifest and unmanifest matter. It is supreme and is never annihilated, even when all others perish.'),
(342, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 21, 'अव्यक्तोऽक्षर इत्युक्तस्तमाहु: परमां गतिम्। यं प्राप्य न निवर्तन्ते तद्धाम परमं मम।।', 'That which is called the unmanifest and the imperishable is the supreme destination. Those who reach it never return. That is My supreme abode.'),
(343, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 22, 'पुरुष: स पर: पार्थ भक्त्या लभ्यस्त्वनन्यया। यस्यान्त:स्थानि भूतानि येन सर्वमिदं ततम्।।', 'The Supreme Person, who is greater than all, is attainable by unalloyed devotion. Although He is present in His abode, He pervades everything and is all that is.');
INSERT INTO `gita` (`id`, `chapter_number`, `chapter_name`, `verse_number`, `verse`, `translation`) VALUES
(344, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 23, 'यत्र काले त्वनावृत्तिमावृत्तिं चैव योगिन:। प्रयाता यान्ति तं कालं वक्ष्यामि भरतर्षभ।।', 'O best of the Bharatas, I shall now explain to you the times at which, departing from this world, the yogis do or do not come back.'),
(345, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 24, 'अग्निर्ज्योतिरह: शुक्ल: षण्मासा उत्तरायणम्। तत्र प्रयाता गच्छन्ति ब्रह्म ब्रह्मविदो जना:।।', 'Those who know the Supreme Brahman depart during the influence of the fiery god, in the light, at an auspicious moment of the day, during the fortnight of the waxing moon, and the six months when the sun travels in the north.'),
(346, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 25, 'धूमो रात्रिस्तथा कृष्ण: षण्मासा दक्षिणायनम्। तत्र चान्द्रमसं ज्योतिरोगी प्राप्य निवर्तते।।', 'The mystic who passes away during the smoke, the night, the dark fortnight, or the six months of the southern path of the sun attains the lunar light and returns.'),
(347, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 26, 'शुक्लकृष्णे गती ह्येते जगत: शाश्वते मते। एकया यात्यनावृत्तिमन्ययावर्तते पुन:।।', 'According to the Vedas, there are two ways of passing from this world—one in light and one in darkness. When one passes in light, he does not return; but when one passes in darkness, he returns.'),
(348, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 27, 'नैते सृती पार्थ जानन्योगी मुह्यति कश्चन। तस्मात्सर्वेषु कालेषु योगयुक्तो भवार्जुन।।', 'The devotees who know these two paths, O Arjuna, are never bewildered. Therefore, be always fixed in yoga.'),
(349, 8, 'Akshara Parabrahma Yoga', 28, 'वेदेषु यज्ञेषु तप:सु चैव दानेषु यत्पुण्यफलं प्रदिष्टम्। अत्येति तत्सर्वमिदं विदित्वा योगी परं स्थानमुपैति चाद्यम्।।', 'Knowing this, the yogi surpasses all the results derived from studying the Vedas, performing sacrifices, austerities, and charities, and attains the supreme eternal abode.'),
(350, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | इदं तु ते गुह्यतमं प्रवक्ष्याम्यनसूयवे। ज्ञानं विज्ञानसहितं यज्ज्ञात्वा मोक्ष्यसेऽशुभात्।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: I shall now declare to you, who do not envy Me, this most confidential knowledge, along with realization. Knowing this, you shall be freed from the miseries of material existence.'),
(351, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 2, 'राजविद्या राजगुह्यं पवित्रमिदमुत्तमम्। प्रत्यक्षावगमं धर्म्यं सुसुखं कर्तुमव्ययम्।।', 'This knowledge is the king of sciences, the most secret of all secrets. It is the purest knowledge, and because it gives direct perception of the self by realization, it is the perfection of religion. It is everlasting and joyfully performed.'),
(352, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 3, 'अश्रद्दधानाः पुरुषा धर्मस्यास्य परन्तप। अप्राप्य मां निवर्तन्ते मृत्युसंसारवर्त्मनि।।', 'Those who are not faithful on the path of devotional service cannot attain Me, O conqueror of foes. Therefore, they return to the path of birth and death in this material world.'),
(353, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 4, 'मया ततमिदं सर्वं जगदव्यक्तमूर्तिना। मत्स्थानि सर्वभूतानि न चाहं तेष्ववस्थित:।।', 'By Me, in My unmanifested form, this entire universe is pervaded. All beings are in Me, but I am not in them.'),
(354, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 5, 'न च मत्स्थानि भूतानि पश्य मे योगमैश्वरम्। भूतभृन्न च भूतस्थो ममात्मा भूतभावन:।।', 'And yet everything that is created does not rest in Me. Behold My mystic opulence! Although I am the maintainer of all living entities and although I am everywhere, still My Self is the very source of creation.'),
(355, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 6, 'यथाकाशस्थितो नित्यं वायु: सर्वत्रगो महान्। तथा सर्वाणि भूतानि मत्स्थानीत्युपधारय।।', 'Understand that as the mighty wind, blowing everywhere, rests always in the sky, all created beings rest in Me.'),
(356, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 7, 'सर्वभूतानि कौन्तेय प्रकृतिं यान्ति मामिकाम्। कल्पक्षये पुनस्तानि कल्पादौ विसृजाम्यहम्।।', 'O son of Kunti, at the end of the millennium, every material manifestation enters into My nature, and at the beginning of another millennium, by My potency, I create them again.'),
(357, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 8, 'प्रकृतिं स्वामवष्टभ्य विसृजामि पुन: पुन:। भूतग्राममिमं कृत्स्नमवशं प्रकृतेर्वशात्।।', 'The whole cosmic order is under Me. By My will, it is manifested again and again, and by My will, it is annihilated at the end.'),
(358, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 9, 'न च मां तानि कर्माणि निबध्नन्ति धनञ्जय। उदासीनवदासीनमसक्तं तेषु कर्मसु।।', 'O Dhananjaya, these acts do not bind Me. I remain like a neutral observer, unattached to these actions.'),
(359, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 10, 'मयाध्यक्षेण प्रकृति: सूयते सचराचरम्। हेतुनानेन कौन्तेय जगद्विपरिवर्तते।।', 'Under My supervision, material nature produces both the moving and the nonmoving. Because of this, O son of Kunti, the world rotates.'),
(360, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 11, 'अवजानन्ति मां मूढा मानुषीं तनुमाश्रितम्। परं भावमजानन्तो मम भूतमहेश्वरम्।।', 'Fools deride Me when I descend in the human form. They do not know My transcendental nature and My supreme dominion over all that be.'),
(361, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 12, 'मोगाशा मोगकर्माणो मोगज्ञाना विचेतस:। राक्षसीमासुरीं चैव प्रकृतिं मोहिनीं श्रिता:।।', 'Those who are thus bewildered are attracted by demonic and atheistic views. In that deluded state, their hopes for liberation, their fruitive activities, and their culture of knowledge are all defeated.'),
(362, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 13, 'महात्मानस्तु मां पार्थ दैवीं प्रकृतिमाश्रिता:। भजन्त्यनन्यमनसो ज्ञात्वा भूतादिमव्ययम्।।', 'But the great souls, O son of Pritha, who are under the protection of the divine nature, engage themselves fully in My devotional service, because they know Me as the Supreme Personality of Godhead, original and inexhaustible.'),
(363, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 14, 'सततं कीर्तयन्तो मां यतन्तश्च दृढव्रता:। नमस्यन्तश्च मां भक्त्या नित्ययुक्ता उपासते।।', 'Always chanting My glories, endeavoring with great determination, and bowing down before Me, these great souls perpetually worship Me with devotion.'),
(364, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 15, 'ज्ञानयज्ञेन चाप्यन्ये यजन्तो मामुपासते। एकत्वेन पृथक्त्वेन बहुधा विश्वतोमुखम्।।', 'Others, who engage in sacrifice by the cultivation of knowledge, worship the Supreme Lord as the one without a second, as diverse in many, and in the universal form.'),
(365, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 16, 'अहं क्रतुरहं यज्ञ: स्वधाहमहमौषधम्। मन्त्रोऽहमहमेवाज्यमहमग्निरहं हुतम्।।', 'I am the ritual, I am the sacrifice, I am the offering to the ancestors, I am the healing herb, I am the transcendental chant, I am the butter, I am the fire, and I am the offering.'),
(366, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 17, 'पिताहमस्य जगतो माता धाता पितामह:। वेद्यं पवित्रमोङ्कार ऋक्साम यजुरेव च।।', 'I am the father of this universe, the mother, the support, and the grandsire. I am the object of knowledge, the purifier, and the syllable Om. I am also the Rig, the Sama, and the Yajur Vedas.'),
(367, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 18, 'गतिर्भर्ता प्रभु: साक्षी निवास: शरणं सुहृत्। प्रभव: प्रलय: स्थानं निधानं बीजमव्ययम्।।', 'I am the goal, the sustainer, the master, the witness, the abode, the refuge, and the most dear friend. I am the creation and the annihilation, the basis of everything, the resting place, and the eternal seed.'),
(368, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 19, 'तपाम्यहमहं वर्षं निगृह्णम्युत्सृजामि च। अमृतं चैव मृत्युश्च सदसच्चाहमर्जुन।।', 'I give heat, and I withhold and send forth the rain. I am immortality, and I am death personified. Both being and nonbeing are in Me, O Arjuna.'),
(369, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 20, 'त्रैविद्या मां सोमपाः पूतपापा यज्ञैरिष्ट्वा स्वर्गतिं प्रार्थयन्ते। ते पुण्यमासाद्य सुरेन्द्रलोकमश्नन्ति दिव्यान्दिवि देवभोगान्।।', 'Those who study the Vedas and drink the soma juice, seeking the heavenly planets, worship Me indirectly. They take birth on the planet of Indra, where they enjoy godly delights.'),
(370, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 21, 'ते तं भुक्त्वा स्वर्गलोकं विशालं क्षीणे पुण्ये मर्त्यलोकं विशन्ति। एव त्रयीधर्ममनुप्रपन्ना गतागतं कामकामा लभन्ते।।', 'When they have thus enjoyed heavenly sense pleasure and their merit is exhausted, they return to the mortal world. Thus, those who seek sense enjoyment by adhering to the principles of the three Vedas achieve only repeated birth and death.'),
(371, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 22, 'अनन्याश्चिन्तयन्तो मां ये जना: पर्युपासते। तेषां नित्याभियुक्तानां योगक्षेमं वहाम्यहम्।।', 'But those who always worship Me with exclusive devotion, meditating on My transcendental form—to them, I carry what they lack, and I preserve what they have.'),
(372, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 23, 'येऽप्यन्यदेवता भक्ता यजन्ते श्रद्धयान्विता:। तेऽपि मामेव कौन्तेय यजन्त्यविधिपूर्वकम्।।', 'Those who are devotees of other gods and who worship them with faith actually worship only Me, O son of Kunti, but they do so in a wrong way.'),
(373, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 24, 'अहं हि सर्वयज्ञानां भोक्ता च प्रभुरेव च। न तु मामभिजानन्ति तत्त्वेनातश्च्यवन्ति ते।।', 'I am the only enjoyer and master of all sacrifices. Therefore, those who do not recognize My true transcendental nature fall down.'),
(374, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 25, 'यान्ति देवव्रता देवान्पितॄन्यान्ति पितृव्रता:। भूतानि यान्ति भूतेज्या यान्ति मद्याजिनोऽपि माम्।।', 'Those who worship the demigods will take birth among the demigods; those who worship the ancestors go to the ancestors; those who worship ghosts and spirits will take birth among such beings; and those who worship Me will live with Me.'),
(375, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 26, 'पत्रं पुष्पं फलं तोयं यो मे भक्त्या प्रयच्छति। तदहं भक्त्युपहृतमश्नामि प्रयतात्मन:।।', 'If one offers Me with love and devotion a leaf, a flower, fruit, or water, I will accept it.'),
(376, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 27, 'यत्करोषि यदश्नासि यज्जुहोषि ददासि यत्। यत्तपस्यसि कौन्तेय तत्कुरुष्व मदर्पणम्।।', 'Whatever you do, whatever you eat, whatever you offer or give away, and whatever austerities you perform—do that, O son of Kunti, as an offering to Me.'),
(377, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 28, 'शुभाशुभफलैरेवं मोक्ष्यसे कर्मबन्धनै:। संन्यासयोगयुक्तात्मा विमुक्तो मामुपैष्यसि।।', 'In this way, you will be freed from bondage to work and its auspicious and inauspicious results. With your mind fixed on Me in this principle of renunciation, you will be liberated and come to Me.'),
(378, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 29, 'समोऽहं सर्वभूतेषु न मे द्वेष्योऽस्ति न प्रिय:। ये भजन्ति तु मां भक्त्या मयि ते तेषु चाप्यहम्।।', 'I envy no one, nor am I partial to anyone. I am equal to all. But whoever renders service unto Me in devotion is a friend, is in Me, and I am also a friend to him.'),
(379, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 30, 'अपि चेत्सुदुराचारो भजते मामनन्यभाक्। साधुरेव स मन्तव्य: सम्यग्व्यवसितो हि स:।।', 'Even if one commits the most abominable action, if he is engaged in devotional service, he is to be considered saintly because he is properly situated.'),
(380, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 31, 'क्षिप्रं भवति धर्मात्मा शश्वच्छान्तिं निगच्छति। कौन्तेय प्रतिजानीहि न मे भक्त: प्रणश्यति।।', 'He quickly becomes righteous and attains lasting peace. O son of Kunti, declare it boldly that My devotee never perishes.'),
(381, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 32, 'मां हि पार्थ व्यपाश्रित्य येऽपि स्यु: पापयोनय:। स्त्रियो वैश्यास्तथा शूद्रास्तेऽपि यान्ति परां गतिम्।।', 'O son of Pritha, those who take shelter in Me, though they be of lower birth—women, vaisyas [merchants], as well as sudras [workers]—can approach the supreme destination.'),
(382, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 33, 'किं पुनर्ब्राह्मणा: पुण्या भक्ता राजर्षयस्तथा। अनित्यमसुखं लोकमिमं प्राप्य भजस्व माम्।।', 'How much more this is so of the righteous Brahmanas, the devotees, and the saintly kings who seek shelter in Me! Therefore, having come to this temporary, miserable world, engage in loving service to Me.'),
(383, 9, 'Raja Vidya Raja Guhya Yoga', 34, 'मन्मना भव मद्भक्तो मद्याजी मां नमस्कुरु। मामेवैष्यसि युक्त्वैवमात्मानं मत्परायण:।।', 'Engage your mind always in thinking of Me, offer obeisances and worship Me. Being completely absorbed in Me, surely you will come to Me.'),
(384, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | भूय एव महाबाहो शृणु मे परमं वच:। यत्तेऽहं प्रीयमाणाय वक्ष्यामि हितकाम्यया।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Listen again, O mighty-armed Arjuna. Because you are My dear friend, I shall speak to you further, giving knowledge that is better than what I have already explained.'),
(385, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 2, 'न मे विदु: सुरगणा: प्रभवं न महर्षय:। अहमादिर्हि देवानां महर्षीणां च सर्वश:।।', 'Neither the hosts of demigods nor the great sages know My origin, for in every way I am the source of the demigods and sages.'),
(386, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 3, 'यो मामजमनादिं च वेत्ति लोकमहेश्वरम्। असम्मूढ: स मर्त्येषु सर्वपापै: प्रमुच्यते।।', 'One who knows Me as unborn and beginningless, as the supreme Lord of all the worlds, is not deluded and is freed from all sins.'),
(387, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 4, 'बुद्धिर्ज्ञानमसम्मोह: क्षमा सत्यं दम: शम:। सुखं दुःखं भवोऽभावो भयं चाभयमेव च।।', 'Intelligence, knowledge, freedom from doubt, forgiveness, truthfulness, control of the senses, calmness, happiness, distress, birth, death, fear, fearlessness—these are created by Me alone.'),
(388, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 5, 'अहिंसा समता तुष्टिस्तपो दानं यशोऽयश:। भवन्ति भावा भूतानां मत्त एव पृथग्विधा:।।', 'Nonviolence, equanimity, contentment, austerity, charity, fame, and infamy—all these various qualities of living beings arise from Me alone.'),
(389, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 6, 'महर्षय: सप्त पूर्वे चत्वारो मनवस्तथा। मद्भावा मानसा जाता येषां लोक इमाः प्रजा:।।', 'The seven great sages and the four Manus of old, whose descendants populate the world, were born from My mind and come forth from Me.'),
(390, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 7, 'एतां विभूतिं योगं च मम यो वेत्ति तत्त्वत:। सोऽविकम्पेन योगेन युज्यते नात्र संशय:।।', 'One who is factually convinced of this opulence and mystic power of Mine engages in unalloyed devotional service. Of this, there is no doubt.'),
(391, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 8, 'अहं सर्वस्य प्रभवो मत्त: सर्वं प्रवर्तते। इति मत्वा भजन्ते मां बुधा भावसमन्विता:।।', 'I am the source of all spiritual and material worlds. Everything emanates from Me. The wise, who perfectly know this, engage in My devotional service and worship Me with all their hearts.'),
(392, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 9, 'मच्चित्ता मद्गतप्राणा बोधयन्त: परस्परम्। कथयन्तश्च मां नित्यं तुष्यन्ति च रमन्ति च।।', 'The thoughts of My devotees dwell in Me, their lives are surrendered to Me, and they derive great satisfaction and bliss by enlightening one another and conversing about Me.'),
(393, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 10, 'तेषां सततयुक्तानां भजतां प्रीतिपूर्वकम्। ददामि बुद्धियोगं तं येन मामुपयान्ति ते।।', 'To those who are constantly devoted to serving Me with love, I give the understanding by which they can come to Me.'),
(394, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 11, 'तेषामेवानुकम्पार्थमहमज्ञानजं तम:। नाशयाम्यात्मभावस्थो ज्ञानदीपेन भास्वता।।', 'To show them special mercy, I, dwelling in their hearts, destroy with the shining lamp of knowledge the darkness born of ignorance.'),
(395, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 12, 'अर्जुन उवाच | परं ब्रह्म परं धाम पवित्रं परमं भवान्। पुरुषं शाश्वतं दिव्यमादिदेवमजं विभुम्।।', 'Arjuna said: You are the Supreme Brahman, the ultimate abode, the purest, the Absolute Truth. You are the eternal, divine person, the primal God, unborn and omnipresent.'),
(396, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 13, 'आहुस्त्वामृषय: सर्वे देवर्षिर्नारदस्तथा। असितो देवलो व्यास: स्वयं चैव ब्रवीषि मे।।', 'All the great sages, such as Narada, Asita, Devala, and Vyasa, proclaim this of You, and now You Yourself are declaring it to me.'),
(397, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 14, 'सर्वमेतदृतं मन्ये यन्मां वदसि केशव। न हि ते भगवन्व्यक्तिं विदुर्देवा न दानवा:।।', 'O Krishna, I totally accept as truth all that You have told me. Neither the gods nor the demons, O Lord, know Thy personality.'),
(398, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 15, 'स्वयमेवात्मनात्मानं वेत्थ त्वं पुरुषोत्तम। भूतभावन भूतेश देवदेव जगत्पते।।', 'Indeed, You alone know Yourself by Yourself, O Supreme Person, origin of all, Lord of all beings, God of gods, and Lord of the universe.'),
(399, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 16, 'वक्तुमर्हस्यशेषेण दिव्या ह्यात्मविभूतय:। याभिर्विभूतिभिर्लोकानिमांस्त्वं व्याप्य तिष्ठसि।।', 'Please describe in detail Your divine opulences by which You pervade all these worlds and abide in them.'),
(400, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 17, 'कथं विद्यामहं योगिंस्त्वां सदा पर्युपासते। केषु केषु च भावेषु चिन्त्योऽसि भगवन्मया।।', 'How should I meditate on You? In what various forms are You to be contemplated, O Blessed Lord?'),
(401, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 18, 'विस्तरेणात्मनो योगं विभूतिं च जनार्दन। भूय: कथय तृप्तिर्हि शृण्वतो नास्ति मेऽमृतम्।।', 'O Janardana, again please describe in detail the mystic power of Your opulences. I am never satiated in hearing about You, for the nectar of Your words is delightful.'),
(402, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 19, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | हन्त ते कथयिष्यामि दिव्या ह्यात्मविभूतय:। प्राधान्यत: कुरुश्रेष्ठ नास्त्यन्तो विस्तरस्य मे।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Yes, I will tell you of My splendorous manifestations, but only of those which are prominent, O best of the Kurus, for My opulence is limitless.'),
(403, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 20, 'अहमात्मा गुडाकेश सर्वभूताशयस्थित:। अहमादिश्च मध्यं च भूतानामन्त एव च।।', 'I am the Self, O Gudakesha, seated in the hearts of all creatures. I am the beginning, the middle, and the end of all beings.'),
(404, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 21, 'आदित्यानामहं विष्णुर्ज्योतिषां रविरंशुमान्। मरीचिर्मरुतामस्मि नक्षत्राणामहं शशी।।', 'Of the Adityas, I am Vishnu; of lights, I am the radiant sun; of the Maruts, I am Marichi; and among the stars, I am the moon.'),
(405, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 22, 'वेदानां सामवेदोऽस्मि देवानामस्मि वासव:। इन्द्रियाणां मनश्चास्मि भूतानामस्मि चेतना।।', 'Of the Vedas, I am the Sama Veda; of the demigods, I am Indra; of the senses, I am the mind; and in living beings, I am the living force [consciousness].'),
(406, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 23, 'रुद्राणां शङ्करश्चास्मि वित्तेशो यक्षरक्षसाम्। वसूनां पावकश्चास्मि मेरु: शिखरिणामहम्।।', 'Of all the Rudras, I am Lord Shiva; of the Yakshas and Rakshasas, I am the lord of wealth [Kubera]; of the Vasus, I am fire [Agni]; and of mountains, I am Meru.'),
(407, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 24, 'पुरोधसां च मुख्यं मां विद्धि पार्थ बृहस्पतिम्। सेनानीनामहं स्कन्द: सरसामस्मि सागर:।।', 'Of priests, O Arjuna, know Me to be the chief, Brihaspati. Of generals, I am Kartikeya, and of bodies of water, I am the ocean.'),
(408, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 25, 'महर्षीणां भृगुरहं गिरामस्म्येकमक्षरम्। यज्ञानां जपयज्ञोऽस्मि स्थावराणां हिमालय:।।', 'Of the great sages, I am Bhrigu; of vibrations, I am the transcendental Om. Of sacrifices, I am the chanting of the holy names [japa], and of immovable things, I am the Himalayas.'),
(409, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 26, 'अश्वत्थ: सर्ववृक्षाणां देवर्षीणां च नारद:। गन्धर्वाणां चित्ररथ: सिद्धानां कपिलो मुनि:।।', 'Of all trees, I am the banyan tree; of the sages among the demigods, I am Narada; of the Gandharvas, I am Chitraratha, and among perfected beings, I am the sage Kapila.'),
(410, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 27, 'उच्चै:श्रवसमश्वानां विद्धि माममृतोद्भवम्। ऐरावतं गजेन्द्राणां नराणां च नराधिपम्।।', 'Of horses, know Me to be Uchchaihshravas, produced during the churning of the ocean for nectar; of lordly elephants, I am Airavata; and among men, I am the monarch.'),
(411, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 28, 'आयुधानामहं वज्रं धेनूनामस्मि कामधुक्। प्रजनश्चास्मि कन्दर्प: सर्पाणामस्मि वासुकि:।।', 'Of weapons, I am the thunderbolt; among cows, I am the Surabhi. Of causes for procreation, I am Kandarpa, the god of love, and of serpents, I am Vasuki.'),
(412, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 29, 'अनन्तश्चास्मि नागानां वरुणो यादसामहम्। पितॄणामर्यमा चास्मि यम: संयमतामहम्।।', 'Of the celestial Naga snakes, I am Ananta; of aquatic beings, I am Varuna. Of departed ancestors, I am Aryama, and among dispensers of law, I am Yama, the lord of death.'),
(413, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 30, 'प्रह्लादश्चास्मि दैत्यानां काल: कलयतामहम्। मृगाणां च मृगेन्द्रोऽहं वैनतेयश्च पक्षिणाम्।।', 'Among the Daityas, I am Prahlada; among subduers, I am time; among beasts, I am the lion, and among birds, I am Garuda.'),
(414, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 31, 'पवन: पवतामस्मि राम: शस्त्रभृतामहम्। झषाणां मकरश्चास्मि स्रोतसामस्मि जाह्नवी।।', 'Of purifiers, I am the wind; of the wielders of weapons, I am Rama. Of fishes, I am the shark, and of flowing rivers, I am the Ganges.'),
(415, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 32, 'सर्गाणामादिरन्तश्च मध्यं चैवाहमर्जुन। अध्यात्मविद्या विद्यानां वाद: प्रवदतामहम्।।', 'Of all creations, I am the beginning, the end, and the middle, O Arjuna. Of all sciences, I am the spiritual science of the self, and among logicians, I am the conclusive truth.'),
(416, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 33, 'अक्षराणामकारोऽस्मि द्वन्द्व: सामासिकस्य च। अहमेवाक्षय: कालो धाताहं विश्वतोमुख:।।', 'Of letters, I am the letter A, and among compounds, I am the dual word. I am also inexhaustible time, and of creators, I am Brahma.'),
(417, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 34, 'मृत्यु: सर्वहरश्चाहमुद्भवश्च भविष्यताम्। कीर्ति: श्रीर्वाक्च नारीणां स्मृतिर्मेधा धृति: क्षमा।।', 'I am all-devouring death, and I am the generating principle of all that is yet to be. Among women, I am fame, fortune, speech, memory, intelligence, faithfulness, and patience.'),
(418, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 35, 'बृहसाम तथा साम्नां गायत्री छन्दसामहम्। मासानां मार्गशीर्षोऽहमृतूनां कुसुमाकर:।।', 'Of the hymns in the Sama Veda, I am the Brihat-sama, and of poetry, I am the Gayatri. Of months, I am Margashirsha [November–December], and of seasons, I am flower-bearing spring.'),
(419, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 36, 'द्यूतं छलयतामस्मि तेजस्तेजस्विनामहम्। जयोऽस्मि व्यवसायोऽस्मि सत्त्वं सत्त्ववतामहम्।।', 'I am the gambling of cheats, and of the splendid, I am the splendor. I am victory, I am adventure, and I am the strength of the strong.'),
(420, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 37, 'वृष्णीनां वासुदेवोऽस्मि पाण्डवानां धनंजय:। मुनीनामप्यहं व्यास: कवीनामुशना कवि:।।', 'Of the Vrishnis, I am Vasudeva, and of the Pandavas, I am Arjuna. Of the sages, I am Vyasa, and among great thinkers, I am Ushanas.'),
(421, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 38, 'दण्डो दमयतामस्मि नीतिरस्मि जिगीषताम्। मौनं चैवास्मि गुह्यानां ज्ञानं ज्ञानवतामहम्।।', 'Among all means of suppressing lawlessness, I am punishment, and of those who seek victory, I am morality. Of secret things, I am silence, and of the wise, I am wisdom.'),
(422, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 39, 'यच्चापि सर्वभूतानां बीजं तदहमर्जुन। न तदस्ति विना यत्स्यान्मया भूतं चराचरम्।।', 'Furthermore, O Arjuna, I am the generating seed of all existences. There is no being—moving or unmoving—that can exist without Me.'),
(423, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 40, 'नान्तोऽस्ति मम दिव्यानां विभूतीनां परन्तप। एष तूद्देशतः प्रोक्तो विभूतेर्विस्तरो मया।।', 'O conqueror of enemies, there is no end to My divine manifestations. What I have spoken to you is but a mere indication of My infinite opulences.'),
(424, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 41, 'यद्यद्विभूतिमत्सत्वं श्रीमदूरिजितमेव वा। तत्देवावगच्छ त्वं मम तेजोंऽशसम्भवम्।।', 'Know that all opulent, beautiful, and glorious creations spring from but a spark of My splendor.'),
(425, 10, 'Vibhuti Yoga', 42, 'अथवा बहुनैतेन किं ज्ञातेन तवार्जुन। विष्टभ्याहमिदं कृत्स्नमेकांशेन स्थितो जगत्।।', 'But what need is there, Arjuna, for all this detailed knowledge? With a single fragment of Myself, I pervade and support this entire universe.'),
(426, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | मदनुग्रहाय परमं गुह्यमध्यात्मसञ्ज्ञितम्। यत्वयोक्तं वचस्तेन मोहोऽयं विगतो मम।।', 'Arjuna said: By my hearing the instructions You have kindly given me about these most confidential spiritual subjects, my illusion has now been dispelled.'),
(427, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 2, 'भवाप्ययौ हि भूतानां श्रुतौ विस्तरशो मया। त्वत्त: कमलपत्राक्ष माहात्म्यमपि चाव्ययम्।।', 'O lotus-eyed one, I have heard from You in detail about the appearance and disappearance of every living entity, as realized through Your inexhaustible glories.'),
(428, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 3, 'एवमेतद्यथात्थ त्वमात्मानं परमेश्वर। द्रष्टुमिच्छामि ते रूपमैश्वरं पुरुषोत्तम।।', 'O greatest of all personalities, O supreme form, though I see here before me Your actual position, I wish to see how You have entered into this cosmic manifestation. I want to see that form of Yours.'),
(429, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 4, 'मन्यसे यदि तच्छक्यं मया द्रष्टुमिति प्रभो। योगेश्वर ततो मे त्वं दर्शयात्मानमव्ययम्।।', 'If You think that I am able to behold Your cosmic form, O my Lord, O master of all mystic power, then kindly show me that unlimited universal Self.'),
(430, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 5, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | पश्य मे पार्थ रूपाणि शतशोऽथ सहस्रश:। नानाविधानि दिव्यानि नानावर्णाकृतीनि च।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: My dear Arjuna, O son of Pritha, behold now My opulences, hundreds of thousands of varied divine and multicolored forms.'),
(431, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 6, 'पश्यादित्यान्वसून्रुद्रानश्विनौ मरुतस्तथा। बहून्यदृष्टपूर्वाणि पश्याश्चर्याणि भारत।।', 'O best of the Bharatas, see here the different manifestations of Adityas, Vasus, Rudras, Ashvins, and Maruts. Behold many wonderful things that no one has ever seen or heard of before.'),
(432, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 7, 'इहैकस्थं जगत्कृत्स्नं पश्याद्य सचराचरम्। मम देहे गुडाकेश यच्चान्यद्द्रष्टुमिच्छसि।।', 'O Gudakesha, see here, within My body, the whole universe, including the moving and the nonmoving, and whatever else you wish to see.'),
(433, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 8, 'न तु मां शक्यसे द्रष्टुमनेनैव स्वचक्षुषा। दिव्यं ददामि ते चक्षु: पश्य मे योगमैश्वरम्।।', 'But you cannot see Me with your present eyes. Therefore, I give you divine eyes. Behold My mystic opulence!'),
(434, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 9, 'सञ्जय उवाच | एवमुक्त्वा ततो राजन्महायोगेश्वरो हरि:। दर्शयामास पार्थाय परमं रूपमैश्वरम्।।', 'Sanjaya said: O King, having spoken thus, the Supreme Lord of all mystic power, the Personality of Godhead, displayed His universal form to Arjuna.'),
(435, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 10, 'अनेकवक्त्रनयनमनेकाद्भुतदर्शनम्। अनेकदिव्याभरणं दिव्यानेकोद्यतायुधम्।।', 'Arjuna saw in that universal form unlimited mouths, unlimited eyes, unlimited wonderful visions. The form was decorated with many celestial ornaments and bore many divine upraised weapons.'),
(436, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 11, 'दिव्यमाल्याम्बरधरं दिव्यगन्धानुलेपनम्। सर्वाश्चर्यमयं देवमनन्तं विश्वतोमुखम्।।', 'He wore celestial garlands and garments, and many divine scents were smeared over His body. All was wondrous, brilliant, unlimited, and all-expanding.'),
(437, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 12, 'दिवि सूर्यसहस्रस्य भवेद्युगपदुत्थिता। यदि भा: सदृशी सा स्याद्भासस्तस्य महात्मन:।।', 'If hundreds of thousands of suns were to rise at once into the sky, their radiance might resemble the effulgence of the Supreme Person in that universal form.'),
(438, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 13, 'तत्रैकस्थं जगत्कृत्स्नं प्रविभक्तमनेकधा। अपश्यद्देवदेवस्य शरीरे पाण्डवस्तदा।।', 'At that time Arjuna could see in the universal form of the Lord the unlimited expansions of the universe situated in one place, although divided into many, many thousands.'),
(439, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 14, 'ततो विभयविष्टात्मा धनंजय: प्रणम्य च। शशाक प्रणम्य केशवं कृताञ्जलिरभाषत।।', 'Then, bewildered and astonished, his hair standing on end, Arjuna bowed his head to offer obeisance and with folded hands began to pray to the Supreme Lord.'),
(440, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 15, 'अर्जुन उवाच | पश्यामि देवांस्तव देव देहे सर्वांस्तथा भूतविशेषसङ्घान्। ब्रह्माणमीशं कमलासनस्थमृषींश्च सर्वानुरगांश्च दिव्यान्।।', 'Arjuna said: My dear Lord Krishna, I see assembled in Your body all the demigods and various other living entities. I see Brahma sitting on the lotus flower as well as Lord Shiva and all the sages and divine serpents.'),
(441, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 15, 'अर्जुन उवाच | पश्यामि देवांस्तव देव देहे सर्वांस्तथा भूतविशेषसङ्घान्। ब्रह्माणमीशं कमलासनस्थमृषींश्च सर्वानुरगांश्च दिव्यान्।।', 'Arjuna said: My dear Lord Krishna, I see assembled in Your body all the demigods and various other living entities. I see Brahma sitting on the lotus flower as well as Lord Shiva and all the sages and divine serpents.'),
(442, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 16, 'अनेकबाहूदरवक्त्रनेत्रं पश्यामि त्वां सर्वतोऽनन्तरूपम्। नान्तं न मध्यं न पुनस्तवादिं पश्यामि विश्वेश्वर विश्वरूप।।', 'O Lord of the universe, O universal form, I see in Your body many, many arms, bellies, mouths, and eyes expanded everywhere, without limit. I see no end, no middle, and no beginning to You.'),
(443, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 17, 'किरीटिनं गदिनं चक्रिणं च तेजोराशिं सर्वतो दीप्तिमन्तम्। पश्यामि त्वां दुर्निरीक्ष्यं समन्ताद्दीप्तानलार्कद्युतिमप्रमेयम्।।', 'Your form is difficult to see because of its glaring effulgence, spreading on all sides like blazing fire or the immeasurable radiance of the sun. Yet I see this glowing form everywhere, adorned with various crowns, clubs, and discs.'),
(444, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 18, 'त्वमक्षरं परमं वेदितव्यं त्वमस्य विश्वस्य परं निधानम्। त्वमव्यय: शाश्वतधर्मगोप्ता सनातनस्त्वं पुरुषो मतो मे।।', 'You are the supreme primal objective. You are the ultimate resting place of all this universe. You are inexhaustible, and You are the protector of the eternal religion, the Personality of Godhead. This is my opinion.'),
(445, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 19, 'अनादिमध्यान्तमनन्तवीर्यमनन्तबाहुं शशिसूर्यनेत्रम्। पश्यामि त्वां दीप्तहुताशवक्त्रं स्वतेजसा विश्वमिदं तपन्तम्।।', 'You are without origin, middle, or end. Your glory is unlimited. You have countless arms, and the sun and moon are Your eyes. I see You with blazing fire coming forth from Your mouth, burning this entire universe by Your own radiance.'),
(446, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 20, 'द्यावापृथिव्योरिदमन्तरं हि व्याप्तं त्वयैकेन दिशश्च सर्वा:। दृष्ट्वाद्भुतं रूपमुग्रं तवेदं लोकत्रयं प्रव्यथितं महात्मन्।।', 'Although You are one, You spread throughout the sky and the planets and all space between. O great one, seeing this wondrous and terrible form, all the planetary systems are perturbed.'),
(447, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 21, 'अमी हि त्वां सुरसङ्घा विशन्ति केचिद्भीता: प्राञ्जलयो गृणन्ति। स्वस्तीत्युक्त्वा महर्षिसिद्धसङ्घा: स्तुवन्ति त्वां स्तुतिभि: पुष्कलाभि:।।', 'All the demigods are surrendering before You and entering into You. They are very much afraid, and with folded hands, they are singing the Vedic hymns.'),
(448, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 22, 'रुद्रादित्या वसवो ये च साध्या विश्वेऽश्विनौ मरुतश्चोष्मपाश्च। गन्धर्वयक्षासुरसिद्धसङ्घा वीक्षन्ते त्वां विस्मिताश्चैव सर्वे।।', 'The Rudras, Adityas, Vasus, Sadhyas, Vishvadevas, the two Ashvins, Maruts, ancestors, Gandharvas, Yakshas, Asuras, and perfected demigods are beholding You in wonder.'),
(449, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 23, 'रूपं महत्ते बहुवक्त्रनेत्रं महाबाहो बहुबाहूरुपादम्। बहूदरं बहुदंष्ट्राकरालं दृष्ट्वा लोकाः प्रव्यथितास्तथाहम्।।', 'O mighty-armed one, seeing this great form of Yours, with its many faces, eyes, arms, thighs, legs, and bellies, and its many terrible teeth, the worlds are terrified, and so am I.'),
(450, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 24, 'नभ:स्पृशं दीप्तमनेकवर्णं व्याताननं दीप्तविशालनेत्रम्। दृष्ट्वा हि त्वां प्रव्यथितान्तरात्मा धृतिं न विन्दामि शमं च विष्णो।।', 'O Vishnu, seeing You with Your many radiant colors touching the sky, Your gaping mouths, and Your great glowing eyes, my mind is perturbed by fear. I can no longer maintain my steadiness or equilibrium.'),
(451, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 25, 'दंष्ट्राकरालानि च ते मुखानि दृष्ट्वैव कालानलसन्निभानि। दिशो न जाने न लभे च शर्म प्रसीद देवेश जगन्निवास।।', 'O Lord of lords, O refuge of the worlds, please be gracious to me. I cannot keep my balance seeing thus Your blazing deathlike faces and awful teeth. In all directions I am bewildered.'),
(452, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 26, 'अमी च त्वां धृतराष्ट्रस्य पुत्राः सर्वे सहैवावनिपालसङ्घैः। भीष्मो द्रोणः सूतपुत्रस्तथासौ सहास्मदीयैरपि योधमुख्यैः।।', 'All the sons of Dhritarashtra along with their allied kings, and Bhishma, Drona, Karna, and our chief soldiers are rushing into Your fearful mouths.'),
(453, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 27, 'वक्त्राणि ते त्वरमाणा विशन्ति दंष्ट्राकरालानि भयानकानि। केचिद्विलग्ना दशनान्तरेषु संदृश्यन्ते चूर्णितैरुत्तमाङ्गैः।।', 'I see all people rushing full speed into Your mouths as moths dash to destruction in a blazing fire.'),
(454, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 28, 'यथा नदीनां बहवोऽम्बुवेगा: समुद्रमेवाभिमुखा द्रवन्ति। तथा तवामी नरलोकवीरा विशन्ति वक्त्राण्यभिविज्वलन्ति।।', 'As the many waves of the rivers flow into the ocean, so do all these great warriors enter blazing into Your mouths.'),
(455, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 29, 'यथा प्रदीप्तं ज्वलनं पतङ्गा विशन्ति नाशाय समृद्धवेगा:। तथैव नाशाय विशन्ति लोकास्तवापि वक्त्राणि समृद्धवेगा:।।', 'I see people entering Your mouths with great speed, as moths rush with full speed into a blazing fire.'),
(456, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 30, 'लेलिह्यसे ग्रसमान: समन्ताल्लोकान्समग्रान्वदनैर्ज्वलद्भि:। तेजोभिरापूर्य जगत्समग्रं भासस्तवोग्रा: प्रतपन्ति विष्णो।।', 'O Vishnu, I see You devouring all people from all sides with Your flaming mouths. Covering all the universe with Your effulgence, You are manifest with terrible, scorching rays.'),
(457, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 31, 'आख्याहि मे को भवानुग्ररूपो नमोऽस्तु ते देववर प्रसीद। विज्ञातुमिच्छामि भवन्तमाद्यं न हि प्रजानामि तव प्रवृत्तिम्।।', 'Who are You in this fierce form, O Lord? I offer my obeisances unto You. Please be gracious to me. I do not understand Your mission, and I desire to know You, the primal Being.'),
(458, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 32, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | कालोऽस्मि लोकक्षयकृत्प्रवृद्धो लोकान्समाहर्तुमिह प्रवृत्त:। ऋतेऽपि त्वां न भविष्यन्ति सर्वे येऽवस्थिताः प्रत्यनीकेषु योधा:।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Time I am, the great destroyer of the worlds, and I have come here to destroy all people. With the exception of you [the Pandavas], all the soldiers here on both sides will be slain.'),
(459, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 33, 'तस्मात्त्वमुत्तिष्ठ यशो लभस्व जित्वा शत्रून्भुङ्क्ष्व राज्यं समृद्धम्। मयैवैते निहता: पूर्वमेव निमित्तमात्रं भव सव्यसाचिन्।।', 'Therefore, get up. Prepare to fight and win glory. Conquer your enemies and enjoy a flourishing kingdom. They are already put to death by My arrangement, and you, O Savyasachi, can be but an instrument in the fight.'),
(460, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 34, 'द्रोणं च भीष्मं च जयद्रथं च कर्णं तथान्यानपि योधवीरान्। मया हता: त्वं जहि मा व्यथिष्ठा युध्यस्व जेतासि रणे सपत्नान्।।', 'Drona, Bhishma, Jayadratha, Karna, and other brave warriors have already been killed by Me. Therefore, kill them without being disturbed. Simply fight, and you will vanquish your enemies in battle.'),
(461, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 35, 'सञ्जय उवाच | एतच्छ्रुत्वा वचनं केशवस्य कृताञ्जलिर्वेपमान: किरीटी। नमस्कृत्वा भूय एवाह कृष्णं सगद्गदं भीतभीत: प्रणम्य।।', 'Sanjaya said: Hearing these words from the Supreme Personality of Godhead, Arjuna trembled, fearfully offered obeisances with folded hands, and began to speak with a faltering voice, bowing down again and again.'),
(462, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 36, 'अर्जुन उवाच | स्थाने हृषीकेश तव प्रकीर्त्या जगत्प्रहृष्यत्यनुरज्यते च। रक्षांसि भीतानि दिशो द्रवन्ति सर्वे नमस्यन्ति च सिद्धसङ्घा:।।', 'Arjuna said: O Hrisikesa, the world becomes joyful upon hearing Your name, and thus everyone becomes attached to You. Although the perfected beings offer You their respectful homage, the demons are afraid, and they flee here and there. All this is rightly done.'),
(463, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 37, 'कस्माच्च ते न नमेरन्महात्मन् गरीयसे ब्रह्मणोऽप्यादिकर्त्रे। अनन्त देवेश जगन्निवास त्वमक्षरं सदसत्तत्परं यत्।।', 'O great one, who are greater even than Brahma, You are the original creator. Why then should they not offer their respectful obeisances unto You? O limitless one, O God of gods, refuge of the universe, You are the invincible source, the cause of all causes, transcendental to this material manifestation.'),
(464, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 38, 'त्वमादिदेव: पुरुष: पुराणस्त्वमस्य विश्वस्य परं निधानम्। वेत्तासि वेद्यं च परं च धाम त्वया ततं विश्वमनन्तरूप।।', 'You are the original Personality, the Godhead. You are the only sanctuary of this manifested cosmic world. You know everything, and You are all that is knowable. You are above the material modes, O limitless form! This whole cosmic manifestation is pervaded by You!'),
(465, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 39, 'वायुर्यमोऽग्निर्वरुण: शशाङ्क: प्रजापतिस्त्वं प्रपितामहश्च। नमो नमस्तेऽस्तु सहस्रकृत्व: पुनश्च भूयोऽपि नमो नमस्ते।।', 'You are air, and You are the supreme controller! You are fire, You are water, and You are the moon! You are Brahma, the first living creature, and You are the great-grandfather. I therefore offer my respectful obeisances unto You again and again! A thousand times, and again and yet again!'),
(466, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 40, 'नम: पुरस्तादथ पृष्ठतस्ते नमोऽस्तु ते सर्वत एव सर्व। अनन्तवीर्यामितविक्रमं त्वां सर्वं समाप्नोषि ततोऽसि सर्व:।।', 'Obeisances to You from the front, from behind, and from all sides! O unbounded power, You are the master of limitless might! You are all-pervading, and thus You are everything!'),
(467, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 41, 'सखेति मत्वा प्रसभं यदुक्तं हे कृष्ण हे यादव हे सखेति। अजानता महिमानं तवेदं मया प्रमादात्प्रणयेन वापि।।', 'Thinking of You as my friend, I have rashly addressed You “O Krishna,” “O Yadava,” “O my friend,” not knowing Your glories. Please forgive whatever I may have done in madness or in love.'),
(468, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 42, 'यच्चावहासार्थमसत्कृतोऽसि विहारशय्यासनभोजनेषु। एकोऽथवाप्यच्युत तत्समक्षं तत्क्षामये त्वामहमप्रमेयम्।।', 'I have dishonored You many times while we were relaxing, lying on the same bed, or eating together, sometimes alone and sometimes in front of many friends. O infallible one, please excuse me for all those offenses.'),
(469, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 43, 'पितासि लोकस्य चराचरस्य त्वमस्य पूज्यश्च गुरुरगरीयान्। न त्वत्समोऽस्त्यभ्यधिक: कुतोऽन्यो लोकत्रयेऽप्यप्रतिमप्रभाव।।', 'You are the father of this complete cosmic manifestation, of the moving and the nonmoving. You are its worshipable chief, the supreme spiritual master. No one is equal to You, nor can anyone be one with You. How, then, could there be anyone greater than You within the three worlds, O Lord of immeasurable power?'),
(470, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 44, 'तस्मात्प्रणम्य प्रणिधाय कायं प्रसादये त्वामहमिशमीड्यम्। पितेव पुत्रस्य सखेव सख्यु: प्रिय: प्रियायार्हसि देव सोढुम्।।', 'You are the Supreme Lord, to be worshiped by every living being. Thus I fall down to offer You my respectful obeisances and ask Your mercy. As a father tolerates the impudence of his son, a friend the impertinence of a friend, or a lover the presumption of a beloved, please tolerate the wrongs I may have done You.'),
(471, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 45, 'अदृष्टपूर्वं हृषितोऽस्मि दृष्ट्वा भयेन च प्रव्यथितं मनो मे। तदेव मे दर्शय देवरूपं प्रसन्नभूतो भव देव विश्वम्।।', 'After seeing this universal form, which I have never seen before, I am gladdened, but at the same time my mind is disturbed with fear. Therefore, please bestow Your grace upon me and reveal again Your form as the Personality of Godhead, O Lord of lords, O abode of the universe.'),
(472, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 46, 'किरीटिनं गदिनं चक्रहस्तं इच्छामि त्वां द्रष्टुमहं तथैव। तेनैव रूपेण चतुर्भुजेन सहस्रबाहो भव विश्वमूर्ते।।', 'O universal form, O thousand-armed Lord, I wish to see You in Your four-armed form, with helmeted head and with club, wheel, conch, and lotus flower in Your hands. I long to see You in that form.'),
(473, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 47, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | मया प्रसन्नेन तवार्जुनेदं रूपं परं दर्शितमात्मयोगात्। तेजोमयं विश्वमनन्तमाद्यं यन्मे त्वदन्येन न दृष्टपूर्वम्।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: My dear Arjuna, happily have I shown you, by My internal potency, this supreme universal form within the material world. No one before you has ever seen this unlimited and glaringly effulgent form of Mine.'),
(474, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 48, 'न वेदयज्ञाध्ययनैर्न दानैर्न च क्रियाभिर्न तपोभिरुग्रै:। एवंरूप: शक्य अहं नृलोके द्रष्टुं त्वदन्येन कुरुप्रवीर।।', 'O best of the Kurus, no one before you has ever seen this universal form of Mine, for neither by studying the Vedas nor by performing sacrifices, nor by engaging in charity or similar pious activities, can this form be seen.'),
(475, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 49, 'मा ते व्यथा मा च विमूढभावो दृष्ट्वा रूपं घोरमीदृङ्ममेदम्। व्यपेतभी: प्रीतमना: पुनस्त्वं तदेव मे रूपमिदं प्रपश्य।।', 'You have been perturbed and bewildered by seeing this horrible feature of Mine. Now let it be finished. My devotee, be free from all disturbance. With a peaceful mind, you can now see the form you desire.'),
(476, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 50, 'सञ्जय उवाच | इत्यर्जुनं वासुदेवस्तथोक्त्वा स्वकं रूपं दर्शयामास भूय:। आश्वासयामास च भीतमेनं भूत्वा पुन: सौम्यवपुर्महात्मा।।', 'Sanjaya said: The Supreme Personality of Godhead, Krishna, having spoken thus to Arjuna, displayed His real four-armed form, and at last He showed His two-armed form, thus encouraging the fearful Arjuna.'),
(477, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 51, 'अर्जुन उवाच | दृष्ट्वेदं मानुषं रूपं तव सौम्यं जनार्दन। इदानीमस्मि संवृत्त: सचेताः प्रकृतिं गतः।।', 'When Arjuna thus saw Krishna in His original form, he said: O Janardana, seeing this humanlike form, so very beautiful, I am now composed in mind, and I am restored to my original nature.'),
(478, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 52, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | सुदुर्दर्शमिदं रूपं दृष्टवानसि यन्मम। देवा अप्यस्य रूपस्य नित्यं दर्शनकाङ्क्षिण:।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: My dear Arjuna, this form of Mine you are now seeing is very difficult to behold. Even the demigods are ever seeking the opportunity to see this form, which is so dear.'),
(479, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 53, 'नाहं वेदैर्न तपसा न दानेन न चेज्यया। शक्य एवंविधो द्रष्टुं दृष्टवानसि मां यथा।।', 'The form you are seeing with your transcendental eyes cannot be understood simply by studying the Vedas, nor by undergoing serious penances, nor by charity, nor by worship. It is not by these means that one can see Me as I am.'),
(480, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 54, 'भक्त्या त्वनन्यया शक्य अहमेवंविधोऽर्जुन। ज्ञातुं द्रष्टुं च तत्वेन प्रवेष्टुं च परन्तप।।', 'My dear Arjuna, only by undivided devotional service can I be understood as I am, standing before you, and can thus be seen directly. Only in this way can you enter into the mysteries of My understanding.'),
(481, 11, 'Vishvarupa Darshana Yoga', 55, 'मत्कर्मकृन्मत्परमो मद्भक्त: संगवर्जित:। निर्वैर: सर्वभूतेषु य: स मामेति पाण्डव।।', 'My dear Arjuna, one who is engaged in My pure devotional service, free from the contaminations of previous activities and from mental speculation, who is friendly to every living entity, certainly comes to Me.'),
(482, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | एवं सततयुक्ता ये भक्तास्त्वां पर्युपासते। ये चाप्यक्षरमव्यक्तं तेषां के योगवित्तमा:।।', 'Arjuna said: Those who are ever steadfast, who worship You in devotion, and those who meditate on the imperishable and the unmanifest—which of these has greater knowledge of yoga?'),
(483, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | मय्यावेश्य मनो ये मां नित्ययुक्ता उपासते। श्रद्धया परयोपेतास्ते मे युक्ततमा मता:।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Those who fix their minds on Me and worship Me with steadfast devotion and faith are considered by Me to be the most perfect.'),
(484, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 3, 'ये त्वक्षरमनिर्देश्यमव्यक्तं पर्युपासते। सर्वत्रगमचिन्त्यं च कूटस्थमचलं ध्रुवम्।।', 'But those who fully worship the unmanifested, that which lies beyond the perception of the senses, the all-pervading, inconceivable, unchanging, fixed, and immovable—the impersonal conception of the Absolute Truth—'),
(485, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 4, 'सन्नियम्येन्द्रियग्रामं सर्वत्र समबुद्धय:। ते प्राप्नुवन्ति मामेव सर्वभूतहिते रता:।।', 'By controlling the senses, being equally disposed to everything, and engaged in the welfare of all beings, they also attain Me.'),
(486, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 5, 'क्लेशोऽधिकतरस्तेषामव्यक्तासक्तचेतसाम्। अव्यक्ता हि गतिर्दुःखं देहवद्भिरवाप्यते।।', 'For those whose minds are attached to the unmanifest, impersonal feature of the Supreme, advancement is very troublesome. To make progress in that discipline is always difficult for those who are embodied.'),
(487, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 6, 'ये तु सर्वाणि कर्माणि मयि संन्यस्य मत्परा:। अनन्येनैव योगेन मां ध्यायन्त उपासते।।', 'But those who worship Me, giving up all their activities unto Me and being devoted to Me without deviation, engaged in devotional service and meditating upon Me, having fixed their minds on Me, O son of Pritha—'),
(488, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 7, 'तेषामहं समुद्धर्ता मृत्युसंसारसागरात्। भवामि नचिरात्पार्थ मय्यावेशितचेतसाम्।।', 'For them, whose minds are fixed on Me, I am the swift deliverer from the ocean of birth and death.'),
(489, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 8, 'मय्येव मन आधत्स्व मयि बुद्धिं निवेशय। निवसिष्यसि मय्येव अत ऊर्ध्वं न संशय:।।', 'Just fix your mind upon Me, the Supreme Personality of Godhead, and engage all your intelligence in Me. Thus you will live in Me always, without a doubt.'),
(490, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 9, 'अथ चित्तं समाधातुं न शक्नोषि मयि स्थिरम्। अभ्यासयोगेन ततो मामिच्छाप्तुं धनञ्जय।।', 'My dear Arjuna, if you cannot fix your mind upon Me without deviation, then follow the regulative principles of bhakti-yoga. In this way, you will develop a desire to attain Me.'),
(491, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 10, 'अभ्यासेऽप्यसमर्थोऽसि मत्कर्मपरमो भव। मदर्थमपि कर्माणि कुर्वन्सिद्धिमवाप्स्यसि।।', 'If you cannot practice the regulations of bhakti-yoga, then just try to work for Me. Because by working for Me, you will come to the perfect stage.'),
(492, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 11, 'अथैतदप्यशक्तोऽसि कर्तुं मद्योगमाश्रित:। सर्वकर्मफलत्यागं तत: कुरु यतात्मवान्।।', 'If you cannot take to this practice, then engage yourself in the cultivation of knowledge. Better than knowledge, however, is meditation, and better than meditation is renunciation of the fruits of action, for by such renunciation one can attain peace of mind.'),
(493, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 12, 'श्रेयो हि ज्ञानमभ्यासाज्ज्ञानाद्ध्यानं विशिष्यते। ध्यानात्कर्मफलत्यागस्त्यागाच्छान्तिरनन्तरम्।।', 'Renunciation of the fruits of action is better than meditation, for by renunciation one can attain peace.'),
(494, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 13, 'अद्वेष्टा सर्वभूतानां मैत्र: करुण एव च। निर्ममो निरहङ्कार: समदु:खसुख: क्षमी।।', 'One who is not envious but is a kind friend to all living entities, who does not think himself a proprietor, who is free from false ego and equal in both happiness and distress, tolerant, always satisfied, self-controlled, and engaged in devotional service with determination, his mind and intelligence fixed on Me—such a devotee of Mine is very dear to Me.'),
(495, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 14, 'सन्तुष्ट: सततं योगी यतात्मा दृढनिश्चय:। मय्यर्पितमनोबुद्धिर्यो मद्भक्त: स मे प्रिय:।।', 'He who is always content and self-controlled, who is dedicated with mind and intelligence fixed on Me—such a devotee is very dear to Me.'),
(496, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 15, 'यस्मान्नोद्विजते लोको लोकान्नोद्विजते च य:। हर्षामर्षभयोद्वेगैर्मुक्तो य: स च मे प्रिय:।।', 'He for whom no one is put into difficulty and who is not disturbed by anyone, who is equipoised in happiness and distress, fear and anxiety, is very dear to Me.'),
(497, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 16, 'अनपेक्ष: शुचिर्दक्ष उदासीनो गतव्यथ:। सर्वारम्भपरित्यागी यो मद्भक्त: स मे प्रिय:।।', 'My devotee, who is pure, expert, without cares, free from all pains, and not striving for some result, is very dear to Me.'),
(498, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 17, 'यो न हृष्यति न द्वेष्टि न शोचति न काङ्क्षति। शुभाशुभपरित्यागी भक्तिमान्य: स मे प्रिय:।।', 'One who neither rejoices, nor grieves, nor laments, nor desires, who renounces both auspicious and inauspicious things, is very dear to Me.'),
(499, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 18, 'सम: शत्रौ च मित्रे च तथा मानापमानयो:। शीतोष्णसुखदु:खेषु सम: सङ्गविवर्जित:।।', 'One who is equal to friends and enemies, who is equipoised in honor and dishonor, heat and cold, happiness and distress, fame and infamy, who is always free from contamination, always silent and satisfied with anything, who doesn’t care for any residence, who is fixed in knowledge and engaged in devotional service, is very dear to Me.'),
(500, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 19, 'तुल्यनिन्दास्तुतिर्मौनी सन्तुष्टो येन केनचित्। अनिकेत: स्थिरमतिर्भक्तिमान्मे प्रियो नर:।।', 'One who neither rejoices nor grieves, who neither laments nor desires, who renounces both good and evil, and who is full of devotion, is very dear to Me.'),
(501, 12, 'Bhakti Yoga', 20, 'ये तु धर्म्यामृतमिदं यथोक्तं पर्युपासते। श्रद्दधाना मत्परमा भक्तास्तेऽतीव मे प्रिया:।।', 'Those who follow this imperishable path of devotional service and who completely engage themselves with faith, making Me the supreme goal, are very, very dear to Me.'),
(502, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | प्रकृतिं पुरुषं चैव क्षेत्रं क्षेत्रज्ञमेव च। एतद्वेदितुमिच्छामि ज्ञानं ज्ञेयं च केशव।।', 'Arjuna said: O Krishna, I wish to understand nature [prakriti], the enjoyer [purusha], the field [ksetra], the knower of the field [ksetrajna], and of knowledge and the object of knowledge.'),
(503, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | इदं शरीरं कौन्तेय क्षेत्रमित्यभिधीयते। एतद्यो वेत्ति तं प्राहु: क्षेत्रज्ञ इति तद्विद:।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: This body, O son of Kunti, is called the field [ksetra], and one who knows this body is called the knower of the field [ksetrajna].'),
(504, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 3, 'क्षेत्रज्ञं चापि मां विद्धि सर्वक्षेत्रेषु भारत। क्षेत्रक्षेत्रज्ञयोर्ज्ञानं यत्तज्ज्ञानं मतं मम।।', 'O scion of Bharata, you should understand that I am also the knower in all bodies. To understand this body and its knower is called knowledge. That is My opinion.');
INSERT INTO `gita` (`id`, `chapter_number`, `chapter_name`, `verse_number`, `verse`, `translation`) VALUES
(505, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 4, 'तत्क्षेत्रं यच्च यादृक्च यद्विकारि यतश्च यत्। स च यो यत्प्रभावश्च तत्समासेन मे शृणु।।', 'Now please hear My brief description of this field of activity and how it is constituted, what its changes are, whence it is produced, who that knower of the field of activities is, and what his influences are.'),
(506, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 5, 'ऋषिभिर्बहुधा गीतं छन्दोभिर्विविधै: पृथक्। ब्रह्मसूत्रपदैश्चैव हेतुमद्भिर्विनिश्चितै:।।', 'That knowledge of the field of activities and of the knower of activities is described by various sages in various Vedic writings—especially in the Vedanta-sutra—and is presented with all reasoning as to cause and effect.'),
(507, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 6, 'महाभूतान्यहंकारो बुद्धिरव्यक्तमेव च। इन्द्रियाणि दशैकं च पञ्च चेन्द्रियगोचरा:।।', 'The five great elements, false ego, intelligence, the unmanifested, the ten senses, and the mind, the five sense objects—'),
(508, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 7, 'इच्छा द्वेष: सुखं दुःखं संघातश्चेतना धृति:। एतत्क्षेत्रं समासेन सविकारमुदाहृतम्।।', 'Desire, hatred, happiness, distress, the aggregate, the life symptoms, and convictions—all these are considered, in summary, to be the field of activities and its interactions.'),
(509, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 8, 'अमानित्वमदम्भित्वमहिंसा क्षान्तिरार्जवम्। आचार्योपासनं शौचं स्थैर्यमात्मविनिग्रह:।।', 'Humility; pridelessness; nonviolence; tolerance; simplicity; approaching a bona fide spiritual master; cleanliness; steadiness; self-control;'),
(510, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 9, 'इन्द्रियार्थेषु वैराग्यमनहङ्कार एव च। जन्ममृत्युजराव्याधिदु:खदोषानुदर्शनम्।।', 'Detachment from the objects of sense gratification; absence of false ego; the perception of the evil of birth, death, old age, and disease;'),
(511, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 10, 'असक्तिरनभिष्वङ्ग: पुत्रदारगृहादिषु। नित्यं च समचित्तत्वमिष्टानिष्टोपपत्तिषु।।', 'Nonattachment to children, wife, home, and the rest and even-mindedness amid pleasant and unpleasant events;'),
(512, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 11, 'मयि चानन्ययोगेन भक्तिरव्यभिचारिणी। विविक्तदेशसेवित्वमरतिर्जनसंसदि।।', 'Unflinching devotion to Me by the practice of yoga, desire for solitary places, detachment from the general mass of people;'),
(513, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 12, 'अध्यात्मज्ञाननित्यत्वं तत्त्वज्ञानार्थदर्शनम्। एतज्ज्ञानमिति प्रोक्तमज्ञानं यदतोऽन्यथा।।', 'Accepting the importance of self-realization and philosophical search for the Absolute Truth—all these I declare to be knowledge, and besides this, whatever there may be is ignorance.'),
(514, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 13, 'ज्ञेयं यत्तत्प्रवक्ष्यामि यज्ज्ञात्वामृतमश्नुते। अनादिमत्परं ब्रह्म न सत्तन्नासदुच्यते।।', 'I shall now explain the knowable, knowing which you will taste the eternal. It is beginningless and subordinate to Me. It is called Brahman, the spirit, and it lies beyond the cause and effect of this material world.'),
(515, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 14, 'सर्वत: पाणिपादं तत्सर्वतोऽक्षिशिरोमुखम्। सर्वत: श्रुतिमल्लोके सर्वमावृत्य तिष्ठति।।', 'Everywhere are His hands and legs, His eyes, heads, and faces, and He has ears everywhere. In this way, the Supersoul exists, pervading everything.'),
(516, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 15, 'सर्वेन्द्रियगुणाभासं सर्वेन्द्रियविवर्जितम्। असक्तं सर्वभृच्चैव निर्गुणं गुणभोक्तृ च।।', 'The Supersoul is the original source of all senses, yet He is without senses. He is unattached, although He is the maintainer of all living beings. He transcends the modes of nature, and at the same time, He is the master of all modes of material nature.'),
(517, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 16, 'बहिरन्तश्च भूतानामचरं चरमेव च। सूक्ष्मत्वात्तदविज्ञेयं दूरस्थं चान्तिके च तत्।।', 'The Supreme Truth exists both inside and outside of all living beings, the moving and the nonmoving. Because He is subtle, He is beyond the power of the material senses to see or to know. Although far, far away, He is also near to all.'),
(518, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 17, 'अविभक्तं च भूतेषु विभक्तमिव च स्थितम्। भूतभर्तृ च तज्ज्ञेयं ग्रसिष्णु प्रभविष्णु च।।', 'Although the Supersoul appears to be divided among all beings, He is never divided. He is situated as one. Although He is the maintainer of every living entity, it is to be understood that He devours and develops all.'),
(519, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 18, 'ज्योतिषामपि तज्ज्योतिस्तमस: परमुच्यते। ज्ञानं ज्ञेयं ज्ञानगम्यं हृदि सर्वस्य विष्ठितम्।।', 'He is the source of light in all luminous objects. He is beyond the darkness of matter and is unmanifested. He is knowledge, He is the object of knowledge, and He is the goal of knowledge. He is situated in everyone’s heart.'),
(520, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 19, 'इति क्षेत्रं तथा ज्ञानं ज्ञेयं चोक्तं समासतः। मद्भक्त एतद्विज्ञाय मद्भावायोपपद्यते।।', 'Thus the field of activities [the body], knowledge, and the knowable have been summarily described by Me. Only My devotees can understand this completely and attain to My nature.'),
(521, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 20, 'प्रकृतिं पुरुषं चैव विद्ध्यनादी उभावपि। विकारांश्च गुणांश्चैव विद्धि प्रकृतिसंभवान्।।', 'Material nature and the living entities should be understood to be beginningless. Their transformations and the modes of matter are products of material nature.'),
(522, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 21, 'कार्यकारणकर्तृत्वे हेतुः प्रकृतिरुच्यते। पुरुषः सुखदुःखानां भोक्तृत्वे हेतुरुच्यते।।', 'Nature is said to be the cause of all material activities and effects, whereas the living entity is the cause of the various sufferings and enjoyments in this world.'),
(523, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 22, 'पुरुषः प्रकृतिस्थो हि भुङ्क्ते प्रकृतिजान्गुणान्। कारणं गुणसङ्गोऽस्य सदसद्योनिजन्मसु।।', 'The living entity in material nature thus follows the ways of life, enjoying the three modes of nature. This is due to his association with that material nature. Thus he meets with good and evil among various species.'),
(524, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 23, 'उपद्रष्टानुमन्ता च भर्ता भोक्ता महेश्वरः। परमात्मेति चाप्युक्तो देहेऽस्मिन्पुरुषः परः।।', 'Yet in this body there is another, a transcendental enjoyer, who is the Lord, the supreme proprietor, who exists as the overseer and permitter, and who is known as the Supersoul.'),
(525, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 24, 'य एवं वेत्ति पुरुषं प्रकृतिं च गुणैः सह। सर्वथा वर्तमानोऽपि न स भूयोऽभिजायते।।', 'One who understands this philosophy concerning material nature, the living entity, and the interaction of the modes of nature is sure to attain liberation. He will not take birth here again, regardless of his present position.'),
(526, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 25, 'ध्यानेनात्मनि पश्यन्ति केचिदात्मानमात्मना। अन्ये साङ्ख्येन योगेन कर्मयोगेन चापरे।।', 'Some perceive the Supersoul within themselves through meditation, others through the cultivation of knowledge, and still others through working without fruitive desires.'),
(527, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 26, 'अन्ये त्वेवमजानन्तः श्रुत्वान्येभ्य उपासते। तेऽपि चातितरन्त्येव मृत्युं श्रुतिपरायणाः।।', 'Again, there are those who, although not conversant in spiritual knowledge, begin to worship the Supreme Person upon hearing about Him from others. Because of their tendency to hear from authorities, they also transcend the path of birth and death.'),
(528, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 27, 'यावत्सञ्जायते किञ्चित्सत्त्वं स्थावरजङ्गमम्। क्षेत्रक्षेत्रज्ञसंयोगात्तद्विद्धि भरतर्षभ।।', 'O chief of the Bharatas, whatever you see in existence—both the moving and the nonmoving—know it to be a combination of the field of activities and the knower of the field.'),
(529, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 28, 'समं सर्वेषु भूतेषु तिष्ठन्तं परमेश्वरम्। विनश्यत्स्वविनश्यन्तं यः पश्यति स पश्यति।।', 'One who sees the Supersoul equally present everywhere, in every living being, does not degrade himself by his mind. Thus he approaches the transcendental destination.'),
(530, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 29, 'समं पश्यन्हि सर्वत्र समवस्थितमीश्वरम्। न हिनस्त्यात्मनात्मानं ततो याति परां गतिम्।।', 'One who sees the Supersoul equally present in every living being and in all perishable and imperishable things sees the truth.'),
(531, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 30, 'प्रकृत्यैव च कर्माणि क्रियमाणानि सर्वशः। यः पश्यति तथात्मानमकर्तारं स पश्यति।।', 'One who sees that all activities are performed by the body, which is created of material nature, and sees that the self does nothing, actually sees.'),
(532, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 31, 'यदा भूतपृथग्भावमेकस्थमनुपश्यति। तत एव च विस्तारं ब्रह्म सम्पद्यते तदा।।', 'When a sensible man ceases to see different identities due to different material bodies and he sees how beings are expanded everywhere, he attains to the Brahman conception.'),
(533, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 32, 'अनादित्वान्निर्गुणत्वात्परमात्मायमव्ययः। शरीरस्थोऽपि कौन्तेय न करोति न लिप्यते।।', 'Those with the vision of eternity can see that the imperishable soul is transcendental, eternal, and beyond the modes of nature. Despite contact with the material body, O Arjuna, the soul neither does anything nor is entangled.'),
(534, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 33, 'यथा सर्वगतं सौक्ष्म्यादाकाशं नोपलिप्यते। सर्वत्रावस्थितो देहे तथात्मा नोपलिप्यते।।', 'The sky, due to its subtle nature, does not mix with anything, although it is all-pervading. Similarly, the soul situated in Brahman vision does not mix with the body, though situated in that body.'),
(535, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 34, 'यथा प्रकाशयत्येक: कृत्स्नं लोकमिमं रवि:। क्षेत्रं क्षेत्री तथा कृत्स्नं प्रकाशयति भारत।।', 'O son of Bharata, as the sun alone illuminates all this universe, so does the living entity, one within the body, illuminate the entire body by consciousness.'),
(536, 13, 'Ksetra-Ksetrajna Vibhaga Yoga', 35, 'क्षेत्रक्षेत्रज्ञयोरेवमन्तरं ज्ञानचक्षुषा। भूतप्रकृतिमोक्षं च ये विदुर्यान्ति ते परम्।।', 'Those who see with the eyes of knowledge the difference between the body and the knower of the body and can also understand the process of liberation from bondage in material nature attain to the supreme goal.'),
(537, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | परं भूय: प्रवक्ष्यामि ज्ञानानां ज्ञानमुत्तमम्। यज्ज्ञात्वा मुनय: सर्वे परां सिद्धिमितो गताः।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Again I shall declare to you the supreme wisdom, the best of all knowledge, knowing which all the sages have attained the supreme perfection.'),
(538, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 2, 'इदं ज्ञानमुपाश्रित्य मम साधर्म्यमागताः। सर्गेऽपि नोपजायन्ते प्रलये न व्यथन्ति च।।', 'By becoming fixed in this knowledge, one can attain to the transcendental nature, which is like My own nature. Thus established, one is not born at the time of creation or disturbed at the time of dissolution.'),
(539, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 3, 'मम योनिर्महद् ब्रह्म तस्मिन्गर्भं दधाम्यहम्। संभव: सर्वभूतानां ततो भवति भारत।।', 'The total material substance, called Brahman, is the source of birth, and it is that Brahman that I impregnate, making possible the births of all living beings, O son of Bharata.'),
(540, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 4, 'सर्वयोनिषु कौन्तेय मूर्तय: सम्भवन्ति या:। तासां ब्रह्म महद्योनिरहं बीजप्रद: पिता।।', 'It should be understood that all species of life, O son of Kunti, are made possible by birth in this material nature, and that I am the seed-giving father.'),
(541, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 5, 'सत्त्वं रजस्तम इति गुणा: प्रकृतिसम्भवा:। निबध्नन्ति महाबाहो देहे देहिनमव्ययम्।।', 'Material nature consists of three modes—goodness, passion, and ignorance. When the eternal living entity comes in contact with nature, O mighty-armed Arjuna, he becomes conditioned by these modes.'),
(542, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 6, 'तत्र सत्त्वं निर्मलत्वात्प्रकाशकमनामयम्। सुखसङ्गेन बध्नाति ज्ञानसङ्गेन चानघ।।', 'O sinless one, the mode of goodness, being purer than the others, is illuminating, and it frees one from all sinful reactions. Those situated in that mode become conditioned by a sense of happiness and knowledge.'),
(543, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 7, 'रजो रागात्मकं विद्धि तृष्णासङ्गसमुद्भवम्। तन्निबध्नाति कौन्तेय कर्मसङ्गेन देहिनम्।।', 'The mode of passion is born of unlimited desires and longings, O son of Kunti, and because of this, the embodied living entity is bound to material fruitive actions.'),
(544, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 8, 'तमस्त्वज्ञानजं विद्धि मोहनं सर्वदेहिनाम्। प्रमादालस्यनिद्राभिस्तन्निबध्नाति भारत।।', 'And know that the mode of darkness, born of ignorance, is the delusion of all embodied living entities. The results of this mode are madness, indolence, and sleep, which bind the conditioned soul.'),
(545, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 9, 'सत्त्वं सुखे सञ्जयति रज: कर्मणि भारत। ज्ञानमावृत्य तु तम: प्रमादे सञ्जयत्युत।।', 'The mode of goodness conditions one to happiness; passion conditions one to the fruits of action, and ignorance, covering one’s knowledge, binds one to madness.'),
(546, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 10, 'रजस्तमश्चाभिभूय सत्त्वं भवति भारत। रज: सत्त्वं तमश्चैव तम: सत्त्वं रजस्तथा।।', 'Sometimes the mode of goodness becomes prominent, defeating the modes of passion and ignorance, O son of Bharata. Sometimes the mode of passion defeats goodness and ignorance, and at other times ignorance defeats goodness and passion. In this way, there is always competition for supremacy.'),
(547, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 11, 'सर्वद्वारेषु देहेऽस्मिन्प्रकाश उपजायते। ज्ञानं यदा तदा विद्याद्विवृद्धं सत्त्वमित्युत।।', 'The manifestations of the mode of goodness can be experienced when all the gates of the body are illuminated by knowledge.'),
(548, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 12, 'लोभ: प्रवृत्तिरारम्भ: कर्मणामशम: स्पृहा। रजस्येतानि जायन्ते विवृद्धे भरतर्षभ।।', 'O chief of the Bharatas, when there is an increase in the mode of passion, the symptoms of great attachment, fruitive activity, intense endeavor, and uncontrollable desire and hankering develop.'),
(549, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 13, 'अप्रकाशोऽप्रवृत्तिश्च प्रमादो मोह एव च। तमस्येतानि जायन्ते विवृद्धे कुरुनन्दन।।', 'When there is an increase in the mode of ignorance, O son of Kuru, darkness, inertia, madness, and illusion are manifested.'),
(550, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 14, 'यदा सत्त्वे प्रवृद्धे तु प्रलयं याति देहभृत्। तदोत्तमविदां लोकानमलान्प्रतिपद्यते।।', 'When one dies in the mode of goodness, he attains to the pure higher planets of the great sages.'),
(551, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 15, 'रजसि प्रलयं गत्वा कर्मसङ्गिषु जायते। तथा प्रलीनस्तमसि मूढयोनिषु जायते।।', 'When one dies in the mode of passion, he takes birth among those engaged in fruitive activities, and when one dies in the mode of ignorance, he takes birth in the animal kingdom.'),
(552, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 16, 'कर्मण: सुकृतस्याहु: सात्त्विकं निर्मलं फलम्। रजसस्तु फलं दु:खमज्ञानं तमस: फलम्।।', 'The result of pious action is pure and is said to be in the mode of goodness. But action done in the mode of passion results in misery, and action performed in the mode of ignorance results in foolishness.'),
(553, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 17, 'सत्त्वात्संजायते ज्ञानं रजसो लोभ एव च। प्रमादमोहौ तमसो भवतोऽज्ञानमेव च।।', 'From the mode of goodness, real knowledge develops; from the mode of passion, greed develops; and from the mode of ignorance develop foolishness, madness, and illusion.'),
(554, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 18, 'ऊर्ध्वं गच्छन्ति सत्त्वस्था मध्ये तिष्ठन्ति राजसा:। जघन्यगुणवृत्तस्था अधो गच्छन्ति तामसा:।।', 'Those situated in the mode of goodness gradually go upward to the higher planets; those in the mode of passion live on the earthly planets; and those in the abominable mode of ignorance go down to the hellish worlds.'),
(555, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 19, 'नान्यं गुणेभ्य: कर्तारं यदा द्रष्टानुपश्यति। गुणेभ्यश्च परं वेत्ति मद्भावं सोऽधिगच्छति।।', 'When you see that there is nothing beyond these modes of nature in all activities and that the Supreme Lord is transcendental to all these modes, then you can know My spiritual nature.'),
(556, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 20, 'गुणानेतानतीत्य त्रीन्देही देहसमुद्भवान्। जन्ममृत्युजरादु:खैर्विमुक्तोऽमृतमश्नुते।।', 'When the embodied being is able to transcend these three modes associated with the material body, he can become free from birth, death, old age, and their distresses and can enjoy nectar even in this life.'),
(557, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 21, 'अर्जुन उवाच | कैर्लिङ्गैस्त्रीन्गुणानेतानतीतो भवति प्रभो। किमाचार: कथं चैतांस्त्रीन्गुणानतिवर्तते।।', 'Arjuna inquired: O my Lord, by what symptoms is one known who is transcendental to these three modes? What is his behavior? And how does he transcend the modes of nature?'),
(558, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 22, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | प्रकाशं च प्रवृत्तिं च मोहमेव च पाण्डव। न द्वेष्टि सम्प्रवृत्तानि न निवृत्तानि काङ्क्षति।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: O son of Pandu, one who does not hate illumination, attachment, and delusion when they are present, nor longs for them when they disappear;'),
(559, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 23, 'उदासीनवदासीनो गुणैर्यो न विचाल्यते। गुणा वर्तन्त इत्येव योऽवतिष्ठति नेङ्गते।।', 'Who is unwavering and undisturbed through all these reactions of the material qualities, remaining neutral and transcendental, knowing that the modes alone are active;'),
(560, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 24, 'समदु:खसुख: स्वस्थ: समलोष्टाश्मकाञ्चन:। तुल्यप्रियाप्रियो धीरस्तुल्यनिन्दात्मसंस्तुति:।।', 'Who is situated in self-realization and regards alike happiness and distress, who looks upon a lump of earth, a stone, and a piece of gold with an equal eye; who is equal toward the desirable and the undesirable; who is steady, situated equally well in praise and blame;'),
(561, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 25, 'मानापमानयोस्तुल्यस्तुल्यो मित्रारिपक्षयो:। सर्वारम्भपरित्यागी गुणातीत: स उच्यते।।', 'Who is equal in honor and dishonor, who treats friend and foe alike, and who has renounced all material activities—such a person is said to have transcended the modes of nature.'),
(562, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 26, 'मां च योऽव्यभिचारेण भक्तियोगेन सेवते। स गुणान्समतीत्यैतान्ब्रह्मभूयाय कल्पते।।', 'One who engages in full devotional service, unfailing in all circumstances, at once transcends the modes of material nature and thus comes to the level of Brahman.'),
(563, 14, 'Gunatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 27, 'ब्रह्मणो हि प्रतिष्ठाहममृतस्याव्ययस्य च। शाश्वतस्य च धर्मस्य सुखस्यैकान्तिकस्य च।।', 'And I am the basis of the impersonal Brahman, which is immortal, imperishable, and eternal and is the constitutional position of ultimate happiness.'),
(564, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | ऊर्ध्वमूलमध:शाखमश्वत्थं प्राहुरव्ययम्। छन्दांसि यस्य पर्णानि यस्तं वेद स वेदवित्।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: There is a banyan tree which has its roots upward and its branches down, and whose leaves are the Vedic hymns. One who knows this tree is the knower of the Vedas.'),
(565, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 2, 'अधश्चोर्ध्वं प्रसृतास्तस्य शाखा गुणप्रवृद्धा विषयप्रवाला:। अधश्च मूलान्यनुसन्ततानि कर्मानुबन्धीनि मनुष्यलोके।।', 'The branches of this tree extend downward and upward, nourished by the modes of nature. Its twigs are the objects of the senses, and its roots, which are bound to action, extend downward into the human world.'),
(566, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 3, 'न रूपमस्येह तथोपलभ्यते नान्तो न चादिर्न च सम्प्रतिष्ठा। अश्वत्थमेनं सुविरूढमूलमसङ्गशस्त्रेण दृढेन छित्त्वा।।', 'The real form of this tree cannot be perceived in this world. No one can understand where it ends, where it begins, or where its foundation is. But with determination, one must cut down this strongly rooted tree with the weapon of detachment.'),
(567, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 4, 'ततः पदं तत्परिमार्गितव्यं यस्मिन्गता न निवर्तन्ति भूय:। तमेव चाद्यं पुरुषं प्रपद्ये यतः प्रवृत्ति: प्रसृता पुराणी।।', 'Thereafter, one must seek that place from which, having gone, one never returns, and there surrender to that Supreme Personality of Godhead from whom everything began and in whom everything is abiding since time immemorial.'),
(568, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 5, 'निर्मानमोहा जितसङ्गदोषा अध्यात्मनित्या विनिवृत्तकामाः। द्वन्द्वैर्विमुक्ताः सुखदुःखसंज्ञैर्गच्छन्त्यमूढाः पदमव्ययं तत्।।', 'Those who are free from pride and delusion, who have overcome the evil of attachment, who are constantly devoted to the Self, who are devoid of material desires, and who are free from the dualities of happiness and distress, reach that eternal goal.'),
(569, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 6, 'न तद्भासयते सूर्यो न शशाङ्को न पावकः। यद्गत्वा न निवर्तन्ते तद्धाम परमं मम।।', 'That supreme abode of Mine is not illumined by the sun or moon, nor by fire or electricity. Those who reach it never return to this material world.'),
(570, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 7, 'ममैवांशो जीवलोके जीवभूत: सनातन:। मन:षष्ठानीन्द्रियाणि प्रकृतिस्थानि कर्षति।।', 'The living entities in this conditioned world are My eternal fragmental parts. But bound by material nature, they are struggling with the six senses, which include the mind.'),
(571, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 8, 'शरीरं यदवाप्नोति यच्चाप्युत्क्रामतीश्वर:। गृहीत्वैतानि संयाति वायुर्गन्धानिवाशयात्।।', 'The living entity, in the material world, carries different conceptions of life from one body to another as the air carries aromas.'),
(572, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 9, 'श्रोत्रं चक्षु: स्पर्शनं च रसनं घ्राणमेव च। अधिष्ठाय मनश्चायं विषयानुपसेवते।।', 'The living entity thus takes another gross body and obtains a particular type of ear, eye, tongue, nose, and sense of touch, which are grouped about the mind. He thus enjoys a particular set of sense objects.'),
(573, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 10, 'उत्क्रामन्तं स्थितं वापि भुञ्जानं वा गुणान्वितम्। विमूढा नानुपश्यन्ति पश्यन्ति ज्ञानचक्षुष:।।', 'The foolish cannot understand how a living entity can quit his body, nor can they understand what sort of body he enjoys under the spell of the modes of nature. But one whose eyes are trained in knowledge can see all this.'),
(574, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 11, 'यतन्तो योगिनश्चैनं पश्यन्त्यात्मन्यवस्थितम्। यतन्तोऽप्यकृतात्मानो नैनं पश्यन्त्यचेतस:।।', 'The endeavoring transcendentalists, who are situated in self-realization, can see all this clearly. But those whose minds are not developed and who are not situated in self-realization cannot see what is taking place, though they may try to.'),
(575, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 12, 'यदादित्यगतं तेजो जगद्भासयतेऽखिलम्। यच्चन्द्रमसि यच्चाग्नौ तत्तेजो विद्धि मामकम्।।', 'The splendor of the sun, which dissipates the darkness of this whole world, comes from Me. And the splendor of the moon and the splendor of fire are also from Me.'),
(576, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 13, 'गामाविश्य च भूतानि धारयाम्यहमोजसा। पुष्णामि चौषधी: सर्वा: सोमो भूत्वा रसात्मक:।।', 'I enter into each planet, and by My energy, they stay in orbit. I become the moon and thereby supply the juice of life to all vegetables.'),
(577, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 14, 'अहं वैश्वानरो भूत्वा प्राणिनां देहमाश्रित:। प्राणापानसमायुक्त: पचाम्यन्नं चतुर्विधम्।।', 'I am the fire of digestion in the bodies of all living entities, and I join with the air of life, outgoing and incoming, to digest the four kinds of foodstuff.'),
(578, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 15, 'सर्वस्य चाहं हृदि सन्निविष्टो मत्त: स्मृतिर्ज्ञानमपोहनं च। वेदैश्च सर्वैरहमेव वेद्यो वेदान्तकृद्वेदविदेव चाहम्।।', 'I am seated in everyone’s heart, and from Me come remembrance, knowledge, and forgetfulness. By all the Vedas, I am to be known. Indeed, I am the compiler of Vedanta, and I am the knower of the Vedas.'),
(579, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 16, 'द्वाविमौ पुरुषौ लोके क्षरश्चाक्षर एव च। क्षर: सर्वाणि भूतानि कूटस्थोऽक्षर उच्यते।।', 'There are two classes of beings, the fallible and the infallible. In the material world, every entity is fallible, and in the spiritual world, every entity is infallible.'),
(580, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 17, 'उत्तम: पुरुषस्त्वन्य: परमात्मेत्युधाहृत:। यो लोकत्रयमाविश्य बिभर्त्यव्यय ईश्वर:।।', 'Besides these two, there is the greatest living personality, the Supreme Soul, the imperishable Lord Himself, who has entered the three worlds and is maintaining them.'),
(581, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 18, 'यस्मात्क्षरमतीतोऽहमक्षरादपि चोत्तम:। अतोऽस्मि लोके वेदे च प्रथित: पुरुषोत्तम:।।', 'Because I am transcendental, beyond both the fallible and the infallible, and because I am the greatest, I am celebrated both in the world and in the Vedas as that Supreme Person.'),
(582, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 19, 'यो मामेवमसम्मूढो जानाति पुरुषोत्तमम्। स सर्वविद्भजति मां सर्वभावेन भारत।।', 'Whoever knows Me as the Supreme Personality of Godhead without doubting is the knower of everything. He therefore engages himself in full devotional service to Me, O son of Bharata.'),
(583, 15, 'Purushottama Yoga', 20, 'इति गुह्यतमं शास्त्रमिदमुक्तं मयानघ। एतद्बुद्ध्वा बुद्धिमान्स्यात्कृतकृत्यश्च भारत।।', 'This is the most confidential part of the Vedic scriptures, O sinless one, and it is disclosed now by Me. Whoever understands this will become wise, and his endeavors will know perfection.'),
(584, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 1, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | अभयं सत्त्वसंशुद्धिर्ज्ञानयोगव्यवस्थितिः। दानं दमश्च यज्ञश्च स्वाध्यायस्तप आर्जवम्।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: Fearlessness; purification of one’s existence; cultivation of spiritual knowledge; charity; self-control; performance of sacrifice; study of the Vedas; austerity; simplicity;'),
(585, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 2, 'अहिंसा सत्यमक्रोधस्त्यागः शान्तिरपैशुनम्। दया भूतेष्वलोलुप्त्वं मार्दवं ह्रीरचापलम्।।', 'Nonviolence; truthfulness; freedom from anger; renunciation; tranquility; aversion to faultfinding; compassion for all living entities; freedom from covetousness; gentleness; modesty; steady determination;'),
(586, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 3, 'तेजः क्षमा धृतिः शौचमद्रोहो नातिमानिता। भवन्ति सम्पदं दैवीमभिजातस्य भारत।।', 'Vigor; forgiveness; fortitude; cleanliness; freedom from envy and from the passion for honor—these transcendental qualities, O son of Bharata, belong to godly men endowed with divine nature.'),
(587, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 4, 'दम्भो दर्पोऽभिमानश्च क्रोधः पारुष्यमेव च। अज्ञानं चाभिजातस्य पार्थ सम्पदामासुरीम्।।', 'Pride; arrogance; conceit; anger; harshness; and ignorance—these qualities belong to those of demoniac nature, O son of Pritha.'),
(588, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 5, 'दैवी सम्पद्विमोक्षाय निबन्धायासुरी मता। मा शुचः सम्पदं दैवीमभिजातोऽसि पाण्डव।।', 'The transcendental qualities are conducive to liberation, whereas the demoniac qualities make for bondage. Do not worry, O son of Pandu, for you are born with the divine qualities.'),
(589, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 6, 'द्वौ भूतसर्गौ लोकेऽस्मिन्दैव आसुर एव च। दैवो विस्तरशः प्रोक्त आसुरं पार्थ मे शृणु।।', 'O son of Pritha, in this world there are two kinds of created beings. One is called the divine and the other demoniac. I have already explained to you at length the divine qualities; now hear from Me of the demoniac.'),
(590, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 7, 'प्रवृत्तिं च निवृत्तिं च जना न विदुरासुरा:। न शौचं नापि चाचारो न सत्यं तेषु विद्यते।।', 'Those who are demoniac do not know what is to be done and what is not to be done. Neither cleanliness nor proper behavior nor truth is found in them.'),
(591, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 8, 'असत्यमप्रतिष्ठं ते जगदाहुरनीश्वरम्। अपरस्परसम्भूतं किमन्यत्कामहैतुकम्।।', 'They say that this world is unreal, with no foundation, no God in control. They say it is produced of sex desire and has no cause other than lust.'),
(592, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 9, 'एतां दृष्टिमवष्टभ्य नष्टात्मानोऽल्पबुद्धयः। प्रभवन्त्युग्रकर्माणः क्षयाय जगतोऽहिता:।।', 'Following such conclusions, the demoniac, who are lost to themselves and who have no intelligence, engage in unbeneficial, horrible works meant to destroy the world.'),
(593, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 10, 'काममाश्रित्य दुष्पूरं दम्भमानमदान्विता:। मोहाद्गृहीत्वासद्ग्राहान्प्रवर्तन्तेऽशुचिव्रता:।।', 'Taking shelter of insatiable lust and absorbed in the conceit of pride and false prestige, the demoniac, thus illusioned, are always sworn to unclean work, attracted by the impermanent.'),
(594, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 11, 'चिन्तामपरिमेयां च प्रलयान्तामुपाश्रिता:। कामोपभोगपरमा एतावदिति निश्चिताः।।', 'They believe that to gratify the senses unto the end of life is the prime necessity of human civilization. Thus there is no measurement for their anxiety. Being bound by a network of hundreds of thousands of desires, they are absorbed in lust and anger.'),
(595, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 12, 'आशापाशशतैर्बद्धा कामक्रोधपरायणा:। ईहन्ते कामभोगार्थमन्यायेनार्थसञ्चयान्।।', 'Bound by a network of desires and engrossed in lust and anger, they secure money by illegal means for sense gratification.'),
(596, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 13, 'इदमद्य मया लब्धमिमं प्राप्स्ये मनोरथम्। इदमस्तीदमपि मे भविष्यति पुनर्धनम्।।', 'The demoniac person thinks: “So much wealth do I have today, and I will gain more according to my schemes.'),
(597, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 14, 'असौ मया हतः शत्रुर्हनिष्ये चापरानपि। ईश्वरोऽहमहं भोगी सिद्धोऽहं बलवान्सुखी।।', 'I have killed this enemy, and I shall kill others also. I am the lord of everything. I am the enjoyer. I am perfect, powerful, and happy.'),
(598, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 15, 'आढ्योऽभिजनवानस्मि कोऽन्योऽस्ति सदृशो मया। यक्ष्ये दास्यामि मोदिष्य इत्यज्ञानविमोहिता:।।', 'I am rich and wealthy, and no one is so powerful and happy as I am. I shall perform sacrifices, I shall give some charity, and thus I shall rejoice.” In this way, such persons are deluded by ignorance.'),
(599, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 16, 'अनेकचित्तविभ्रान्ता मोहजालसमावृता:। प्रसक्ताः कामभोगेषु पतन्ति नरकेऽशुचौ।।', 'Bewildered by false ego, strength, pride, lust, and anger, the demoniac becomes envious of the Supreme Personality of Godhead, who is situated in their own body and in the bodies of others. Blaspheming against the real religion, they become envious and arrogant.'),
(600, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 17, 'आत्मसम्भाविता: स्तब्धा धनमानमदान्विता:। यजन्ते नामयज्ञैस्ते दम्भेनाविधिपूर्वकम्।।', 'Those who are arrogant and possessed by false prestige perform ostentatious sacrifices without following any principles.'),
(601, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 18, 'अहङ्कारं बलं दर्पं कामं क्रोधं च संश्रिता:। मामात्मपरदेहेषु प्रद्विषन्तोऽभ्यसूयका:।।', 'Bewildered by false ego, strength, pride, lust, and anger, the demoniac blaspheme against the Supreme Personality of Godhead, who is situated within themselves and in others.'),
(602, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 19, 'तानहं द्विषतः क्रूरान्संसारेषु नराधमान्। क्षिपाम्यजस्रमशुभानासुरीष्वेव योनिषु।।', 'Those who are envious and mischievous, who are the lowest among men, I perpetually cast into the ocean of material existence, into various demoniac species of life.'),
(603, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 20, 'आसुरीं योनिमापन्ना मूढा जन्मनि जन्मनि। मामप्राप्यैव कौन्तेय ततो यान्त्यधमां गतिम्।।', 'Attaining repeated birth among demoniac species, such persons, O son of Kunti, can never approach Me. Gradually they sink down to the most abominable type of existence.'),
(604, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 21, 'त्रिविधं नरकस्येदं द्वारं नाशनमात्मन:। काम: क्रोधस्तथा लोभस्तस्मादेतत्त्रयं त्यजेत्।।', 'There are three gates leading to hell—lust, anger, and greed. Every sane man should give these up, for they lead to the degradation of the soul.'),
(605, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 22, 'एतैर्विमुक्त: कौन्तेय तमोद्वारैस्त्रिभिर्नर:। आचरत्यात्मन: श्रेयस्ततो याति परां गतिम्।।', 'The man who has escaped these three gates of hell, O son of Kunti, performs acts conducive to self-realization and thus gradually attains the supreme destination.'),
(606, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 23, 'य: शास्त्रविधिमुत्सृज्य वर्तते कामकारतः। न स सिद्धिमवाप्नोति न सुखं न परां गतिम्।।', 'He who discards scriptural injunctions and acts according to his own whims attains neither perfection, happiness, nor the supreme destination.'),
(607, 16, 'Daivasura Sampad Vibhaga Yoga', 24, 'तस्माच्छास्त्रं प्रमाणं ते कार्याकार्यव्यवस्थितौ। ज्ञात्वा शास्त्रविधानोक्तं कर्म कर्तुमिहार्हसि।।', 'One should understand what is duty and what is not duty by the regulations of the scriptures. Knowing such rules and regulations, one should act so that he may gradually be elevated.'),
(608, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | ये शास्त्रविधिमुत्सृज्य यजन्ते श्रद्धयान्विता:। तेषां निष्ठा तु का कृष्ण सत्त्वमाहो रजस्तम:।।', 'Arjuna said: O Krishna, what is the situation of those who do not follow the principles of scripture but worship according to their own faith? Is it in goodness, in passion, or in ignorance?'),
(609, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | त्रिविधा भवति श्रद्धा देहिनां सा स्वभावजा। सात्त्विकी राजसी चैव तामसी चेति तां शृणु।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: According to the modes of nature acquired by the embodied soul, one’s faith can be of three kinds—in goodness, in passion, or in ignorance. Now hear about this.'),
(610, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 3, 'सत्त्वानुरूपा सर्वस्य श्रद्धा भवति भारत। श्रद्धामयोऽयं पुरुषो यो यच्छ्रद्ध: स एव स:।।', 'O son of Bharata, according to one’s existence under the various modes of nature, one evolves a particular kind of faith. The living being is said to be of a particular faith according to the modes he has acquired.'),
(611, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 4, 'यजन्ते सात्त्विका देवान्यक्षरक्षांसि राजसा:। प्रेतान्भूतगणांश्चान्ये यजन्ते तामसा जना:।।', 'Men in the mode of goodness worship the demigods; those in the mode of passion worship the demons; and those in the mode of ignorance worship ghosts and spirits.'),
(612, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 5, 'अशास्त्रविहितं घोरं तप्यन्ते ये तपो जना:। दम्भाहङ्कारसंयुक्ता: कामरागबलान्विता:।।', 'Those who undergo severe austerities and penances not recommended in the scriptures, performing them out of pride and egoism, who are impelled by lust and attachment,'),
(613, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 6, 'कर्शयन्त: शरीरस्थं भूतग्राममचेतस:। मां चैवान्त:शरीरस्थं तान्विद्ध्यासुरनिश्चयान्।।', 'Who torture their own bodies as well as the Supersoul dwelling within, are to be known as demons.'),
(614, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 7, 'आहारस्त्वपि सर्वस्य त्रिविधो भवति प्रिय:। यज्ञस्तपस्तथा दानं तेषां भेदमिमं शृणु।।', 'Even the food each person prefers is of three kinds, according to the three modes of material nature. The same is true of sacrifices, austerities, and charity. Listen, and I shall tell you of the distinctions in these.'),
(615, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 8, 'आयु:सत्त्वबलारोग्यसुखप्रीतिविवर्धना:। रस्याः स्निग्धा: स्थिरा हृद्या आहारा सात्त्विकप्रियाः।।', 'Foods that increase life, purify one’s existence, give strength, health, happiness, and satisfaction, which are juicy, fatty, wholesome, and pleasing to the heart, are dear to those in the mode of goodness.'),
(616, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 9, 'कट्वम्ललवणात्युष्णतीक्ष्णरूक्षविदाहिन:। आहारा राजसस्येष्टा दु:खशोकामयप्रदा:।।', 'Foods that are too bitter, too sour, salty, hot, pungent, dry, and burning are dear to those in the mode of passion. Such foods cause pain, distress, and disease.'),
(617, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 10, 'यातयामं गतरसं पूति पर्युषितं च यत्। उच्छिष्टमपि चामेध्यं भोजनं तामसप्रियम्।।', 'Food prepared more than three hours before being eaten, food that is tasteless, decomposed, and putrid, and food consisting of remnants and untouchable things is dear to those in the mode of ignorance.'),
(618, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 11, 'अफलाङ्क्षिभिर्यज्ञो विधिदृष्टो य इज्यते। यष्टव्यमेवेति मन: समाधाय स सात्त्विक:।।', 'Of sacrifices, the sacrifice performed according to duty and to scriptural rules and with no expectation of reward is of the nature of goodness.'),
(619, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 12, 'अभिसन्धाय तु फलं दम्भार्थमपि चैव यत्। इज्यते भरतश्रेष्ठ तं यज्ञं विद्धि राजसम्।।', 'But the sacrifice performed for some material benefit or for the sake of pride, O chief of the Bharatas, you should know to be in the mode of passion.'),
(620, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 13, 'विधिहीनमसृष्टान्नं मन्त्रहीनमदक्षिणम्। श्रद्धाविरहितं यज्ञं तामसं परिचक्षते।।', 'Any sacrifice performed without regard for the directions of scripture, without distribution of prasadam, without chanting of Vedic hymns, without remunerations to the priests, and without faith is considered to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(621, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 14, 'देवद्विजगुरुप्राज्ञपूजनं शौचमार्जवम्। ब्रह्मचर्यमहिंसा च शारीरं तप उच्यते।।', 'Austerity of the body consists in worship of the Supreme Lord, the brahmanas, the spiritual master, and superiors like the father and mother, and in cleanliness, simplicity, celibacy, and nonviolence.'),
(622, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 15, 'अनुद्वेगकरं वाक्यं सत्यं प्रियहितं च यत्। स्वाध्यायाभ्यसनं चैव वाङ्मयं तप उच्यते।।', 'Austerity of speech consists in speaking words that are truthful, pleasing, beneficial, and not agitating to others, and also in regularly reciting Vedic literature.'),
(623, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 16, 'मन:प्रसाद: सौम्यत्वं मौनमात्मविनिग्रह:। भावसंशुद्धिरित्येतत्तपो मानसमुच्यते।।', 'And serenity, simplicity, gravity, self-control, and purity of thought are the austerities of the mind.'),
(624, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 17, 'श्रद्धया परया तप्तं तपस्तत्त्रिविधं नरै:। अफलाकाङ्क्षिभिर्युक्तै: सात्त्विकं परिचक्षते।।', 'This threefold austerity, performed with transcendental faith by men not expecting material benefits but engaged only for the sake of the Supreme, is called austerity in goodness.'),
(625, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 18, 'सत्कारमानपूजार्थं तपो दम्भेन चैव यत्। क्रियते तदिह प्रोक्तं राजसं चलमध्रुवम्।।', 'Penance performed out of pride and for the sake of gaining respect, honor, and worship is said to be in the mode of passion. It is neither stable nor permanent.'),
(626, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 19, 'मूढग्राहेणात्मनो यत्पीडया क्रियते तप:। परस्योत्सादनार्थं वा तत्तामसमुदाहृतम्।।', 'Penance performed out of foolishness, with self-torture, or to destroy or injure others is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(627, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 20, 'दातव्यमिति यद्दानं दीयतेऽनुपकारिणे। देशे काले च पात्रे च तद्दानं सात्त्विकं स्मृतम्।।', 'Charity given out of duty, without expectation of return, at the proper time and place, and to a worthy person is considered to be in the mode of goodness.'),
(628, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 21, 'यत्तु प्रत्युपकारार्थं फलमुद्दिश्य वा पुन:। दीयते च परिक्लिष्टं तद्दानं राजसं स्मृतम्।।', 'But charity performed with the expectation of some return or with a desire for fruitive results or in a grudging mood is said to be charity in the mode of passion.'),
(629, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 22, 'अदेशकाले यद्दानमपात्रेभ्यश्च दीयते। असत्कृतमवज्ञातं तत्तामसमुदाहृतम्।।', 'And charity performed at an improper place and time and given to unworthy persons, without respect and with contempt, is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(630, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 23, 'ॐ तत्सदिति निर्देशो ब्रह्मणस्त्रिविध: स्मृत:। ब्राह्मणास्तेन वेदाश्च यज्ञाश्च विहिता: पुरा।।', 'From the beginning of creation, the three words Om Tat Sat were used to indicate the Supreme Absolute Truth. These three symbolic representations were used by brahmanas while chanting the hymns of the Vedas and during sacrifices for the satisfaction of the Supreme.'),
(631, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 24, 'तस्मादोमित्युदाहृत्य यज्ञदानतप:क्रिया:। प्रवर्तन्ते विधानोक्ता: सततं ब्रह्मवादिनाम्।।', 'Therefore, transcendentalists undertaking performances of sacrifice, charity, and penance in accordance with scriptural regulations begin always with Om to attain the Supreme.'),
(632, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 25, 'तदित्यनभिसन्धाय फलं यज्ञतप:क्रिया:। दानक्रियाश्च विविधा: क्रियन्ते मोक्षकाङ्क्षिभि:।।', 'Without desiring fruitive results, one should perform various kinds of sacrifice, penance, and charity with the word Tat. The purpose of such transcendental activities is to get free from material entanglement.'),
(633, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 26, 'सद्भावे साधुभावे च सदित्येतत्प्रयुज्यते। प्रशस्ते कर्मणि तथा सच्छब्द: पार्थ युज्यते।।', 'The Absolute Truth is the objective of devotional sacrifice, and it is indicated by the word Sat. The performer of such sacrifice is also called Sat, as are all works of sacrifice, penance, and charity, which, true to the absolute nature, are performed to please the Supreme Person, O son of Pritha.'),
(634, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 27, 'अश्रद्धया हुतं दत्तं तपस्तप्तं कृतं च यत्। असदित्युच्यते पार्थ न च तत्प्रेत्य नो इह।।', 'Anything done as sacrifice, charity, or penance without faith in the Supreme, O son of Pritha, is impermanent. It is called Asat and is useless both in this life and the next.'),
(635, 17, 'Shraddhatraya Vibhaga Yoga', 28, 'अश्रद्धया हुतं दत्तं तपस्तप्तं कृतं च यत्। असदित्युच्यते पार्थ न च तत्प्रेत्य नो इह।।', 'Anything done as sacrifice, charity, or penance without faith in the Supreme, O son of Pritha, is impermanent. It is called Asat and is useless both in this life and the next.'),
(636, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 1, 'अर्जुन उवाच | संन्यासस्य महाबाहो तत्त्वमिच्छामि वेदितुम्। त्यागस्य च हृषीकेश पृथक्केशिनिषूदन।।', 'Arjuna said: O mighty-armed Krishna, I wish to understand the true nature of renunciation [sannyasa] and of the renunciation of the fruits of action [tyaga], and the difference between the two, O slayer of Kesi.'),
(637, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 2, 'श्रीभगवानुवाच | काम्यानां कर्मणां न्यासं संन्यासं कवयो विदु:। सर्वकर्मफलत्यागं प्राहुस्त्यागं विचक्षणा:।।', 'The Blessed Lord said: The renunciation of actions motivated by desire is what the wise call renunciation [sannyasa], and the abandonment of the fruits of all action is called tyaga by the learned.'),
(638, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 3, 'त्याज्यं दोषवदित्येके कर्म प्राहुर्मनीषिण:। यज्ञदानतप:कर्म न त्याज्यमिति चापरे।।', 'Some learned men declare that all kinds of fruitive actions should be given up as faulty, yet other sages maintain that acts of sacrifice, charity, and penance should never be abandoned.'),
(639, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 4, 'निश्चयं श्रृणु मे तत्र त्यागे भरतसत्तम। त्यागो हि पुरुषव्याघ्र त्रिविध: सम्प्रकीर्तित:।।', 'O best of the Bharatas, now hear My judgment about renunciation. O tiger among men, renunciation is declared in the scriptures to be of three kinds.'),
(640, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 5, 'यज्ञदानतप:कर्म न त्याज्यं कार्यमेव तत्। यज्ञो दानं तपश्चैव पावनानि मनीषिणाम्।।', 'Acts of sacrifice, charity, and penance are not to be given up but should be performed, for they purify even the great souls.'),
(641, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 6, 'एतान्यपि तु कर्माणि सङ्गं त्यक्त्वा फलानि च। कर्तव्यानीति मे पार्थ निश्चितं मतमुत्तमम्।।', 'All these activities should be performed without attachment or expectation of results. They must be performed as a matter of duty. This is My final opinion, O son of Pritha.'),
(642, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 7, 'नियतस्य तु संन्यास: कर्मणो नोपपद्यते। मोहात्तस्य परित्यागस्तामस: परिकीर्तित:।।', 'Prescribed duties should never be renounced. If one gives up his prescribed duties because of illusion, such renunciation is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(643, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 8, 'दु:खमित्येव यत्कर्म कायक्लेशभयात्त्यजेत्। स कृत्वा राजसं त्यागं नैव त्यागफलं लभेत्।।', 'Anyone who gives up prescribed duties as troublesome, or out of fear of bodily discomfort, is said to have renounced in the mode of passion. Such action does not lead to the benefit of renunciation.'),
(644, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 9, 'कार्यमित्येव यत्कर्म नियतं क्रियतेऽर्जुन। सङ्गं त्यक्त्वा फलं चैव स त्याग: सात्त्विको मत:।।', 'But he who performs his prescribed duty only because it ought to be done and renounces all attachment to the fruit—his renunciation is of the nature of goodness, O Arjuna.'),
(645, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 10, 'न द्वेष्ट्यकुशलं कर्म कुशले नानुषज्जते। त्यागी सत्त्वसमाविष्टो मेधावी छिन्नसंशय:।।', 'The intelligent renouncer situated in the mode of goodness, neither hating unpleasant work nor attached to pleasant work, is free from all doubts.'),
(646, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 11, 'न हि देहभृता शक्यं त्यक्तुं कर्माण्यशेषत:। यस्तु कर्मफलत्यागी स त्यागीत्यभिधीयते।।', 'It is indeed impossible for an embodied being to give up all activities. But one who renounces the fruits of action is said to have truly renounced.'),
(647, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 12, 'अनिष्टमिष्टं मिश्रं च त्रिविधं कर्मण: फलम्। भवत्यत्यागिनां प्रेत्य न तु संन्यासिनां क्वचित्।।', 'For one who is not renounced, the threefold fruits of action—desirable, undesirable, and mixed—accrue after death. But those who are in the renounced order of life have no such results to suffer or enjoy.'),
(648, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 13, 'पञ्चैतानि महाबाहो कारणानि निबोध मे। सांख्ये कृतान्ते प्रोक्तानि सिद्धये सर्वकर्मणाम्।।', 'O mighty-armed Arjuna, learn from Me the five factors which bring about the accomplishment of all action, as stated in the Sankhya philosophy.'),
(649, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 14, 'अधिष्ठानं तथा कर्ता करणं च पृथग्विधम्। विविधाश्च पृथक्चेष्टा दैवं चैवात्र पञ्चमम्।।', 'The place of action [the body], the performer, the various senses, the many kinds of endeavor, and ultimately the Supersoul—these are the five factors of action.'),
(650, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 15, 'शरीरवाङ्मनोभिर्यत्कर्म प्रारभते नर:। न्याय्यं वा विपरीतं वा पञ्चैते तस्य हेतव:।।', 'Whatever action a man performs with his body, speech, and mind, whether right or wrong, is caused by these five factors.'),
(651, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 16, 'तत्रैवं सति कर्तारमात्मानं केवलं तु य:। पश्यत्यकृतबुद्धित्वान्न स पश्यति दुर्मतिः।।', 'Therefore one who thinks himself the only doer, not considering the five factors, is certainly not very intelligent and cannot see things as they are.'),
(652, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 17, 'यस्यानहङ्कारो भावो बुद्धिर्यस्य न लिप्यते। हत्वापि स इमाँल्लोकान्न हन्ति न निबध्यते।।', 'One who is not motivated by false ego, whose intelligence is not entangled, even though he kills men in this world, does not kill, nor is he bound by his actions.'),
(653, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 18, 'ज्ञानं ज्ञेयं परिज्ञाता त्रिविधा कर्मचोदना। करणं कर्म कर्तेति त्रिविध: कर्मसङ्ग्रह:।।', 'Knowledge, the object of knowledge, and the knower are the three factors which motivate action; the senses, the work, and the doer comprise the threefold basis of action.'),
(654, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 19, 'ज्ञानं कर्म च कर्ता च त्रिधैव गुणभेदत:। प्रोच्यते गुणसंख्याने यथावच्छृणु तान्यपि।।', 'Knowledge, action, and the doer are declared in the Sankhya philosophy to be of three kinds, according to the modes of material nature. Hear of them also.'),
(655, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 20, 'सर्वभूतेषु येनैकं भावमव्ययमीक्षते। अविभक्तं विभक्तेषु तज्ज्ञानं विद्धि सात्त्विकम्।।', 'That knowledge by which one undivided spiritual nature is seen in all living beings, though they are divided into innumerable forms, should be understood to be in the mode of goodness.'),
(656, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 21, 'पृथक्त्वेन तु यज्ज्ञानं नानाभावान्पृथग्विधान्। वेत्ति सर्वेषु भूतेषु तज्ज्ञानं विद्धि राजसम्।।', 'That knowledge by which one sees that in every different body there is a different type of living entity, you should understand to be in the mode of passion.'),
(657, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 22, 'यत्तु कृत्स्नवदेकस्मिन्कार्ये सक्तमहैतुकम्। अतत्त्वार्थवदल्पं च तत्तामसमुदाहृतम्।।', 'And that knowledge by which one is attached to one kind of work as the all in all, without knowledge of the truth, and which is very meager, is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(658, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 23, 'नियतं संग रहितमरागद्वेषत: कृतम्। अफलप्रेप्सुना कर्म यत्तत्सात्त्विकमुच्यते।।', 'That action which is regulated and performed without attachment, without love or hatred, and without desire for fruitive results, is said to be in the mode of goodness.'),
(659, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 24, 'यत्तु कामेप्सुना कर्म साहङ्कारेण वा पुन:। क्रियते बहुलायासं तद्राजसमुदाहृतम्।।', 'But action performed with great effort by one seeking to gratify his desires, and enacted from a sense of false ego, is called action in the mode of passion.'),
(660, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 25, 'अनुबन्धं क्षयं हिंसामनपेक्ष्य च पौरुषम्। मोहादारभ्यते कर्म यत्तत्तामसमुच्यते।।', 'That action performed in illusion, in disregard of scriptural injunctions, and without concern for future bondage, or for violence or distress caused to others, is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(661, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 26, 'मुक्तसङ्गोऽनहंवादी धृत्युत्साहसमन्वित:। सिद्ध्यसिद्ध्योर्निर्विकार: कर्ता सात्त्विक उच्यते।।', 'One who performs his duty without association with the modes of material nature, without false ego, with great determination and enthusiasm, and without wavering in success or failure, is said to be a worker in the mode of goodness.'),
(662, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 27, 'रागी कर्मफलप्रेप्सुर्लुब्धो हिंसात्मकोऽशुचि:। हर्षशोकान्वित: कर्ता राजस: परिकीर्तित:।।', 'The worker who is attached to work and the fruits of work, who passionately desires to enjoy them, who is greedy, envious, impure, and moved by joy and sorrow, is said to be in the mode of passion.'),
(663, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 28, 'अयुक्त: प्राकृत: स्तब्ध: शठो नैष्कृतिकोऽलस:। विषादी दीर्घसूत्री च कर्ता तामस उच्यते।।', 'The worker who is always engaged in work against the injunctions of the scripture, who is materialistic, obstinate, cheating, expert in insulting others, lazy, always morose, and procrastinating, is said to be in the mode of ignorance.'),
(664, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 29, 'बुद्धेर्भेदं धृतेश्चैव गुणतस्त्रिविधं शृणु। प्रोच्यमानमशेषेण पृथक्त्वेन धनञ्जय।।', 'O conqueror of wealth, now please listen as I tell you in detail of the three kinds of understanding and determination, according to the three modes of material nature.');
INSERT INTO `gita` (`id`, `chapter_number`, `chapter_name`, `verse_number`, `verse`, `translation`) VALUES
(665, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 30, 'प्रवृत्तिं च निवृत्तिं च कार्याकार्ये भयाभये। बन्धं मोक्षं च या वेत्ति बुद्धि: सा पार्थ सात्त्विकी।।', 'O son of Pritha, that understanding by which one knows what ought to be done and what ought not to be done, what is to be feared and what is not to be feared, what is binding and what is liberating, is in the mode of goodness.'),
(666, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 31, 'यया धर्ममधर्मं च कार्यं चाकार्यमेव च। अयथावत्प्रजानाति बुद्धि: सा पार्थ राजसी।।', 'And that understanding which cannot distinguish between religion and irreligion, between action that should be done and action that should not be done, is in the mode of passion, O son of Pritha.'),
(667, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 32, 'अधर्मं धर्ममिति या मन्यते तमसावृता। सर्वार्थान्विपरीतांश्च बुद्धि: सा पार्थ तामसी।।', 'That understanding which considers irreligion to be religion and religion to be irreligion, under the spell of illusion and darkness, and strives always in the wrong direction, O son of Pritha, is in the mode of ignorance.'),
(668, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 33, 'धृत्या यया धारयते मन:प्राणेन्द्रियक्रिया:। योगेनाव्यभिचारिण्या धृति: सा पार्थ सात्त्विकी।।', 'O son of Pritha, that determination which is unbreakable, which is sustained with steadfastness by yoga practice, and which thus controls the activities of the mind, life, and senses, is in the mode of goodness.'),
(669, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 34, 'यया तु धर्मकामार्थान्धृत्या धारयते अर्जुन। प्रसङ्गेन फलाकाङ्क्षी धृति: सा पार्थ राजसी।।', 'But that determination by which one holds fast to fruitive results in religion, economic development, and sense gratification is of the nature of passion, O Arjuna.'),
(670, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 35, 'यया स्वप्नं भयं शोकं विषादं मदमेव च। न विमुञ्चति दुर्मेधा धृति: सा पार्थ तामसी।।', 'And that determination which cannot go beyond dreaming, fearfulness, lamentation, moroseness, and illusion—such unintelligent determination, O son of Pritha, is in the mode of ignorance.'),
(671, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 36, 'सुखं त्विदानीं त्रिविधं शृणु मे भरतर्षभ। अभ्यासाद्रमते यत्र दु:खान्तं च निगच्छति।।', 'Now hear from Me, O best of the Bharatas, about the three kinds of happiness by which the conditioned soul enjoys, and by which he sometimes comes to the end of all distress.'),
(672, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 37, 'यत्तदग्रे विषमिव परिणामेऽमृतोपमम्। तत्सुखं सात्त्विकं प्रोक्तमात्मबुद्धिप्रसादजम्।।', 'That which in the beginning may be just like poison but at the end is just like nectar and which awakens one to self-realization is said to be happiness in the mode of goodness.'),
(673, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 38, 'विषयेन्द्रियसंयोगाद्यत्तदग्रेऽमृतोपमम्। परिणामे विषमिव तत्सुखं राजसं स्मृतम्।।', 'That happiness which is derived from contact of the senses with their objects and which appears like nectar at first but poison at the end is said to be of the nature of passion.'),
(674, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 39, 'यदग्रे चानुबन्धे च सुखं मोहनमात्मन:। निद्रालस्यप्रमादोत्थं तत्तामसमुदाहृतम्।।', 'And that happiness which is blind to self-realization, which is delusion from beginning to end, and which arises from sleep, laziness, and illusion is said to be of the nature of ignorance.'),
(675, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 40, 'न तदस्ति पृथिव्यां वा दिवि देवेषु वा पुन:। सत्त्वं प्रकृतिजैर्मुक्तं यदेभि: स्यात्त्रिभिर्गुणै:।।', 'There is no being existing, either here or among the demigods in the higher planetary systems, which is free from these three modes born of material nature.'),
(676, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 41, 'ब्राह्मणक्षत्रियविशां शूद्राणां च परन्तप। कर्माणि प्रविभक्तानि स्वभावप्रभवैर्गुणै:।।', 'Brahmanas, kshatriyas, vaishyas, and shudras are distinguished by the qualities born of their own natures in accordance with the material modes, O chastiser of the enemy.'),
(677, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 42, 'शमो दमस्तप: शौचं क्षान्तिरार्जवमेव च। ज्ञानं विज्ञानमास्तिक्यं ब्रह्मकर्म स्वभावजम्।।', 'Peacefulness, self-control, austerity, purity, tolerance, honesty, knowledge, wisdom, and religiousness—these are the natural qualities by which the brahmanas work.'),
(678, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 43, 'शौर्यं तेजो धृतिर्दाक्ष्यं युद्धे चाप्यपलायनम्। दानमीश्वरभावश्च क्षात्रं कर्म स्वभावजम्।।', 'Heroism, power, determination, resourcefulness, courage in battle, generosity, and leadership are the natural qualities of work for the kshatriyas.'),
(679, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 44, 'कृषिगौरक्ष्यवाणिज्यं वैश्यकर्म स्वभावजम्। परिचर्यात्मकं कर्म शूद्रस्यापि स्वभावजम्।।', 'Farming, cow protection, and business are the natural work for the vaishyas, and for the shudras there is labor and service to others.'),
(680, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 45, 'स्वे स्वे कर्मण्यभिरत: संसिद्धिं लभते नर:। स्वकर्मनिरत: सिद्धिं यथा विन्दति तच्छृणु।।', 'By following his qualities of work, every man can become perfect. Now please hear from Me how this can be done.'),
(681, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 46, 'यत: प्रवृत्तिर्भूतानां येन सर्वमिदं ततम्। स्वकर्मणा तमभ्यर्च्य सिद्धिं विन्दति मानव:।।', 'By worship of the Lord, who is the source of all beings and who is all-pervading, man can, in the performance of his own duty, attain perfection.'),
(682, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 47, 'श्रेयान्स्वधर्मो विगुण: परधर्मात्स्वनुष्ठितात्। स्वभावनियतं कर्म कुर्वन्नाप्नोति किल्बिषम्।।', 'It is better to perform one’s own duties imperfectly than to perform the duties of another perfectly. Duties prescribed according to one’s nature are never affected by sinful reactions.'),
(683, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 48, 'सहजं कर्म कौन्तेय सदोषमपि न त्यजेत्। सर्वारम्भा हि दोषेण धूमेनाग्निरिवावृता:।।', 'Every endeavor is covered by some fault, just as fire is covered by smoke. Therefore, one should not give up the work born of his nature, O son of Kunti, even if such work is full of fault.'),
(684, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 49, 'असक्तबुद्धि: सर्वत्र जितात्मा विगतस्पृह:। नैष्कर्म्यसिद्धिं परमां संन्यासेनाधिगच्छति।।', 'One who is self-controlled and unattached and who disregards all material enjoyments can obtain by renunciation the highest perfection of freedom from reaction.'),
(685, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 50, 'सिद्धिं प्राप्तो यथा ब्रह्म तथाप्नोति निबोध मे। समासेनैव कौन्तेय निष्ठा ज्ञानस्य या परा।।', 'O son of Kunti, learn from Me how one who has achieved this perfection can attain to the supreme perfectional stage, Brahman, the stage of highest knowledge, by acting in the manner I shall now summarize.'),
(686, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 51, 'बुद्ध्या विशुद्धया युक्तो धृत्यात्मानं नियम्य च। शब्दादीन्विषयांस्त्यक्त्वा रागद्वेषौ व्युदस्य च।।', 'Being purified by his intelligence and controlling the mind with determination, giving up the objects of sense gratification, being freed from attachment and hatred,'),
(687, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 52, 'विविक्तसेवी लघ्वाशी यतवाक्कायमानस:। ध्यानयोगपरो नित्यं वैराग्यं समुपाश्रित:।।', 'Living in a secluded place, eating little, controlling the body, mind, and power of speech, always in trance and detached, free from false ego, false strength, false pride, lust, anger, and acceptance of material things,'),
(688, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 53, 'अहङ्कारं बलं दर्पं कामं क्रोधं परिग्रहम्। विमुच्य निर्मम: शान्तो ब्रह्मभूयाय कल्पते।।', 'Such a person, freed from all false ego, false strength, false pride, lust, anger, and material attachment, becomes eligible for self-realization.'),
(689, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 54, 'ब्रह्मभूत: प्रसन्नात्मा न शोचति न काङ्क्षति। सम: सर्वेषु भूतेषु मद्भक्तिं लभते पराम्।।', 'One who is thus transcendentally situated at once realizes the Supreme Brahman and becomes fully joyful. He never laments or desires to have anything; he is equally disposed toward every living entity. In that state, he attains pure devotional service unto Me.'),
(690, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 55, 'भक्त्या मामभिजानाति यावान्यश्चास्मि तत्त्वत:। ततो मां तत्त्वतो ज्ञात्वा विशते तदनन्तरम्।।', 'One can understand Me as I am, the Supreme Personality of Godhead, only by devotional service. And when, by such devotion, one is fully conscious of Me, one can enter into the kingdom of God.'),
(691, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 56, 'सर्वकर्माण्यपि सदा कुर्वाणो मद्व्यपाश्रय:। मत्प्रसादादवाप्नोति शाश्वतं पदमव्ययम्।।', 'Though engaged in all kinds of work, My devotee, under My protection, reaches the eternal and imperishable abode by My grace.'),
(692, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 57, 'चेतसा सर्वकर्माणि मयि संन्यस्य मत्पर:। बुद्धियोगमुपाश्रित्य मच्चित्त: सततं भव।।', 'In all activities, just depend upon Me and work always under My protection. In such devotional service, be fully conscious of Me.'),
(693, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 58, 'मच्चित्त: सर्वदुर्गाणि मत्प्रसादात्तरिष्यसि। अथ चेत्त्वमहङ्कारान्न श्रोष्यसि विनङ्क्ष्यसि।।', 'If you become conscious of Me, you will pass over all the obstacles of conditioned life by My grace. If, however, you do not work in such consciousness but act through false ego, not hearing Me, you will be lost.'),
(694, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 59, 'यदहङ्कारमाश्रित्य न योत्स्य इति मन्यसे। मिथ्यैष व्यवसायस्ते प्रकृतिस्त्वां नियोक्ष्यति।।', 'If you do not act according to My direction and do not fight, then you will be falsely directed. By your nature, you will have to be engaged in warfare.'),
(695, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 60, 'स्वभावजेन कौन्तेय निबद्ध: स्वेन कर्मणा। कर्तुं नेच्छसि यन्मोहात्करिष्यस्यवशोऽपि तत्।।', 'Under illusion, you are now declining to act according to My direction. But, compelled by your own nature, you will act all the same, O son of Kunti.'),
(696, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 61, 'ईश्वर: सर्वभूतानां हृद्देशेऽर्जुन तिष्ठति। भ्रामयन्सर्वभूतानि यन्त्रारूढानि मायया।।', 'The Supreme Lord is situated in everyone’s heart, O Arjuna, and is directing the wanderings of all living entities, who are seated as on a machine, made of the material energy.'),
(697, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 62, 'तमेव शरणं गच्छ सर्वभावेन भारत। तत्प्रसादात्परां शान्तिं स्थानं प्राप्स्यसि शाश्वतम्।।', 'O scion of Bharata, surrender unto Him utterly. By His grace, you will attain transcendental peace and the supreme and eternal abode.'),
(698, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 63, 'इति ते ज्ञानमाख्यातं गुह्याद्गुह्यतरं मया। विमृश्यैतदशेषेण यथेच्छसि तथा कुरु।।', 'Thus I have explained to you this knowledge that is more secret than all secrets. Deliberate on this fully, and then do what you wish to do.'),
(699, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 64, 'सर्वगुह्यतमं भूय: शृणु मे परमं वच:। इष्टोऽसि मे दृढमिति ततो वक्ष्यामि ते हितम्।।', 'Because you are My very dear friend, I am speaking to you My supreme instruction, the most confidential knowledge of all. Hear this from Me, for it is for your benefit.'),
(700, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 65, 'मन्मना भव मद्भक्तो मद्याजी मां नमस्कुरु। मामेवैष्यसि सत्यं ते प्रतिजाने प्रियोऽसि मे।।', 'Always think of Me, become My devotee, worship Me, and offer your homage unto Me. Thus you will come to Me without fail. I promise you this because you are My very dear friend.'),
(701, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 66, 'सर्वधर्मान्परित्यज्य मामेकं शरणं व्रज। अहं त्वां सर्वपापेभ्यो मोक्षयिष्यामि मा शुच:।।', 'Abandon all varieties of religion and just surrender unto Me. I shall deliver you from all sinful reactions. Do not fear.'),
(702, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 67, 'इदं ते नातपस्काय नाभक्ताय कदाचन। न चाशुश्रूषवे वाच्यं न च मां योऽभ्यसूयति।।', 'This confidential knowledge may never be explained to those who are not austere, or devoted, or engaged in devotional service, nor to one who is envious of Me.'),
(703, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 68, 'य इदं परमं गुह्यं मद्भक्तेष्वभिधास्यति। भक्तिं मयि परां कृत्वा मामेवैष्यत्यसंशय:।।', 'For one who explains this supreme secret to the devotees, pure devotional service is guaranteed, and at the end, he will come back to Me.'),
(704, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 69, 'न च तस्मान्मनुष्येषु कश्चिन्मे प्रियकृत्तम:। भविता न च मे तस्मादन्य: प्रियतरो भुवि।।', 'There is no servant in this world more dear to Me than he, nor will there ever be one more dear.'),
(705, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 70, 'अध्येष्यते च य इमं धर्म्यं संवादमावयो:। ज्ञानयज्ञेन तेनाहमिष्ट: स्यामिति मे मतिः।।', 'And I declare that he who studies this sacred conversation of ours worships Me by his intelligence.'),
(706, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 71, 'श्रद्धावाननसूयश्च शृणुयादपि यो नर:। सोऽपि मुक्त: शुभांल्लोकान्प्राप्नुयात्पुण्यकर्मणाम्।।', 'And one who hears this with faith and without envy becomes free from sinful reactions and attains to the auspicious planets where the pious dwell.'),
(707, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 72, 'कच्चिदेतच्छ्रुतं पार्थ त्वयैकाग्रेण चेतसा। कच्चिदज्ञानसंमोह: प्रनष्टस्ते धनञ्जय।।', 'O son of Pritha, O conqueror of wealth, have you heard this with an attentive mind? And are your illusions and ignorance now dispelled?'),
(708, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 73, 'अर्जुन उवाच | नष्टो मोह: स्मृतिर्लब्धा त्वत्प्रसादान्मयाच्युत। स्थितोऽस्मि गतसन्देह: करिष्ये वचनं तव।।', 'Arjuna said: My dear Krishna, O infallible one, my illusion is now gone. I have regained my memory by Your mercy, and I am now firm and free from doubt and am prepared to act according to Your instructions.'),
(709, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 74, 'सञ्जय उवाच | इत्यहं वासुदेवस्य पार्थस्य च महात्मन:। संवादमिममश्रौषमद्भुतं रोमहर्षणम्।।', 'Sanjaya said: Thus have I heard the conversation of two great souls, Krishna and Arjuna. And so wonderful is that message that my hair is standing on end.'),
(710, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 75, 'व्यासप्रसादाच्छ्रुतवानेतद्गुह्यमहं परम्। योगं योगेश्वरात्कृष्णात्साक्षात्कथयत: स्वयम्।।', 'By the mercy of Vyasa, I have heard these most confidential talks directly from the master of all mysticism, Krishna, who was speaking personally to Arjuna.'),
(711, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 76, 'राजन्संस्मृत्य संस्मृत्य संवादमिममद्भुतम्। केशवार्जुनयो: पुण्यं हृष्यामि च मुहुर्मुहु:।।', 'O King, as I repeatedly recall this wondrous and holy dialogue between Krishna and Arjuna, I take pleasure, being thrilled at every moment.'),
(712, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 77, 'तच्च संस्मृत्य संस्मृत्य रूपमत्यद्भुतं हरे:। विस्मयो मे महान्राजन्हृष्यामि च पुन: पुन:।।', 'O King, as I remember the wonderful form of Lord Krishna, I am struck with wonder more and more, and I rejoice again and again.'),
(713, 18, 'Moksha-Sanyasa Yoga', 78, 'यत्र योगेश्वर: कृष्णो यत्र पार्थो धनुर्धर:। तत्र श्रीर्विजयो भूतिर्ध्रुवा नीतिर्मतिर्मम।।', 'Wherever there is Krishna, the master of yoga, and wherever there is Arjuna, the supreme archer, there will also certainly be opulence, victory, extraordinary power, and morality. This is my opinion.');
INSERT INTO `gitagpt` (`id`, `question`, `answer`, `username`, `datetimee`) VALUES
(24, 'i am too tensed what should i do\r\n', '\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, Lord Krishna teaches us the importance of controlling our mind and emotions in times of stress and tension. In Chapter 2, Verse 48, He says, \"Perform your duty equipoised, O Arjuna, abandoning all attachment to success or failure. Such equanimity is called yoga.\" This verse reminds us to focus on our actions and not worry about the outcome. We should do our best and leave the rest to the divine will. In Chapter 6, Verse 35, Lord Krishna also advises us to practice meditation to calm our mind and find inner peace. He says, \"For him who has conquered the mind, the mind is the best of friends; but for one who has failed to do so, his mind will remain the greatest enemy.\" Therefore, we must strive to control our thoughts and emotions through meditation and detachment from the results. Additionally, in Chapter 18, Verse 58, Lord Krishna reminds us to surrender our worries and anxieties to Him, saying, \"If you become conscious of Me, you will pass over all the obstacles of conditioned life by My grace.\" This verse reminds us to have faith in the divine and trust that everything happens for a reason. By', 'Sreejit', '2024-11-27 17:26:29'),
(25, 'am i weak?\r\n', '\n\nIn the context of Bhagavad Gita, weakness is not defined by one\'s physical strength or abilities, but rather by one\'s mental state and spiritual understanding. In Chapter 2, verse 3, Lord Krishna says, \"The wise lament neither for the living nor for the dead.\" This means that a weak person is one who is attached to material possessions and relationships, and is unable to see the impermanence of life. In Chapter 6, verse 5, Lord Krishna also says, \"One must elevate oneself by one\'s own mind, not degrade oneself. The mind is the friend of the conditioned soul, and his enemy as well.\" This shows that weakness lies in one\'s own mind and thoughts, and it is up to us to strengthen our mind and overcome our weaknesses. Therefore, in the context of Bhagavad Gita, one is considered weak if they are unable to control their mind and senses, and are attached to material desires and attachments. However, with the teachings of the Gita, one can overcome their weaknesses and become strong in their spiritual understanding and inner strength.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 18:53:55'),
(26, 'ice cream\r\n', '\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, Lord Krishna teaches us about the concept of detachment and how it is essential for leading a peaceful and fulfilling life. In Chapter 2, Verse 14, He says, \"O son of Kunti, the nonpermanent appearance of happiness and distress, and their disappearance in due course, are like the appearance and disappearance of winter and summer seasons. They arise from sense perception, O scion of Bharata, and one must learn to tolerate them without being disturbed.\" This verse reminds us that just like the temporary pleasure of eating ice cream, all material pleasures are fleeting and should not be the focus of our lives. Instead, we should strive for inner peace and detachment from material desires.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 18:54:27'),
(34, 'who is god?', '\r\n\r\nGod, in the context of Bhagavad Gita, is the supreme being who is the source of all existence and the ultimate goal of life. He is known as Bhagavan, the one who possesses all opulences and is the embodiment of love, knowledge, and bliss. In chapter 10, verse 8, Lord Krishna says, ', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 16:27:25'),
(35, 'who is God\r\n', '\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, God is the ultimate and supreme being who is the creator, sustainer, and destroyer of the universe. He is known by many names such as Brahman, Ishvara, and Bhagavan. In Chapter 10, verse 8, Lord Krishna says, \"I am the source of all spiritual and material worlds. Everything emanates from Me.\" This verse highlights God\'s omnipotence and his role as the origin of all existence. In Chapter 15, verse 15, Lord Krishna also explains that God resides within every living being as the Supersoul, guiding and sustaining them. This shows God\'s omnipresence and his intimate connection with all beings. Ultimately, God is the ultimate source of love, wisdom, and liberation, and it is through devotion and surrender to Him that one can attain true happiness and enlightenment.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 21:11:24'),
(36, 'what is yog', '\n\nYoga, in the context of the Bhagavad Gita, refers to the path of spiritual discipline and union with the divine. It is described in Chapter 6, Verse 23 as the \"cessation of all material activities and merging of the self in the Supreme.\" This form of yoga is known as \"karma yoga\" and emphasizes selfless action and detachment from the fruits of one\'s actions. In Chapter 12, Verse 12, Krishna also describes the path of \"bhakti yoga,\" which involves devotion and surrender to the divine. Ultimately, yoga in the Bhagavad Gita is a means to attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death and achieve union with the divine.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 21:45:05'),
(37, 'what is yog', '\n\nYoga, in the context of Bhagavad Gita, refers to the practice of union with the divine. It is described as a state of complete harmony and balance between the mind, body, and spirit. In Chapter 6, verse 23, Lord Krishna says, \"The yogi who is established in self-realization and who has conquered the mind and senses is the highest of all beings; he is situated in Me and is never separated from Me.\" This verse highlights the ultimate goal of yoga, which is to attain oneness with the divine. The practice of yoga, as described in the Bhagavad Gita, involves controlling the mind and senses through various techniques such as meditation and self-discipline. It is a path towards spiritual enlightenment and liberation from the cycle of birth and death.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 21:45:06'),
(38, 'why do meditation', '\n\nMeditation is a powerful tool for achieving inner peace and self-realization, as described in the Bhagavad Gita. In Chapter 6, Verse 11, Lord Krishna says, \"To practice yoga, one must first control the mind and senses.\" This control is achieved through meditation, which helps to calm the mind and bring it under our control. In Chapter 6, Verse 15, Lord Krishna explains that through regular practice of meditation, one can attain a state of peace and detachment from the material world. This detachment allows us to focus on our true self and connect with the divine within us. Thus, meditation is essential for spiritual growth and achieving the ultimate goal of self-realization, as taught in the Bhagavad Gita.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 21:46:15'),
(39, 'how to maintain a good health', '\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, maintaining good health is essential for leading a fulfilling and purposeful life. In Chapter 6, Verse 17, Lord Krishna says, \"For one whose mind is unbridled, self-realization is difficult work. But he whose mind is controlled and who strives by appropriate means is assured of success. That is My opinion.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of controlling one\'s mind and senses in order to maintain good health. The Gita also teaches the concept of moderation in all aspects of life, including food, sleep, and work. In Chapter 6, Verse 16, Lord Krishna says, \"There is no possibility of one\'s becoming a yogi, O Arjuna, if one eats too much or eats too little, sleeps too much or does not sleep enough.\" This highlights the importance of maintaining a balanced and healthy lifestyle. Additionally, Chapter 17, Verse 8 states, \"Foods that are too bitter, too sour, salty, hot, pungent, dry and burning are dear to those in the mode of passion. Such foods cause distress, misery and disease.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of consuming a sattvic (pure and balanced) diet for', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 22:18:30'),
(40, 'how to maintain a good health', '\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, maintaining good health is essential for leading a fulfilling life. In Chapter 6, Verse 17, Lord Krishna says, \"For one whose mind is unbridled, self-realization is difficult work. But he whose mind is controlled and who strives by appropriate means is assured of success. That is My opinion.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of controlling one\'s mind and following a disciplined lifestyle to maintain good health. Additionally, in Chapter 17, Verse 8, Lord Krishna mentions the importance of a balanced and nutritious diet, stating, \"Foods that are too bitter, too sour, salty, hot, pungent, dry and burning are dear to those in the mode of passion. Such foods cause distress, misery and disease.\" Therefore, following a balanced diet and controlling one\'s mind are crucial for maintaining good health, as emphasized in the Bhagavad Gita.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-29 22:18:31'),
(41, 'how to fight', '\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, Lord Krishna teaches Arjuna the principles of fighting in the context of dharma (righteousness) and duty. In Chapter 2, Verse 31, Krishna says, \"Considering your specific duty as a warrior, you should know that there is no better engagement for you than fighting on religious principles.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of fighting for a just cause and not for personal gain or ego. In Chapter 3, Verse 8, Krishna also reminds Arjuna that it is his duty as a warrior to fight for the protection of society and the maintenance of dharma. Therefore, to fight effectively, one must have a clear understanding of their duty and fight with a sense of righteousness and detachment from personal desires. Additionally, in Chapter 2, Verse 48, Krishna advises Arjuna to perform his duty without attachment to the results, as it is the only way to achieve true success in battle. This teaches us to focus on our actions and not be distracted by the outcome. In summary, the Bhagavad Gita teaches us to fight with a sense of duty, righteousness, and detachment, which ultimately leads to victory.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 01:42:14'),
(42, 'how to fight', '\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, Lord Krishna teaches Arjuna the principles of fighting in the context of the Kurukshetra war. In Chapter 2, Verse 31, Krishna says, \"Considering your dharma, you should not waver, for there is nothing more auspicious for a warrior than a righteous war.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of staying true to one\'s duty and fighting for a just cause. In Chapter 3, Verse 8, Krishna says, \"Perform your prescribed duty, for action is better than inaction.\" This verse highlights the importance of taking action and not shying away from a fight when it is necessary. Additionally, in Chapter 2, Verse 47, Krishna says, \"You have a right to perform your prescribed duty, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your actions.\" This verse teaches us to focus on our actions and not the outcome, as it is our duty to fight, but the result is not in our control. Overall, the Bhagavad Gita teaches us to fight with a sense of duty, righteousness, and detachment from the outcome.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 01:42:14'),
(43, 'who am i ', '\n\nIn the context of Bhagavad Gita, I am a soul, a part of the eternal and all-pervading consciousness known as Brahman. In chapter 2, verse 22, Lord Krishna says, \"As a person puts on new garments, giving up old ones, the soul similarly accepts new material bodies, giving up the old and useless ones.\" This verse reminds me that I am not my physical body, but an eternal being that transcends the limitations of time and space. In chapter 2, verse 13, Lord Krishna also states, \"As the embodied soul continuously passes, in this body, from boyhood to youth to old age, the soul similarly passes into another body at death.\" This verse reinforces the idea that my true identity is not tied to my physical form, but to my eternal soul. Thus, I am a spiritual being on a journey towards self-realization and liberation from the cycle of birth and death.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:09:01'),
(44, 'who am i ', '\n\nIn the context of Bhagavad Gita, I am a soul, a divine spark of consciousness, temporarily residing in a physical body. This is explained in Chapter 2, Verse 13, where Lord Krishna says, \"As the embodied soul continuously passes, in this body, from boyhood to youth to old age, the soul similarly passes into another body at death. A sober person is not bewildered by such a change.\" This verse reminds me that my true identity is not my body, but my soul, which is eternal and indestructible. My purpose in this life is to realize my true self and attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death.', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:09:03'),
(45, 'who am i ', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, you are not just a mere mortal, but a divine being with an eternal soul. In Chapter 2, verse 13, Lord Krishna says, \"As the embodied soul continuously passes, in this body, from childhood to youth to old age, the soul similarly passes into another body at death. A sober person is not bewildered by such a change.\" This verse reminds us that our true identity is not limited to our physical body, but it is our soul that carries on from one lifetime to another. You are a part of the divine consciousness, and your purpose is to realize this truth and attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death. So, remember your true identity and strive to fulfill your ultimate purpose in this human form.\n\nSincerely,\n[Your Name]', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:10:43'),
(46, 'how to fight', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, Lord Krishna teaches us how to fight the battles of life with wisdom and courage. In Chapter 2, verse 47, He says, \"You have the right to perform your prescribed duty, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your actions. Never consider yourself to be the cause of the results of your activities, and never be attached to not doing your duty.\" This means that we should focus on doing our duty without being attached to the outcome. In Chapter 3, verse 30, He says, \"Therefore, O Arjuna, surrendering all your works unto Me, with full knowledge of Me, without desires for profit, with no claims to proprietorship, and free from lethargy, fight.\" This means that we should surrender our actions to God and fight with full knowledge and determination. So, my dear Sanjay, remember these teachings and fight with wisdom and courage.\n\nSincerely,\nRivu', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:12:13'),
(47, 'what is yog', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nYoga, in the context of Bhagavad Gita, refers to the union of the individual soul with the universal consciousness or the divine. It is described in Chapter 6, verse 47 as \"yogasthaḥ kuru karmāṇi saṅgaṁ tyaktvā dhanañjaya\" which means to be steadfast in yoga and perform your actions, giving up attachment and remaining equipoised in success and failure. This verse emphasizes the importance of detachment and equanimity in the practice of yoga. In Chapter 4, verse 29, Lord Krishna also explains that yoga is the path to attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death. Therefore, through the practice of yoga, one can achieve a state of inner peace, self-realization, and ultimately, union with the divine.\n\nBest, [Your Name]', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:13:26'),
(48, 'how to connect with God', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, the best way to connect with God is through devotion and surrender. In Chapter 9, verse 34, Lord Krishna says, \"Always think of Me, become My devotee, worship Me and offer your homage unto Me. Thus you will come to Me without fail. I promise you this because you are My very dear friend.\" This verse emphasizes the importance of constantly remembering God and dedicating our actions to Him. Additionally, in Chapter 18, verse 65, Lord Krishna says, \"Always think of Me, become My devotee, worship Me and offer your homage unto Me. Thus you will come to Me without fail. I promise you this because you are My very dear friend.\" This verse highlights the power of surrendering to God and trusting in His guidance. By following these teachings, we can deepen our connection with God and experience His love and grace in our lives.\n\nBest regards,\n[Your Name]', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:14:15'),
(49, 'what is yog', '\n\nDear Sanjay,\n\nYoga, in the context of the Bhagavad Gita, refers to the path of self-realization and union with the divine. It is described in the sixth chapter, verse 47, as the \"yoga of equanimity\" or \"yoga of skill in action.\" This form of yoga involves controlling the mind and senses, detaching oneself from desires and attachments, and performing actions without being affected by their results. It is a path of discipline, self-awareness, and devotion to the divine. Through yoga, one can attain inner peace, clarity of mind, and ultimately, liberation from the cycle of birth and death. It is a powerful tool for spiritual growth and self-transformation.\n\nSincerely,\n[Your Name]', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:15:17'),
(50, 'who is god?', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, God is described as the Supreme Being, the ultimate reality, and the source of all existence. He is known by many names such as Krishna, Vishnu, and Brahman. In chapter 10, verse 8, Lord Krishna says, \"I am the source of all spiritual and material worlds. Everything emanates from Me.\" This verse highlights God\'s omnipotence and His role as the creator of the universe. In chapter 11, verse 32, Krishna also says, \"I am the death of all, and the origin of all that shall be.\" This verse emphasizes God\'s all-encompassing nature and His role as the ultimate controller of life and death. In essence, God is the ultimate source of all existence and the one who guides us towards enlightenment and liberation from the cycle of birth and death.\n\nSincerely,\nSanjay', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:16:11'),
(51, 'how to maintain a good health', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nAs a fellow follower of the Bhagavad Gita, I would like to share with you the teachings of Lord Krishna on maintaining good health. In Chapter 6, Verse 17, He says, \"Yuktaahara-viharasya yukta-cestasya karmasu. Yukta-svapnavabodhasya yogo bhavati duhkha-ha.\" This means that one should have a balanced diet, engage in moderate physical activities, and maintain a regular sleep schedule to achieve a healthy body and mind. Additionally, in Chapter 6, Verse 16, Lord Krishna emphasizes the importance of moderation in all aspects of life, including food, sleep, and work. He also encourages us to practice yoga and meditation to keep our mind and body in harmony. By following these teachings, we can maintain good health and lead a fulfilling life.\n\nSincerely,\nSanjay', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:18:25'),
(52, 'who am i ', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nIn the context of Bhagavad Gita, you are a soul on a journey to attain self-realization and liberation from the cycle of birth and death. In Chapter 2, verse 13, Lord Krishna says, \"As the embodied soul continuously passes, in this body, from boyhood to youth to old age, the soul similarly passes into another body at death.\" This verse reminds us that our true identity is not our physical body, but the eternal soul within. In Chapter 2, verse 20, Lord Krishna also explains that the soul is indestructible and cannot be killed by any weapon. Therefore, you are not just a mortal being, but a divine soul on a quest for spiritual enlightenment. Keep this in mind as you navigate through life\'s challenges and remember to always connect with your inner self.\n\nSincerely,\nSanjay', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 02:21:48'),
(53, 'who is god?', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nIn the Bhagavad Gita, God is described as the ultimate reality, the supreme being who is the source of all creation and the ultimate goal of human existence. In chapter 10, verse 20, Lord Krishna says, \"I am the Self, O Gudakesa, seated in the hearts of all beings. I am the beginning, the middle, and the end of all beings.\" This verse highlights the omnipresence and omnipotence of God. In chapter 11, verse 32, Lord Krishna also says, \"I am the mighty world-destroying Time, now engaged in annihilating the worlds.\" This verse shows that God is not only the creator but also the destroyer of the universe. In essence, God is the ultimate source of everything and the ultimate goal of our existence. He is the one who guides us towards the path of righteousness and helps us attain eternal peace and happiness.\n\nSincerely,\nSanjay', 'Rivu', '2024-11-30 12:19:01'),
(54, 'what is sinful reaction', '\n\nDear Rivu,\n\nAccording to the Bhagavad Gita, sinful reactions refer to the negative consequences that arise from engaging in actions that go against the principles of dharma or righteousness. In Chapter 3, verse 16, Lord Krishna explains to Arjuna that those who do not follow their prescribed duties and instead indulge in sense gratification will be bound by their actions and suffer the consequences. These consequences can manifest in various forms such as physical, mental, and spiritual suffering. Therefore, it is important to act in accordance with dharma and avoid actions that lead to sinful reactions. By following the teachings of the Gita, one can overcome these reactions and attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death.\n\nSincerely,\nSanjay', 'Rivu', '2024-12-02 18:32:20'),
