(63, 'who am i ', '\n\nDear Sreejit,\n\nAs Sanjay, I am here to answer your question on who you are in the context of Bhagavad Gita. In Chapter 2, Verse 13, Lord Krishna says, \"As the embodied soul continuously passes, in this body, from boyhood to youth to old age, the soul similarly passes into another body at death. A sober person is not bewildered by such a change.\" This verse reminds us that we are not just our physical bodies, but eternal souls on a journey through different bodies in this material world. In Chapter 2, Verse 20, Lord Krishna also says, \"For the soul there is neither birth nor death at any time. He has not come into being, does not come into being, and will not come into being. He is unborn, eternal, ever-existing and primeval. He is not slain when the body is slain.\" This verse further emphasizes that our true identity is not limited to our current body, but is eternal and unchanging. So, in the context of Bhagavad Gita, you are an eternal soul on a journey through different bodies, ultimately seeking liberation from the cycle of birth and death. ', 'Sreejit', '2025-04-11 19:31:35'),
(64, 'My final exams are near I am verystressed out, what to do?', '\n\nDear Shobhit,\n\nI understand that your final exams are near and you are feeling stressed out. This is a common feeling among students, especially during important exams. However, I would like to remind you of the teachings of Bhagavad Gita, specifically in Chapter 2, Verse 48 where Lord Krishna says, \"Yogastha kuru karmani\" which means, \"Be steadfast in yoga, O Arjuna. Perform your duty and abandon all attachment to success or failure. Such evenness of mind is called yoga.\"\n\nThis verse reminds us to focus on our actions and duties, rather than the outcome. It is important to put in your best effort and leave the rest to the divine. Remember, your hard work and dedication will not go to waste. Trust in the process and have faith in yourself. Also, in Chapter 6, Verse 35, Lord Krishna says, \"Asamshayam mahabaho mano durnigraham chalam abhyasena tu kaunteya vairagyena cha grhyate\" which means, \"It is undoubtedly difficult to curb the restless mind, but it is possible by constant practice and detachment.\"\n\nThis verse teaches us the importance of practice and detachment', 'Shobhit', '2025-04-16 13:31:37');
